1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 { This is going to be a repertoire for Black with the Queen's Gambit Accepted variation, and in this chapter, the rare 3rd moves will be analyzed. } 3. Qa4+ { If White decides so to give this check, it's better to include the moves 3.Nf3 Nf6, when 4.Qa4+ would lead to a better version for White. } ( 3. Na3 $2 e5 $1 { A typical pawn push! Black intends to capture the knight on a3 now. } 4. dxe5 { After 4.Nxc4, Black can simply win the d4-pawn with 4...exd4. } ( 4. e3 Be6 $5 { Trying to defend the c4-pawn temporarily. } ( { A good alternative is: } 4... Bxa3 5. bxa3 ( 5. Qa4+ b5 { After 6. Qxb5+ c6 7. Qxe5+ Be7, Black has an extra piece and a winning position. } 6. Qxa3 exd4 $17 { White doesn't have compensation for the material deficit. } ) 5... b5 $17 ) 5. Nxc4 { 5.Bxc4 Bxa3 6.Bxe6 runs into 6...Bb4+, when Black is a piece up. } 5... exd4 6. exd4 Qe7 $1 { [%csl Re1] A very unpleasant move for White to face. It's not easy to deal with the discovered attack on the e-file since 7.Be3 runs into 7...Bxc4 8.Bxc4 Qb4+, winning the bishop on c4. } 7. Ne3 Nc6 $17 { [%cal Ge8c8] } ) 4... Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 Bxa3 6. bxa3 Nd7 ( 6... b5 $17 { Black has the better pawn structure and an example continuation can be 7.e3 Nd7 8.f4 Nc5, when Black can continue with Bb7 and 0-0-0, with a quick development. } ) 7. Nf3 Nc5 $17 ) ( 3. a4 $2 e5 $1 4. dxe5 ( 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bc5 6. e3 Bxd4 7. exd4 Be6 8. Nc3 Ne7 $17 { [%cal Gb8c6] If White plays Bg5, Black can play f6 first and then continue with Nbc6. } ) 4... Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 Nc6 6. Nf3 Be6 $17 { [%cal Ge8c8] } ) ( 3. Bf4 $6 { The bishop doesn't belong on this square and White spent a tempo for it. } 3... Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 { Intending b7-b5. } ( 4... c6 $5 { Is also possible. } ) 5. e3 ( 5. e4 $6 b5 { Black is simply a pawn-up. } ) 5... b5 6. a4 b4 7. Nb1 Be6 8. Nf3 c5 $13 { Black can continue with Nc6 and g6 with Bg7, when White should be careful not to land in a worse position. } ) ( 3. Nc3 Nf6 { Black also has other options such as: } ( 3... e5 ) ( 3... a6 ) 4. e3 ( 4. e4 $6 e5 $1 { With a better version for Black from the 3...e5 line, and after 5.dxe5 Qxd1+, recapturing with the knight drops the e4-pawn, while 6.Kxd1 Ng4 is a double attack on f2 and e5, so Black will regain the pawn. } ) 4... e6 5. Bxc4 c5 { Will transpose to the main lines. } ) 3... Nd7 $5 ( 3... Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 { Transposes to 4.Qa4+. } ) ( 3... c6 $5 4. Qxc4 Nd7 { Is similar to the analysis below. } ) 4. Nf3 ( 4. Qxc4 e5 $13 ) 4... c6 $5 ( 4... a6 { This is also an interesting possibility for Black, intending b7-b5 next. } 5. Qxc4 ( 5. Nc3 { Preventing b5 due to Nxb5. } 5... Rb8 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qd3 Bb7 $11 { With a typical position, intending moves like e7-e6 and c7-c5 next. } ) 5... e6 { [%cal Gb7b5] } ) 5. Qxc4 e5 6. dxe5 ( 6. Nc3 exd4 7. Nxd4 Ngf6 $13 { White spent too much time trying to regain the pawn on c4, and additionally, Black can gain another tempo with Ne5 at some point, so Black is doing well. } ) ( 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. dxe5 Qa5+ { Transposes below. } ) 6... Nxe5 7. Nxe5 ( 7. Qe4 Bd6 8. Nxe5 Qa5+ 9. Nd2 Qxe5 10. Qxe5+ Bxe5 11. e4 Bc7 $11 { [%cal Gg8e7,Gc8e6] } ) 7... Qa5+ 8. Nc3 Qxe5 { Black has already equalized and intends to continue developing with moves like Nf6 and Be6. } 9. g3 ( 9. Bf4 Qa5 { [%cal Gc8e6] } ) 9... Be6 10. Qa4 ( 10. Qf4 Qxf4 { Black is also fine in the endgame. } 11. Bxf4 Nf6 12. Bg2 O-O-O $11 ) 10... Bc5 { Black's idea is to meet 11.Bf4 with 11...Qd4. } ( 10... Nf6 { Is also possible. } 11. Bf4 Qc5 12. Bg2 Be7 13. O-O O-O 14. Rac1 Qb6 $11 ) 11. Bg2 Nf6 12. Bf4 Qd4 13. O-O Qxa4 14. Nxa4 Be7 15. Be3 Nd7 { Preventing Nc5. } 16. Rfd1 f5 $11 { [%cal Ge8f7,Gh8d8] Black intends to continue with Kf7 and Rhd8, with a solid position. } *

