1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 { In this chapter, White's rare options on move 4 will be analyzed. } 4. g3 { White is aiming for a Catalan-type of position. } ( 4. e4 $6 Nxe4 5. Bxc4 g6 ( 5... e6 { This is also possible, although White may have some compensation for the pawn after 0-0 and Re1. } ) ( 5... Nd6 { Is similar. } ) 6. O-O Nd6 7. Bb3 Bg7 8. h3 ( 8. Re1 Bg4 $1 { The pin is quite unpleasant for White and soon, Nc6 is coming when the d4-pawn will be under some pressure. } 9. Bg5 Nc6 $17 { [%csl Rd4] 10.d5 can be met with 10...Ne5. } ) 8... O-O 9. Re1 Nc6 $15 { [%cal Gd6f5] 10.d5 doesn't accomplish much for White after 10...Na5. } ) ( 4. Qc2 b5 ( { Another possibility is: } 4... e6 $5 5. e3 ( 5. Qxc4 a6 { [%cal Gb7b5] } ) 5... c5 { With a version of the Queen's Gambit Accepted where the queen doesn't belong on the c2-square. } ) 5. a4 ( 5. e4 Bb7 6. Nc3 a6 $15 { White always needs to be careful of b5-b4 which can win the pawn on e4 at an appropriate moment, for example, 7.a4 is met with 7...b4. } ) 5... c6 6. Nc3 ( 6. g3 Bb7 7. Bg2 e6 8. O-O Be7 $13 { This position is similar to the ones arising from the Catalan, when White usually plays b3 and recaptures on b3 with the queen, which would lead to a loss of tempo in this case due to the move Qc2. } ) ( 6. axb5 cxb5 7. Nc3 Bd7 8. g3 e6 9. Bg2 Nc6 10. O-O { After 10.Nxb5 Nb4 11.Qxc4 Rc8, there are too many threats and the White position falls apart. } 10... Nb4 11. Qb1 a5 12. Ne5 Ra6 $13 { [%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black has a pleasant position. } ) 6... b4 { Defending the pawn with Bd7 looks passive in this case. } 7. Ne4 ( 7. Nb1 $6 Ba6 8. e3 b3 9. Qd1 e6 10. Be2 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 c5 $15 ) 7... b3 $5 { I prefer to give the pawn back immediately. } ( 7... Nxe4 { This is another possibility for Black, keeping the extra pawn, although White will have some activity to show for it. } 8. Qxe4 e6 9. g3 a5 10. Bg2 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Ne5 Ba6 $13 ) 8. Nxf6+ exf6 9. Qxc4 Be6 10. Qc3 a5 11. Bd2 Bb4 12. Qc1 Na6 { Black has a nice lead in development, so capturing the pawn on c6 will be too dangerous for White. } 13. e3 Bxd2+ 14. Qxd2 Nb4 15. Bd3 O-O 16. Rc1 Qb6 17. O-O Rfd8 18. Be2 ( 18. Be4 Rac8 { With c6-c5 to follow. } ) 18... Na2 19. Rc5 Rd5 $11 ) ( 4. Na3 $6 e5 $1 { Employing the same antidote to this line as in 3.Na3. } 5. Nxe5 ( 5. dxe5 $2 Qxd1+ 6. Kxd1 Ne4 $17 ) 5... Bxa3 ( 5... Bb4+ $5 { Provoking Bd2 so that the pawn on d4 is hanging after Bxa3 is also a playable idea for Black. } 6. Bd2 Bxa3 7. Qa4+ b5 8. Qxa3 Qxd4 9. Nf3 Qb6 10. Ba5 Qa6 11. Bxc7 Qxa3 12. bxa3 Nc6 $15 ) 6. bxa3 b5 7. e3 O-O 8. Be2 Nd5 $15 { Black can continue with Nc3 or Bb7 next. } ) 4... Nc6 $5 { [%cal Ge7e5] The move c6 hasn't been played yet, so this is a good way to make use of that. } ( { Another good option for Black is: } 4... c5 5. Qa4+ Qd7 6. Qxc4 cxd4 7. Qxd4 Nc6 8. Qxd7+ Bxd7 $11 ) 5. Nc3 ( 5. Bg2 $6 e5 $15 ) ( 5. Qa4 $6 Nd7 $1 { Intending Nb6 and e7-e5. } 6. Qxc4 Nb6 { [%csl Rd4] } 7. Qd3 { White has to stay close to the d4-pawn. 7.Qc3 runs into 7...e5, threatening Bb4. } 7... e5 $1 8. Nxe5 ( 8. dxe5 $6 Qxd3 9. exd3 Bb4+ 10. Bd2 Bg4 $17 { 0-0-0 is coming and Black has a fantastic activity. } ) 8... Nb4 9. Qd2 Qxd4 10. Qxd4 Nc2+ 11. Kd2 Nxd4 12. e3 Ne6 $15 { White's king is a bit exposed on the d2-square. } ) 5... e5 $1 { Black didn't spend a tempo on e7-e6, so it makes sense to play this move directly. } ( 5... e6 6. Bg2 Bb4 7. O-O O-O { Transposes to a variation from the Catalan opening. } ) 6. Nxe5 ( 6. dxe5 $6 Qxd1+ 7. Nxd1 Nb4 $15 ) ( 6. d5 $6 Nb4 $15 ) 6... Nxe5 ( 6... Qxd4 { Is also possible for Black. } 7. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 8. Nxd1 bxc6 9. Bg2 Nd5 $11 { Although Black's pawn structure is compromised, Black is a pawn-up. Having the open b-file and with moves like Rb8, Bb4 and Be6 coming, Black has sufficient activity in the position. } ) 7. dxe5 Qxd1+ 8. Nxd1 { 8.Kxd1 Ng4 is good for Black. } 8... Ne4 9. Bg2 ( 9. a3 $6 Nc5 $15 { Intending Nb3 and Bf5 next. } ) 9... Bb4+ 10. Kf1 Nd2+ 11. Kg1 { White doesn't like to surrender the bishop pair to the opponent, so this is the best continuation. } 11... O-O 12. Nc3 ( 12. Ne3 Rd8 13. Nd5 { Leads to the same position. } ) 12... Rd8 13. Nd5 { A lot of pieces are hanging now but Black has an amazing resource that saves the day: } 13... Bh3 $1 14. Bxd2 { 14.Nxb4 Nf3+ leads to checkmate. } ( 14. e4 Be6 15. h4 ( 15. Nxb4 $2 Nb3 $17 { Hits the rook on a1 and threatens Rd1+ with Bh3. } ) 15... Ba5 16. Bxd2 Bxd2 17. Nxc7 Rac8 18. Nd5 c3 19. bxc3 Bxd5 ( 19... Bxc3 { Is similar. } ) 20. exd5 Bxc3 21. Rb1 Bxe5 22. Rxb7 Rc2 $11 { Black has a lot of activity. } ) ( 14. Bxh3 $6 Rxd5 $15 ) 14... Bxd2 15. Nxc7 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Rac8 17. Nb5 Rc5 18. a4 Rxe5 $11 { After the dust has settled, an equal endgame has been reached. } *

