1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qa4+ Nc6 $1 { Black keeps the option of playing e7-e5 at some point. } ( 4... c6 5. Qxc4 { Leads to the Slav defence. } ) 5. Qxc4 ( 5. Nbd2 a6 $1 { [%cal Gb7b5] } 6. Qxc4 Be6 7. Qd3 ( 7. Qc5 Bd5 $15 { [%cal Ge7e5] } ) 7... Qd7 { Creating the possibility of castling long. } 8. e3 ( 8. e4 O-O-O $1 { Sacrificing a piece! } 9. d5 Nxd5 10. exd5 Bxd5 11. Be2 e5 12. O-O f5 $15 { [%csl Ge5,Gf5][%cal Ge5e4] Black has two pawns and activity to compensate for the missing piece, but in addition, White's pieces are passive, so Black is already better. } ) 8... g5 $1 { A very promising idea, intending g5-g4. } ( 8... O-O-O { Is also possible. } ) 9. Nb3 ( 9. Nxg5 Nb4 10. Qb1 ( 10. Qc3 Nfd5 $17 ) 10... Bf5 11. e4 Bg6 $15 { [%csl Rd4] The pawn on d4 will fall soon. } ) 9... g4 10. Nc5 Qd5 11. Nxe6 Qxe6 { Black is already ahead with the development. } 12. Nh4 ( 12. Nd2 O-O-O 13. Nb3 Kb8 $15 ) 12... Nb4 13. Qd2 a5 14. a3 Ne4 15. Bb5+ c6 16. Qe2 Nc2+ 17. Qxc2 cxb5 $15 { Black's pieces are very well placed. } ) ( 5. g3 $6 Nd7 $1 { [%cal Gd7b6] Transposes to the previous lesson. } ) ( 5. e3 $5 { This move was played by Magnus Carlsen. } 5... Nd7 $1 { [%cal Gd7b6,Ge7e5] We can see this move once again, intending e5 and Nb6. } 6. Bxc4 ( 6. Qxc4 e5 7. Qc2 Bd6 8. Nc3 O-O $13 ) ( 6. Qc2 e5 7. Bxc4 Bd6 8. O-O O-O $11 { Black can continue with moves like Qe7 and Nb6, with a solid position in the center. } ) 6... Nb6 7. Qb3 Nxc4 8. Qxc4 Be6 9. Qe2 ( 9. Qc2 Bg4 10. Nc3 e6 $11 ) ( 9. Qb5 a6 10. Qxb7 $2 Bd5 $19 { [%csl Rb7][%cal Ga8a7] } ) ( 9. Qa4 Bd7 $5 { I prefer to keep the bishop pair. } ( 9... Bd5 { Is also possible for Black. } 10. Nc3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 e6 12. Qb5 Rb8 $11 ) 10. Nc3 e6 11. Qd1 Bd6 $11 { [%cal Ge8g8] } ) 9... Bg4 { [%cal Ge7e6] The simplest continuation for Black. } ( 9... Qd5 10. Nbd2 f5 11. O-O O-O-O $13 { 1/2 (47) Carlsen,M (2839) -Vachier Lagrave,M (2727) Durres 2023 } ) 10. h3 ( 10. Nc3 e6 { Doesn't change much. } ) 10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 e6 12. Nc3 Qd7 { [%cal Ge8c8] } 13. O-O O-O-O 14. Rd1 { White's idea can be to expand on the queenside sooner or later, so Black should be quick on the other flank. } 14... Rg8 $5 { [%cal Gg7g5] } 15. d5 ( 15. a3 $6 g5 16. b4 f5 $15 { [%cal Gg5g4] Black arrives first on the kingside. } ) ( 15. b3 Bd6 16. Bb2 f5 { [%cal Gg7g5] } 17. Rac1 g5 $13 ) 15... exd5 16. Nxd5 ( 16. Rxd5 Bd6 { Black is fine. } ) 16... Bd6 17. Bd2 ( 17. e4 Qe6 { Black doesn't have any problems in the position. } ) 17... Ne5 18. Qh5 f5 19. Bc3 Qf7 20. Qxf7 Nxf7 21. Rac1 c6 $11 ) ( 5. Nc3 Nd5 $1 { Intending Nb6. } 6. Ne5 ( 6. e4 Nb6 7. Qd1 f5 $5 { Undermining White's control over the d5-square. } ( 7... Bg4 $13 ) 8. d5 { 8.exf5 Bxf5 leaves Black a pawn-up and a pleasant position, when Black can follow-up with Qd7 and 0-0-0 next. } 8... fxe4 9. Ng5 Nb4 10. Bxc4 e6 $1 ( 10... Nxc4 $6 11. Qa4+ { This is in White's favor. } ) 11. Bb5+ c6 12. dxc6 Qxd1+ 13. Kxd1 bxc6 14. Be2 Be7 { This endgame is already slightly more pleasant for Black. } 15. a3 N4d5 16. Ncxe4 O-O $15 { [%csl Rd1][%cal Ge6e5] White's king on d1 is a bit exposed while e5 is coming and the knight on d5 is very well placed. } ) ( 6. Qxc4 Ndb4 $1 7. Qb3 Be6 ( 7... e5 $5 { Black can try to continue the game with this move. } ) 8. Qa4 { White must repeat the moves, otherwise Black will be doing very well. } 8... Bd7 $11 ) 6... Nb6 ( { A good alternative is: } 6... Bd7 $14 7. Qxc4 { If White included the moves Nxd7 and Qxd7, now Nb6 would have won the d4-pawn. } 7... Nxe5 8. Qxd5 ( 8. dxe5 $6 e6 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. Qxd5 Qh4 $15 { Black has very good activity and can follow up with moves like Bc6 or 0-0-0 and Bb4, while White still hasn't developed yet. } ) 8... Nc6 9. Bf4 ( 9. e4 e6 10. Qc4 e5 $11 { After 11.d5 Nb4, Black is doing well. } ) 9... e6 10. Qc4 ( 10. Qe4 g5 $1 11. Bd2 f5 12. Qe3 Bg7 13. Qxg5 Qxg5 14. Bxg5 Nxd4 15. O-O-O h6 $13 { Black's dark-squared bishop and knight on d4 are very strong, so White needs to be a bit careful. } ) 10... Bd6 $11 ) 7. Nxc6 Qd6 8. Qa5 Qxc6 9. e4 e6 10. Be2 ( 10. Be3 Be7 11. O-O-O O-O 12. h4 Qd6 $13 { [%cal Gd6b4] } ) 10... Be7 11. O-O { White has some compensation for the pawn, but on the other hand, Black isn't worse. } 11... O-O 12. Be3 ( 12. a4 f5 $13 ) 12... f5 $1 { We see this typical idea once again. } 13. d5 ( 13. Bf3 Qe8 { Simply stepping away from the scope of the bishop on f3. } ) 13... exd5 14. exd5 Qg6 $13 { The position is very promising for Black who can follow up with f5-f4 or Bd6 next. } ) ( 5. Ne5 $6 Qxd4 6. Nxc6 Qd7 $15 ) 5... e5 $1 6. Nxe5 ( 6. dxe5 { Capturing with the knight on e5 is a bit better for White since now Black can gain a strong initiative. } 6... Be6 7. Qh4 ( 7. Qa4 Nd7 { [%cal Gd7c5] } 8. Bd2 Nc5 9. Qc2 Qd7 { [%cal Ge6f5] } 10. b4 Bf5 11. Qb2 Ne6 { White should be extremely careful in this line. } 12. Bc3 a5 $1 13. bxa5 O-O-O 14. Nbd2 Ncd4 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Qxd4 17. Qxd4 Rxd4 18. e3 Ra4 $15 { Black has the bishop pair and White's weak pawns should fall, so Black has a very promising position. } ) 7... Bb4+ { This check seems to be the most ambitious continuation. } ( 7... Nb4 8. Na3 { Is also a possible continuation. } ) ( { A viable alternative is: } 7... Nd7 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Qxe7+ Kxe7 $11 ) 8. Bd2 Ng4 9. Qxd8+ Rxd8 $11 ) 6... Nxe5 7. dxe5 Ng4 8. Bf4 ( 8. Nc3 c6 { Covering the d5-square. } ( 8... Nxe5 $2 9. Qe4 Qe7 10. Nd5 $18 { This move is the difference between 8.Nc3 and 8.Bd2. } ) 9. Qe4 ( 9. Qf4 Qa5 10. g3 Be7 11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O Nxe5 $11 ) 9... Bc5 10. e3 Qe7 11. f4 h5 $14 ( 11... O-O $2 { 1-0 (32) Carlsen,M (2861) -Aronian,L (2759) chess24.com INT 2022 } 12. Bd3 f5 13. Qf3 $16 ) 12. Be2 ( 12. a3 Be6 13. b4 Bb6 14. Be2 a5 15. b5 Rc8 $44 16. bxc6 O-O $1 17. f5 { The position becomes very double-edged. } 17... Rxc6 18. fxe6 Rxc3 $13 ) 12... Be6 13. O-O O-O-O 14. h3 f5 { This is Black's point! } 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. Qg6 Kb8 $44 { The position is quite sharp but Black has fantastic compensation for the missing pawn. } ) ( 8. Bd2 Nxe5 9. Qe4 Qe7 $11 ) 8... c6 9. e3 g5 $1 ( 9... Qa5+ { This logical move leads to a slightly more pleasant position for White. } 10. Nc3 Nxe5 11. Qd4 f6 12. a3 Be7 13. b4 Qc7 14. Be2 $14 ) 10. Bg3 Qa5+ ( 10... h5 $6 11. h4 Qb6 12. Qc1 $14 ) 11. Nd2 ( 11. Nc3 Nxe5 12. Qe4 Bg7 $11 ) 11... Be6 12. Qc2 O-O-O ( 12... Bb4 13. a3 O-O-O { Should lead to the same thing as the main line below. } ) 13. O-O-O Bb4 ( 13... Qxa2 $6 { It's important to avoid capturing this pawn for the moment since Black loses the momentum. } 14. Bc4 Bxc4 15. Qxc4 Qxc4+ 16. Nxc4 $14 ) 14. a3 Bxd2+ 15. Rxd2 Bb3 { Black has this resource thanks to the pressure on White's rook on d2. } 16. Qf5+ Be6 17. Qc2 Bb3 18. Qc3 ( 18. Qf5+ $11 ) 18... Qxc3+ 19. bxc3 Rxd2 20. Kxd2 Rd8+ 21. Ke2 Rd5 22. h4 ( 22. e4 Ra5 23. h4 h6 24. Kd3 Be6 $11 { Black will start to collect White's pawns. } ) 22... Bc4+ 23. Kf3 Nxe5+ 24. Bxe5 Bxf1 25. Bd4 ( 25. Rxf1 Rxe5 26. hxg5 Rxg5 $11 ) 25... Rf5+ 26. Kg3 gxh4+ 27. Rxh4 Rg5+ 28. Rg4 Rxg4+ 29. Kxg4 Bxg2 30. Bxa7 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (45) Rapport,R (2763) -Dominguez Perez,L (2758) Saint Louis 2021 } *

