1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 { This line used to be popular at some point in the past, but nowadays it has been established that Black is equalizing without much trouble. } 4... a6 $1 { Preparing b7-b5. } ( 4... e6 { Transposes to the Vienna. } ) ( 4... c6 { Transposes to the Slav defence. } ) 5. e4 ( 5. a4 Nc6 $1 { After a2-a4, the b4 and a5-squares became very attractive for the knight on c6. } 6. e4 ( 6. e3 $6 Na5 $1 7. Ne5 Be6 8. e4 Nd7 $15 ) 6... Bg4 7. Be3 Na5 8. h3 { The most critical continuation. } ( 8. Qc2 e6 { Black is fine. } ) 8... Bh5 9. g4 Bg6 10. Nd2 e6 11. f4 ( 11. f3 c5 { It's important to strike in the center. } ) 11... Bb4 12. f5 exf5 13. exf5 ( 13. gxf5 $2 Bh5 14. Be2 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Qd7 $17 { [%cal Ge8c8] } ) 13... O-O 14. Qf3 Re8 15. fxg6 hxg6 { Black gave up a piece but the initiative is quite dangerous to White. } 16. Bg2 ( 16. Kf2 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6d4] } 17. Nxc4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Qxd4+ 19. Kg2 Qc5 $44 { [%cal Ga8d8,Gb7b5] } ) 16... Qxd4 17. Kf2 Qd3 18. Rhd1 Qc2 ( { Winning another pawn with: } 18... Bxc3 $5 { is also possible, when Black has four pawns for the piece. } 19. bxc3 Qxc3 20. Rac1 Qb4 $44 ) 19. Rdc1 Qxb2 20. Rab1 Qa3 21. Ra1 Qb2 $11 ) ( 5. e3 b5 6. a4 b4 7. Nb1 e6 ( { Another good continuation for Black is: } 7... c5 8. Bxc4 Nc6 $11 ) 8. Bxc4 Bb7 9. O-O c5 $11 { [%cal Gb8c6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8] The b8-knight is better placed on c6 instead of d7 because it will put pressure on the d4-pawn and can potentially go to a5 in the future. } ) 5... b5 6. e5 ( 6. a4 b4 7. e5 ( 7. Na2 Nxe4 8. Bxc4 e6 9. O-O Bb7 $15 ) 7... bxc3 8. exf6 cxb2 9. fxg7 bxa1 10. gxh8 { This is not a thing that you will see every day, four queens on the board, but in any case, Black is better. } 10... Qd6 11. Bxc4 { 1-0 (33) Adhiban,B (2654) -Alekseenko,K (2704) Moscow 2019 } ( 11. hxf8 Kxf8 12. Bh6+ Qxh6 13. Qxa1 Qe6+ 14. Be2 Nd7 $15 ) 11... c3 $1 12. Nd2 Qg6 13. e5 Nc6 14. e3 cxd4 15. O-O dxe3 16. fxe3 Be6 $15 { Black is a pawn-up with a solid position, and it's good to note that the king is quite safe on the e8-square. } ) ( 6. Be2 e6 7. a4 ( 7. O-O $6 Bb7 8. Qc2 Nbd7 $17 { Black is a clear pawn up and it's good to note that Black hasn't played c7-c6 in this case, so the bishop from b7 has a good scope on the long diagonal. } ) 7... Bb7 8. axb5 axb5 9. Rxa8 Bxa8 $11 ) 6... Nd5 7. a4 ( 7. Ng5 $2 e6 8. Qh5 Qe7 9. Be2 Nc6 $17 { Putting pressure on the d4-pawn. } ) 7... e6 { The simplest continuation for Black. } ( { The other main theory is: } 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 Bb7 9. e6 fxe6 10. Be2 Qd5 11. Ng5 $13 ) 8. axb5 Bb4 $1 { Trying to provoke Bd2 first and then to continue with Nb6. } ( 8... Nb6 { This is the old main line that is also fine for Black. } ) 9. Qc2 ( 9. Bd2 Nb6 10. Be2 Bb7 11. bxa6 Rxa6 12. Rxa6 Nxa6 13. O-O O-O $11 { c7-c5 can be considered next. } ) ( 9. Qd2 Nb6 10. Be2 ( 10. bxa6 Rxa6 11. Rxa6 Bxa6 12. Be2 Nc6 13. O-O O-O { Black has a very promising position, especially with the d5-square being under control. } 14. Qf4 Ne7 $11 { 0-1 (53) Salem,A (2684) -Aronian,L (2775) Chess.com INT 2022 } ) 10... axb5 11. Rxa8 Nxa8 12. Qf4 Nb6 13. Qg4 Kf8 14. O-O Bxc3 15. bxc3 h6 16. h4 Bb7 $13 { White doesn't seem to have sufficient compensation for the pawn. } ) 9... Nb6 10. Qe4 ( 10. Bg5 Qd7 { Doesn't bring White anything. } ) 10... Qd5 11. Qg4 ( 11. Qxd5 $6 exd5 12. bxa6 Nxa6 $15 ) 11... axb5 12. Rxa8 Qxa8 13. Qxg7 ( 13. Be2 $6 g6 14. O-O Bxc3 15. bxc3 h6 $15 { Black can eventually bring the king on the kingside with Kf8 and Kg7. } ) 13... Bxc3+ ( 13... Qa1 14. Qxh8+ Kd7 15. Kd1 { Leads to the same thing as the main line below. } ) 14. bxc3 Qa1 15. Qxh8+ Kd7 16. Kd1 ( 16. Kd2 Qa2+ { With a draw. } ) 16... Qa4+ 17. Ke1 ( 17. Kd2 Qa2+ { White can't escape the move repetition. } ) 17... Qa1 $11 *

