1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 ( 3. e3 { Starting with this move for White cuts off the option of playing a6 as in the 3.Nf3 a6 line, but 3.e3 allows the additional option of 3...e5, although in this course, I will recommend the move 3...Nf6. } 3... Nf6 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nc3 ( 5. Qe2 c5 { This will also transpose. } ) 5... c5 { This will transpose to the upcoming chapters. } ) 3... Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 { White usually castles in this position in order to keep some flexibility with the knight from b1 that can go to c3 or the d2-square later on. } 6. Qe2 ( 6. a3 Nc6 ( 6... a6 { This is also very good in this move order. } ) 7. O-O { Transposes to the upcoming lessons. } ) ( 6. b3 cxd4 ( 6... Nc6 { Is also good. } ) 7. Qxd4 ( 7. Nxd4 Bb4+ { It's good to provoke White's next move. } 8. Bd2 Bc5 9. Bc3 O-O $11 { Black has a very simple plan of developing the pieces with Qe7, Bd7 and Nc6. } ) 7... Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 $11 { [%cal Gb8c6] } ) ( 6. dxc5 { This idea is better once White has castled because now, White will be forced to recapture with the king on d1. } 6... Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Bxc5 8. Ke2 b6 $11 { Intending Bb7 next. } ) 6... Nc6 { Sticking with the same plan as in the lines analyzed in the upcoming chapters. } ( 6... a6 $5 { This is also possible. } ) 7. dxc5 ( 7. O-O { Transposes to the upcoming lessons. } ) 7... Bxc5 { Black usually spends a tempo on Be7 first, but in this case, the bishop was developed on c5 in one move. } 8. O-O O-O 9. Nc3 ( 9. Rd1 Qe7 { Doesn't change much. } ) 9... e5 { Other plans are also possible, such as playing with Bd7 and Rc8 for example. } 10. Ng5 { 10.e4 isn't good for White since it gives away the control over the d4-square, and Black can play 10...Bg4 in order to make use of it. } ( 10. Bd3 Qe7 11. Ne4 Bg4 { Black isn't afraid to give up the bishop on c5 because after 12.Nxc5 Qxc5, e5-e4 is a threat. } 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. Be4 Bf5 $11 ) ( 10. Rd1 Qe7 { Intending e5-e4 next. } ) 10... Qe7 { It's good to be aware that 10...h6 11.Nxf7 Rxf7 12. Bxf7+ Kxf7 13.Qc4+ wins the bishop on c5 for White. } 11. Nge4 ( 11. Qc2 { [%cal Gc3d5,Gc2h7] } 11... Nb4 $1 { Covering the d5-square and attacking the queen simultaneously. } 12. Qb1 h6 13. Nge4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Bb6 { Black can also choose to play something else, such as Rd8 for example, but it seems logical to keep the bishop. } 15. a3 Nc6 16. b4 Rd8 17. Ng3 ( 17. Bb2 Bf5 { Pins the knight. } ) 17... Be6 $11 { Black will bring the a8-rook to c8 soon. } ) 11... Bf5 $1 12. Qf3 ( 12. Nxc5 Qxc5 { [%csl Rc4] } 13. b3 Rfd8 14. a4 Na5 15. Ba3 Qb6 $11 { Black will exchange the bishop on c4 and play Rac8 at some point. } ) 12... Bg6 $5 ( 12... Nxe4 { Is also possible. } 13. Nxe4 Bg6 $11 ) 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Qxf6 gxf6 15. a3 { 1/2 (30) Sandocal,U (1879) -Krug,E (1812) LSS email 2019 } ( 15. Nd5 Rfd8 { Is similar. The point is that 16.Nxf6+ Kg7 17.Nd5 Na5 leads to some problems for White. } ) 15... Rfd8 16. Nd5 Rac8 { Sacrificing a pawn for activity. } 17. Nxf6+ ( 17. b4 Bf8 18. Bb2 Ne7 { Trying to exchange some pieces, while 19.Nxf6+ Kg7 20.Bxe5 Rxc4 wins a piece when White doesn't have any good discovered checks. } 19. Rad1 Nxd5 20. Rxd5 ( 20. Bxd5 a5 21. bxa5 Rc2 { [%csl Rb2] } 22. Ba1 Ra8 $11 ) 20... Rxd5 21. Bxd5 Rc2 22. Ba1 Bd3 23. Rd1 Be2 24. Re1 Bc4 $11 { [%csl Ra1] Even if White captures the pawn on b7, Black is the one fighting for advantage due to the more active pieces, while Ra2 is also an idea in order to regain the pawn. } ) 17... Kg7 18. Nd5 b5 ( 18... Na5 $5 { This is a very straightforward continuation that leads to equality. } 19. Ba2 Bc2 20. b4 Nb3 21. Bxb3 Bxb3 22. bxc5 Rxd5 $11 ) 19. Ba2 a5 20. Rd1 b4 $44 { Although Black is a pawn down, White's pieces are very passive and there is fantastic compensation. } *

