1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. Nc3 Nc6 { This is the move that is going to be recommended in this course. It became popular in recent years, with the idea to postpone capturing on d4 and make the idea of Qe2 and Rd1 more difficult to execute for White. Black intends to continue with a6 and b5 next. } 7. a3 ( 7. Bb5 Be7 8. O-O ( 8. Ne5 Qc7 9. Qf3 { 9.Qa4 would be similar. } 9... O-O { Black doesn't want to spend a tempo protecting the knight with Bd7, so giving up a pawn for activity is a good idea in this case. } 10. Bxc6 ( 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxc6 ( 11. Qxc6 Qb8 { [%cal Gc8b7] Black has very good compensation for the pawn. } ) 11... Rb8 12. O-O Rd8 $44 ) 10... bxc6 11. Qxc6 Qb8 12. O-O Bb7 13. Qa4 Bd6 $11 { Black's bishop pair is quite strong, compensating for the pawn deficit. } ) 8... O-O 9. dxc5 ( 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Na4 Ba6 11. Re1 cxd4 ( 11... Nd7 { This move, with the idea to keep the bishop on c1 closed, is also possible. } ) 12. exd4 Rc8 $11 { Black can consider playing c6-c5 or Nd5 next. } ) 9... Bxc5 10. Qe2 Bd7 11. Rd1 Qe7 $11 { Including the rooks in the game with Rfd8 and Rac8 should be Black's plan. } ) ( 7. d5 $6 exd5 8. Nxd5 Be6 9. Nxf6+ Qxf6 10. Qb3 Bxc4 11. Qxc4 Be7 $11 { [%csl Rc1] The position is slightly more preferable for Black because the bishop on c1 is quite passive and Black's queenside pawn majority can start advancing soon. } ) 7... a6 8. Bd3 { Other moves will transpose to lines that will be analyzed later. } 8... cxd4 { Black should capture on d4 now, otherwise White will capture the pawn on c5. } 9. exd4 g6 $5 { [%csl Rd4][%cal Gf8g7] A very interesting way to play that is possible because White played Bd3 too early, so the pawn push d4-d5 isn't supported. The idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 that will put pressure on the d4-pawn, and have a solid structure in front of the king that can withstand White's potential attack. } ( { The normal way to continue for Black is: } 9... Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 b5 { With a decent position for Black. } ) 10. O-O ( 10. Ne5 Bg7 ( 10... Nxd4 $6 11. Qa4+ { Runs into problems for Black. } ) ( 10... Qxd4 { This is also possible, although Black will need to be more accurate since the development is being neglected. } 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Be3 Qe5 13. Qa4 Bd7 14. O-O Bd6 15. g3 c5 16. Qd1 Bc6 17. Bf4 Qd4 18. Be3 Qe5 $11 ) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. O-O ( 12. Be3 O-O 13. O-O a5 $11 { [%cal Ga8b8,Gf6d5] } ) 12... Qxd4 ( 12... O-O { Is also fine for Black. } ) 13. Be3 Qd8 14. Na4 { White is trying to make use of the c5 and b6-squares. } 14... O-O { 14...Nd5 runs into 15.Bc5, when Black won't be able to castle. } 15. Bb6 Qd5 16. Qc2 ( 16. Bc5 Re8 17. Rc1 Rb8 18. Nb6 Qe5 19. b4 Qc7 20. Nc4 Rd8 21. Qe2 Nd5 $11 { Black will push e5 and develop the light-squared bishop, while Nf4 is a threat that White should deal with. } ) 16... c5 { Opening up the h1-a8 diagonal! } 17. Nxc5 { Fedoseev-Cheparinov, Samarkand,blity 2023, } ( 17. Bxc5 Bb7 { [%cal Gf8d8] } ) 17... a5 $1 { [%csl Rb6] } 18. Rac1 Qc6 19. Na4 Qxc2 20. Rxc2 Nd5 21. Bc5 Rd8 $11 { [%cal Gc8d7] The position is approximately balanced but Black is the side who is playing for a win, and moves like Bd7 and Rb8 can be considered next. } ) ( 10. Bg5 Bg7 11. Ne4 h6 { Black will exchange some pieces and will have a fine position. } 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Be4 Bd7 { The position is a bit passive for the moment, but on the other hand, the pawn on d4 is quite weak, while there won't be any real attack on the kingside since some minor pieces have already been exchanged. } 15. O-O O-O 16. Qd2 h5 17. Rfd1 Rfd8 $11 { [%cal Gd7e8] } ) 10... Bg7 11. Ne4 ( 11. Re1 O-O 12. Be3 Ne7 13. Ne5 Nfd5 $11 { Black will continue with b6 and Bb7, when Black will be doing very well. } ) ( 11. Be3 O-O 12. Qd2 b6 $11 { [%cal Gc8b7] 1-0 (73) Hakobyan,A (2613) -Grischuk,A (2736) Chess.com INT 2023 } ) 11... Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Nxd4 { Black doesn't have to capture this pawn, although it seems reasonable to do so. } 13. Be3 ( 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Qf3 O-O 15. Rd1 { White has sufficient compensation for the pawn but not more. } 15... Qf6 16. Qg3 Qe5 $11 ) 13... e5 14. Qa4+ Qd7 ( { Another possible continuation is: } 14... Bd7 15. Qb4 a5 16. Qxb7 Rb8 17. Qa7 Qb6 18. Qxb6 Rxb6 $11 ) 15. Qxd7+ Bxd7 16. Bxb7 Rb8 17. Bxa6 Nc2 18. Rac1 Nxe3 19. fxe3 Rxb2 { The position is approximately balanced but Black has good potential to be better thanks to the bishop pair and better pawn structure. } 20. Rc7 e4 21. Ng5 Be5 22. Rc5 f6 $11 *[Event "?"]

