1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 {The recommended move of this course. The other main move for Black is 6...a6.} 7. Bb5 (7. Ne5 Qc7 (7... Nxe5 $6 {Capturing the knight may lead to some problems for Black.} 8. dxe5 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Nd7 10. f4 $14) (7... cxd4 $5 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. exd4 Bd6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd8c7] This continuation is also fine for Black.}) 8. Nxc6 (8. Na3 $6 {This is overambitious for White.} Nxe5 9. Nb5 Qb8 10. dxe5 Qxe5 11. f4 Qb8 $15 {Black will kick the knight away with a6 and will stay a clear pawn-up.}) 8... Qxc6 9. Nc3 (9. Qe2 a6 {Intending b5 and Bb7 next.}) (9. Na3 Bd7 {The knight on a3 seems to be a bit misplaced.}) 9... Bd7 {Black isn't spending time on a6 in this case and continues with the development immediately.} 10. b3 (10. d5 exd5 11. Nxd5 b5 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. Bd5 Rc8 14. e4 Be7 $11 {Black will castle next and can play c4 later on, and even though the bishop on d5 looks strong, Black can simply exchange it with Be6 at any moment.}) (10. Bb5 Qc7 $11) 10... cxd4 11. exd4 {White intends to push d4-d5 next, so Black needs to take some action.} (11. Qxd4 Qc5 $11 {The endgame is fine for Black, while running away from the queen trade with 12. Qh4 can be met by 12...b5.}) 11... Bb4 12. d5 (12. Bb2 Bxc3 13. Bxc3 O-O {Black gave up the dark-squared bishop but gained control over the outpost on d5 in return.} 14. Bb4 Rfe8 15. Rc1 Qb6 $11) 12... Qc5 13. Bd2 (13. Be3 Qa5 14. dxe6 Bxe6 15. Nb5 (15. Bxe6 Bxc3 {Attacks both the rook on a1 and bishop on e6.}) 15... O-O 16. a3 Bxc4 17. bxc4 Bc3 18. Rb1 Be5 $11) 13... O-O 14. dxe6 Bxe6 15. Na4 (15. Bxe6 Bxc3 16. Rc1 Rad8 17. Rxc3 Qd4 $11 18. Bc4 Qxd2 19. Qf3 Ne4 {Black doesn't have any problems in the position.}) 15... Qe7 16. Bxb4 Qxb4 17. Bxe6 fxe6 {It may seem like the e6-pawn can be weak, but the material is reduced and Black doesn't have any problems.} 18. Qe2 Qe4 {The queen exchange is in Black's favor.} 19. Rfe1 Qxe2 20. Rxe2 Rac8 {Sacrificing the pawn for activity.} 21. Nb2 {21.Rxe6 is met by 21...Rc2.} Rfd8 22. Nc4 b5 23. Ne5 Kf8 $11 {[%cal Gf8e7] Black has good control over the c and d-files, while the e6-pawn can be easily protected if needed, so the endgame is simply equal.}) (7. Bd3 cxd4 (7... Be7 8. dxc5 {This is White's idea.}) 8. exd4 Be7 {Playing with g6 and Bg7 is also possible, when White will likely play Nc3 and will transpose to the previous chapter, but here, Be7 is also good enough since Black didn't spend a tempo on a7-a6.} 9. Nc3 O-O {Black intends to continue with b6 and Bb7 next.} 10. a3 (10. Re1 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] This is a standard position where White has an isolated pawn, but the problem is that White played Bd3 too early which gave Black the time to develop properly.} 11. Ne5 Bb7 12. Ba6 {An interesting try, intending to meet 12...Bxa6 with 13.Nxc6 and then d4-d5, but Black can simply sidestep all that with:} Qc8 13. Bxb7 Qxb7 14. Nxc6 (14. Qf3 Rac8 $11) 14... Qxc6 15. d5 Qc4 16. Qe2 (16. dxe6 {Leads to a similar position.} fxe6 17. Qe2 Qxe2 18. Rxe2 Kf7 $11) 16... Qxe2 17. Rxe2 Bc5 18. dxe6 fxe6 19. Be3 {Capturing the pawn on e6 will be met by Ng4, when there is too much pressure on the f2-pawn.} Bxe3 20. Rxe3 Nd5 {This is the easiest way to equalize, sacrificing the e6-pawn.} 21. Rxe6 (21. Nxd5 exd5 {Is fine for Black.}) 21... Nxc3 22. bxc3 Rac8 $11 {Black will continue by targeting White's weak queenside pawns with Rc5 and Rfc8, while the maximum that White can reach is 3vs2 on the kingside which is also drawn.}) (10. Bg5 Nd5 $11 {The exchanges favor Black.}) (10. Bf4 Nb4 11. Bb1 b6 $13) 10... b6 11. Re1 (11. Bc2 {Allows:} Ba6 $5 12. Re1 Rc8 $13 {When the moves Qd3 and Qe2 have been prevented.}) 11... Bb7 12. Bc2 (12. Bg5 Nd5 $11) (12. Bf4 Rc8 {Doesn't change much.}) 12... Na5 $5 {The most direct approach since now, it's not so easy for White to play Qd3.} ({There are many games with:} 12... Rc8 13. Qd3 g6 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Rad1 $13 {when Black is fine although the position remains complex.}) 13. Bg5 (13. Qd3 Bxf3 $1 14. Qxf3 Qxd4 15. Bf4 Qc4 $11 {White has some compensation for the pawn but Black has sufficient resources.}) (13. Bf4 Rc8 14. Ne5 b5 $13 {Intending Nc4 next, while 15.Nxb5 is impossible due to 15. ..Qd5, a double attack that wins the knight.}) (13. Ne5 Nc6 14. Be3 Rc8 $11 {Black wants to exchange the knights, the queens, and then to play Nd5 at some point.}) 13... h6 14. Bf4 Nc4 (14... Rc8 {Is also possible.} 15. Ne5 Nc6 $11) 15. Ne5 Bd6 $5 16. Qe2 (16. Bxh6 {It seems tempting to play this move since the knight on c4 is hanging now, but Black also has a small tactic that leads to equality.} Nxe5 17. dxe5 Bxe5 18. Rxe5 Qxd1+ 19. Rxd1 gxh6 $11) 16... Rc8 17. Bd3 (17. Bb3 Ba6 {Defending the knight and pointing the bishop against White's queen. Black is fine.}) 17... b5 $5 {I like this move for Black, simply supporting the knight on c4.} 18. Nxb5 Bxe5 19. dxe5 Qd5 20. f3 Nh5 21. Be3 Qxb5 22. b3 Qxb3 23. Rab1 Qc3 24. Bxc4 Qxc4 25. Rxb7 a5 $11 {The knight isn't stranded on h5 and will jump to f4 soon.}) (7. Bb3 Be7 8. Nc3 (8. Qe2 cxd4 9. Rd1 e5 10. exd4 exd4 11. Be3 Bg4 12. Ba4 {Trying to regain the pawn.} (12. h3 $2 Qb6 $17) 12... O-O 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Bxd4 Nd5 $11) 8... O-O 9. Qe2 (9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Qe2 Qc7 $11) 9... cxd4 10. Rd1 e5 (10... b6 $5) (10... d3 $5 11. Rxd3 Qa5 {Is another option for Black.}) 11. h3 a6 $5 12. exd4 exd4 13. Be3 (13. Bf4 Bc5 {Black is fine.}) 13... Bc5 14. Qc4 Qe7 15. Nxd4 Na5 16. Nd5 (16. Nf5 Qxe3 {A strong in-between move, with Nxc4 to follow.}) 16... Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Nxb3 18. axb3 Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Be6 $11) (7. Re1 Be7 8. Nc3 (8. dxc5 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bxc5 {Transposes to 7.dxc5 that will be analyzed in the next lessons.}) (8. e4 cxd4 9. e5 Nd7 {It's unclear if White has sufficient compensation for the pawn, so Black is doing very well.} 10. Bb5 (10. Bf4 Nb6 11. Bf1 Bd7 $13 {[%cal Ga8c8]}) 10... Qb6 11. a4 O-O 12. Na3 {The position is complicated so it's good to see how it can continue, for example:} Nc5 13. Nc4 Qd8 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Nxd4 Qd5 16. Na5 Bd7 17. Be3 Rfc8 18. Rc1 Be8 {Black still has some problems due to the passive bishop on e8, but Black has sufficient resources in the position.} 19. Nc4 (19. b3 Nd3 20. Qxd3 Qxa5 $11 {Black will play c6-c5 next and activate the bishop through the c6-square.}) 19... Nxa4 20. Qxa4 c5 21. Nb5 Bc6 22. f3 Rcb8 23. Ncd6 (23. Red1 Bxb5 {Black is fine.}) 23... Bxd6 24. exd6 Bxb5 25. Qf4 e5 26. Qg3 Qxd6 27. Bxc5 Qg6 $11) 8... O-O 9. dxc5 (9. a3 b6 {Intending to recapture on c5 with the b-pawn.} 10. dxc5 bxc5 $11 {Black is also fine in these types of positions.}) 9... Qxd1 (9... Bxc5 {Should also be fine for Black.}) 10. Rxd1 Bxc5 {Black hasn't played a6 and weakened the b6-square, so now Black intends to continue with b6 and Bb7 next.} 11. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]} (11. b3 b6 12. Bb2 Bb7 13. Nb5 Rad8 $11) 11... b6 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7]} (11... Bd7 {I don't like this move very much because after:} 12. e4 $1 e5 13. Bg5 Bg4 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Nd5 Kg7 16. b4 Bb6 17. Rac1 $14 {The position is unpleasant for Black.}) 12. b4 Be7 13. Bb2 (13. e4 Bb7 14. e5 Ng4 15. Bf4 g5 16. Bxg5 (16. Bg3 Rfd8 $11 {If White plays h3, the knight can always be rerouted with Nh6-Nf5.}) 16... Bxg5 17. Nxg5 Ncxe5 $11) 13... Bb7 $11 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8]}) (7. e4 cxd4 8. e5 Nd7 9. Re1 Be7 {Transposes to 7.Re1.}) 7... Bd7 8. Nc3 Qb6 $146 {Putting pressure on the bishop on b5.} (8... cxd4 {There are games that continued with this move which is also possible to play, although it is a bit passive in my opinion.} 9. exd4 Be7 10. a3 O-O 11. Bd3 {The issue for Black is the passive bishop on d7 which is the difference to the other lines when Black plays b6 and Bb7.} Rc8 12. Re1 Qc7 13. Be3 Rfd8 14. Rc1 Be8 15. Qe2 $13) 9. Re1 (9. dxc5 Qxc5 10. Be2 Be7 11. e4 O-O 12. Bf4 (12. Be3 Qa5 {The queen simply sidesteps the attack and Black is fine.}) 12... Rfd8 {[%cal Gd7e8]} 13. Rc1 Be8 14. Qb3 Qb4 $11 {Later on, Black can play Nd4 and activate the light-squared bishop from the c6-square.}) 9... Bd6 10. dxc5 Bxc5 {10...Qxc5 can be met with 11.e4 now.} 11. Bf1 Qc7 {Avoiding Na4 and with that, saving the dark-squared bishop.} (11... O-O $6 12. Na4 {This is White's idea.}) 12. b3 (12. a3 {Intending b2-b4.} Ne5 $1 13. Nb5 Bxb5 14. Bxb5+ Ke7 $11 {[%cal Gh8d8] Black's pieces are becoming very active while the bishop on c1 remains closed.}) (12. Nb5 Qb8 13. b3 (13. a3 a6 14. b4 Be7 15. Nbd4 Nxd4 {Black will simply make some exchanges and will have a solid position.} 16. Qxd4 O-O 17. Bb2 Rd8 18. Qh4 Nd5 19. Qe4 Bf6 20. Ne5 (20. Bxf6 Nxf6 $11) 20... Bb5 $11) (13. Qc2 Bb4 14. Bd2 (14. Rd1 O-O {Simply continuing the development.}) 14... Bxd2 15. Nxd2 O-O $11 {Intending a6 and Rc8 next.}) 13... O-O 14. Bb2 Rd8 15. Qc2 {The pawn structure after 15.Bxf6 gxf6 is fine for Black.} Be7 16. Rac1 a6 17. Nc3 Be8 18. h3 Qc7 {[%cal Ga8c8]} 19. Ne4 Nxe4 20. Qxe4 Qa5 {[%cal Ga5h5] An interesting idea, trying to get the queen to the kingside.} 21. a3 Qh5 $11 {Black can consider playing moves like Qg6 and Rac8 eventually.}) 12... O-O 13. Bb2 Rfd8 14. Qb1 (14. Qc2 Be7 {Is similar.}) 14... Be7 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 Qa5 {Once again, Black employs the same idea of transferring the queen to the kingside.} 17. a3 (17. Qg4 Bf8 {Simply defends the checkmate threat, so it doesn't change much in the position.}) 17... Qf5 18. Qxf5 exf5 19. b4 Be6 $11 *


