1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. a3 { This move is White's best choice if White is heading for the endgame, although Black is fine in this line too. } 7... a6 8. dxc5 ( 8. Nc3 { Transposes to 7.Nc3 a6 8.a3. } ) ( 8. Qe2 { Will transpose to the upcoming lessons. } ) ( 8. Ba2 b5 9. Qc2 $14 { White's idea is to put pressure on the pinned c5-pawn. } ( 9. Nc3 { Transposes to lessons that will be analyzed later. } ) 9... c4 $1 { An aggressive approach that shows that Black also has ambitions in the position. } ( 9... Qb6 $6 10. Nc3 Be7 ( 10... Bb7 11. d5 $1 { The start of a strong initiative. } 11... exd5 12. e4 $36 ) 11. dxc5 $1 Bxc5 12. b4 Be7 13. e4 $1 { [%cal Gc1e3] White is able to gain an advantage with accurate play. } 13... Bb7 14. Be3 Qc7 15. Nd5 $1 exd5 16. exd5 O-O 17. Nd4 $1 Ng4 18. g3 Bf6 19. dxc6 Nxe3 20. fxe3 Bxd4 21. exd4 Qxc6 22. Qxc6 Bxc6 23. Rac1 $14 { [%csl Ra6,Rb5] After the dust has settled, by having weak pawns on the queenside and the worse minor piece, the position is unpleasant for Black. } ) 10. Nc3 ( 10. b3 { This isn't working for White after: } 10... cxb3 11. Qxc6+ $6 { If White recaptured the pawn on b3, Black could have simply continued the development with Bb7. } 11... Bd7 { [%csl Ra2] } ) ( 10. Rd1 Be7 11. e4 Ra7 $1 { [%cal Ga7d7] A very interesting idea! Black will get the rook to d7 and there will be a lot of pressure on the d4-pawn. } 12. h3 ( 12. b3 Rd7 13. Bb2 cxb3 14. Bxb3 Bb7 15. Nc3 Na5 16. Ba2 O-O 17. Ne5 Rc7 18. Qe2 Qc8 19. Rac1 Nd7 20. Nxd7 Qxd7 { Having control over the c4-square is a good asset for Black. } 21. d5 Nc4 22. dxe6 Qxe6 $11 ) 12... Rd7 13. Be3 Bc5 $1 14. e5 Nd5 15. Nc3 Be7 $13 { Black has accomplished a very nice light-squared strategy. } ) 10... Be7 ( 10... Bb7 11. Rd1 { Is similar. } ) 11. Rd1 Qc7 { It may be advantageous to postpone Bb7 because if White plays e3-e4, Black can reply with e6-e5 when the bishop can also be developed along the h3-c8 diagonal. } 12. h3 O-O 13. e4 e5 14. d5 Na5 $11 { Black has a nice blockade over the d6-square and can consider moves like Bd6, Nd7, and Bb7, while the bishop on a2 remains passive. } ) ( 8. Bd3 cxd4 9. exd4 g6 $5 10. Nc3 Bg7 { Transposes to the previous lessons. } ) 8... Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bxc5 10. b4 ( 10. Nbd2 O-O { This is similar as White needs to play b2-b4 sooner or later. } ) 10... Be7 { The difference from this position in comparison to other similar endgames is that Black has already played a7-a6 and the b1-knight hasn't commited to c3 yet, so Nbd2 with the idea of Nb3 and eventually to use the c5-square is a possibility for White. } 11. Bb2 O-O { If White proceeds with Nbd2, Black's plan is to play Bd7, Rfd8, and then Be8, while if White continues with Nc3, then Black can already commit with b7-b5 and then Bb7 since White won't have the plan of using the c5-square with Nbd2-Nb3 and Nc5 at some point. } ( 11... b5 { It's also possible to play this, although it's not my preferred choice. } 12. Be2 Bb7 13. Nbd2 O-O 14. Nb3 { [%csl Rc5] Trying to use the c5-square when Ne1-Nd3 is also a possible idea for White. } 14... Rfd8 ( 14... a5 15. Bxb5 axb4 16. a4 $14 { [%csl Ga4,Gb5] The passed a-pawn can be unpleasant for Black in a practical game. } ) 15. Rac1 ( 15. Ne1 Rac8 16. Nd3 Nd7 17. Rdc1 Na7 $11 { [%cal Gb7d5] } ) 15... Rxd1+ 16. Bxd1 Nd7 17. Nfd2 Rc8 { Black has enough resources in the position to hold the balance. } 18. f4 Kf8 19. Bf3 g6 20. Kf2 Nd8 21. Rxc8 Bxc8 $11 { 1/2 (41) Yilmaz,M (2650) -Vitiugov,N (2712) Budva 2023 } ) 12. Nbd2 ( 12. Nc3 b5 13. Be2 Bb7 $11 { [%csl Rc3] } ) 12... Bd7 13. Bf1 $5 { White is retreating the bishop so the d2-knight can use the c4-square. Retreating the bishop to f1 instead of e2 gives White the additional possibility to play g3 and Bg2 at some point. } ( 13. Ne4 { This move leads to exchanges after which Black is fine since Black's pieces are more passive. } 13... Rfd8 { 1/2-1/2 (61) Erdos,V (2622) -Borisek,J (2591) chess.com INT 2021 } 14. Nxf6+ ( 14. Nd6 Na5 $1 15. bxa5 Ba4 { [%csl Rd1,Rd6] An interesting tactic that's good to be aware of. } ) 14... Bxf6 15. Bxf6 gxf6 $11 { The pawn structure on the kingside is fine for Black and the plan is to continue with moves like Kf8, Ke7, Be8, and Rac8. } ) ( 13. Nb3 Rfd8 14. Rac1 Be8 15. Rxd8 Rxd8 16. Be2 Ne4 { The knight will retreat to d6 if needed in order to guard the b7-pawn, while this move also opens the possibility of exchanging the dark-squared bishops with Bf6 at some point. } 17. Nfd4 Nd6 $11 18. f4 { Black's position is very solid. } ) ( 13. Be2 Rfd8 14. Nc4 ( 14. Nb3 Be8 ( 14... Ne4 $5 { Is also possible. } ) 15. Rxd8 ( 15. Rdc1 Ne4 { Is in Black's favor. } ) 15... Rxd8 ( { Another possibility is: } 15... Nxd8 $5 16. Rc1 Ne4 17. Ne5 Nd6 { Black is a bit passive but will slowly exchange the pieces, so the following game ended in a draw: } 18. f4 Rc8 19. Rxc8 Nxc8 20. Nc4 Ba4 21. Nd4 Nd6 22. Nxd6 Bxd6 $11 { 1/2 (30) Yilmaz,M (2640) -Praggnanandhaa,R (2738) Douglas 2023 } ) 16. Rc1 ( 16. Nfd2 Na7 $5 { The idea is to activate the light-squared bishop with Ba4 next. } 17. Rc1 Ba4 18. Kf1 Nc6 19. Ke1 Nd7 $11 ) 16... Ne4 17. Nfd4 Nd6 18. Kf1 ( 18. Nxc6 Bxc6 19. Bxa6 $2 Bd5 $19 { [%csl Ra6,Rb3] } ) ( 18. Bf3 Ne5 { Simply attacks the bishop, so White didn't accomplish much by putting the bishop on f3. } ) 18... Rc8 $11 ) 14... Be8 15. Nd4 ( 15. Nb6 Rxd1+ 16. Rxd1 Rd8 17. Rxd8 Bxd8 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (78) Terry,R (2503) -Van Foreest,J (2641) Chess.com INT 2018 } ) 15... Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bb5 $1 { Trying to exchange the light-squared bishops, although Bxc4 might also be a possibility sometimes. } 17. Rdc1 ( 17. Bf1 { White spends a tempo with the bishop and intends to play Na5 next, so Black can capture the knight now. That being said, Rac8 is also fine for Black. } 17... Bxc4 ( 17... Rac8 18. Na5 { 1-0 (62) Adhiban, B (2671) -Van Foreest,J (2609) Hoogeveen 2017 } 18... Rd7 $11 ) 18. Bxc4 a5 $11 { White has the bishop pair but the material is reduced and Black's position is quite solid. } ) 17... Nd5 18. Bf3 ( 18. Kf1 $6 Nf4 $1 { The position can become unpleasant for White. } ) ( 18. Bf1 h5 $5 19. Na5 Rd7 $11 ) 18... Bxc4 19. Rxc4 b5 20. Rcc1 a5 $11 ) 13... Rfd8 14. Nc4 ( 14. g3 { [%cal Gf1g2] } 14... Be8 15. Bg2 Nd5 ( 15... Rac8 { Is also possible. } 16. Rac1 h6 $11 ) 16. Nc4 ( 16. Nb3 Nb6 { The knight can jump to the c4 or a4-square later on. } ) 16... b5 17. Nce5 a5 18. Nxc6 Bxc6 19. Nd4 Be8 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (54) Goryachkina,A (2610) -Gaponenko,I (2347) Warsaw 2021 } ) ( 14. Nb3 Ne4 15. Rac1 Be8 $11 ) 14... Be8 15. Nd4 Nxd4 ( { An alternative for Black is: } 15... Rab8 $5 16. Rdc1 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Ne4 18. Bd3 Nd6 19. Nxd6 Bxd6 $11 ) 16. Bxd4 Nd5 17. e4 ( 17. Rdc1 Bb5 { This is a good square for the light-squared bishop. } ) ( 17. Rac1 Bb5 $11 ) ( 17. g3 Bb5 $11 { Intending Rac8 next. } ) 17... Nf6 18. Nb6 Rab8 19. f3 Nd7 20. Nc4 Nf6 { Black still wants to play Bb5. } 21. Be5 Rxd1 22. Rxd1 Rc8 23. Nd6 Rd8 $11 { Next moves that can be considered are Ba4 or Bc6 with the idea of playing Ne8 to put pressure on the pinned knight on d6. Black's position is quite solid, so this endgame is equal. } *[Event "?"]
