1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qe2 { White's idea is to play Rd1 next. The main move is 7.Nc3 which can transpose after 7... a6 8.Qe2, and in this chapter, options that avoid the transposition will be analyzed. } 7... a6 { Intending b7-b5 and Bb7 next, while capturing on d4 can be considered eventually. } 8. Rd1 ( 8. Bb3 b5 { I prefer to delay the capture on d4. } ( 8... cxd4 9. Rd1 Be7 10. exd4 O-O { Is another playable continuation for Black. } ) 9. a4 ( 9. dxc5 Bxc5 { Transposes to 8.dxc5. } ) ( 9. Nc3 { Tranposes to the upcoming lessons. } ) 9... Na5 ( 9... b4 { Is similar. } ) 10. Bc2 ( 10. Ba2 b4 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. e4 O-O 14. e5 Nd5 ( 14... Nd7 $5 15. Ne4 Be7 ) 15. Ne4 Be7 16. h4 Qb6 $13 { [%cal Gb4b3,Ga8c8] } ) 10... b4 11. Nbd2 ( 11. Rd1 Qc7 { Simply stepping away from the d-file. } ) ( 11. dxc5 Bxc5 { Is similar. } ) 11... Bb7 12. dxc5 Bxc5 { The knight on a5 is doing a good job by protecting the b3 and c4-squares. } 13. b3 ( 13. e4 Rc8 14. e5 Nd5 15. Ne4 h6 $1 { It's important to take control over the g5-square. } 16. Bd2 { Capturing the bishop with 16.Nxc5 doesn't accomplish much for White because Black's knights are very strong. } 16... Be7 17. Rac1 Nc4 $13 ) 13... O-O 14. Bb2 Nd5 15. Rfd1 Qe7 16. Rac1 Rfc8 $11 { [%csl Rc3] } 17. Ne4 f5 $5 18. Nxc5 Rxc5 { Black gave up the dark-squared bishop but intends to play Nc3 as soon as possible. } 19. e4 Nc3 20. Bxc3 Rxc3 21. Nd4 ( 21. exf5 Bxf3 22. gxf3 Rac8 $44 ) 21... f4 $1 22. Qh5 e5 23. Nf5 Qc7 24. h3 Rf8 { 24...Rxc2 25.Rxc2 Qxc2 26.Rd7 is good for White. } 25. Qg5 Nc6 26. Bd3 Bc8 $1 27. Bc4+ Kh8 28. Nh4 { [%cal Gh4g6] } 28... Rf6 29. Qh5 Qe7 30. Nf3 Bd7 31. Rxc3 bxc3 32. Rc1 Be8 33. Qg4 Bd7 34. Qh4 ( 34. Qh5 $11 { Leads to a repetition. } ) 34... Qa3 35. Rc2 Qa1+ 36. Kh2 Rh6 37. Qg5 Rg6 38. Qh4 Rh6 $11 ) ( 8. a4 Be7 $5 ( 8... cxd4 9. Rd1 Be7 10. exd4 O-O 11. Nc3 { This is a large theoretical position that is also playable for Black, although I prefer the simpler 8...Be7. } ) ( 8... Qc7 $5 { Is another interesting possibility. } ) 9. Rd1 ( 9. dxc5 O-O ( 9... Bxc5 $6 10. e4 $36 { It's better to avoid spending time on capturing the pawn, 9...0-0 is better. } ) 10. e4 ( 10. Rd1 { Transposes to 9.Rd1. } ) 10... Nd7 $1 { [%cal Gd7c5] An important move, intending to capture the c5-pawn with the knight and additionally, e4-e5 won't come with tempo in the future. } 11. Bf4 ( 11. Nc3 Nxc5 { Doesn't change much. } ) ( 11. Rd1 Qc7 { This is also fine for Black. } ) 11... Nxc5 12. Rd1 Bd7 13. Nc3 Qb6 $11 { Intending Rfd8 and Rac8 next. The position is pleasant for Black since the knight on c5 is untouchable because the pawn is already on a4, if it was on a3 however, it would have been a different story due to b2-b4. In addition, Black enjoys control over the b4 and a5-squares in this position. } ) ( 9. Nc3 O-O { Transposes to 7.Nc3 which will be analyzed in the upcoming lessons. } ) 9... O-O ( 9... Qc7 { Is also playable. } ) 10. dxc5 ( 10. Nc3 { Transposes to the upcoming lessons. } ) 10... Qc7 11. b3 ( 11. Nbd2 Bxc5 12. h3 ( 12. b3 e5 { Opens up the bishop from c8 that can be developed along the h3-c8 diagonal. } ) 12... Rd8 13. b3 Bd7 14. Bb2 Be8 $11 { The moves Rfd8 and Bd7-Be8 are a typical plan for Black, which after Black intends to continue with Rac8 and Be7 next. It's good to note that there shouldn't be any fear of Bxf6 gxf6 since the pawn structure will be fine for Black. } ) ( 11. Nc3 { Transposes to the next lessons. } ) 11... Ne4 $5 { [%cal Ge4c5] I prefer to capture the c5-pawn with the knight. } ( 11... Bxc5 { Capturing the c5-pawn immediately is also fine for Black. } 12. Bb2 Be7 13. Nbd2 Rd8 14. Rac1 Bd7 { [%cal Gd7e8] } 15. e4 Be8 16. e5 Nd5 17. Ne4 Qb6 { It seems like Black's position is a bit passive, although Black has sufficient counterplay with moves like Na5 or Nf4 later on. } ) 12. Bb2 ( 12. Ba3 Nxc5 13. Qc2 b6 $11 14. b4 Nxa4 $1 { [%cal Gb6b5] } 15. Qxa4 b5 16. Bxb5 axb5 17. Qxa8 $2 { If White captures the pawn on b5, Black has a choice between 17...Ba6 or 17...Nxb4. } 17... Bb7 18. Qxf8+ Bxf8 $17 { The queen is stronger than the two rooks since White's king can get in trouble, while the b4-pawn is also under attack. } ) ( 12. Qc2 Nxc5 13. Bd2 Rb8 ( 13... b6 $5 { Is another decent option for Black. } ) 14. Na3 Bd7 15. Bc3 Rfc8 16. Rac1 ( 16. Nb5 axb5 17. axb5 Ra8 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19. bxc6 Bxc6 $11 ) 16... Be8 $11 { The position remains complex, although it's good to note that the White pieces aren't placed ideally, especially the knight on a3. } ) ( 12. Nd4 Ne5 $1 13. b4 ( 13. Qc2 Ng4 14. f4 Nxc5 15. Nc3 Rd8 16. h3 Nf6 $11 ) 13... b6 14. Bd3 Nf6 15. cxb6 Qxb6 16. b5 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 axb5 18. Qxb5 Qc7 19. Qc6 Qb8 $11 { Black has sufficient counterplay due to the bishop pair and White's weak pawn on a4. Bb7 or Bd7 can be considered next. } ) 12... Nxc5 13. Nbd2 Rd8 14. Rac1 Bd7 15. h4 ( 15. Ne1 { Intending to activate the queen to the g4-square, albeit Black's position remains solid. } 15... Be8 16. Qg4 Bf8 $11 { Black can consider playing Rac8 next and Ne5 at some point. } ) 15... h6 $11 { With typical moves such as Be8, Bf8, and Rac8. } ) ( 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. e4 { The most critical continuation, opening up the bishop from c1 and intending e4-e5, when 9...e5 can be met with 10.Bxf7+ Kxf7 11.Qc4+ and Qxc5. } ( 9. Rd1 Qe7 { The queen is supporting e6-e5 now. } 10. Nc3 ( 10. a3 e5 11. b4 Ba7 $13 { [%cal Ge5e4,Gc8g4] e5-e4 is a threat and if White plays e3-e4, then Bg4 and Black will have good control over the d4-square. } ) 10... b5 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Bb7 14. Bd2 Rac8 15. Rac1 Bd6 $11 { The bishop on e4 seems strong but Black can exchange it with Ne5 later on, while other moves that can be considered are h6 and Rfd8. } ) ( 9. Nc3 O-O 10. e4 e5 11. Be3 ( 11. Bg5 Bg4 12. Nd5 Nd4 13. Qd1 Be7 $11 ) ( 11. h3 { Prevents Bg4 but Black can continue with: } 11... Nd4 12. Nxd4 Bxd4 $11 ) ( 11. Rd1 Nd4 12. Nxd4 exd4 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Qe7 $11 { The pawn on d4 is strong and Be6 can be considered next. } ) 11... Nd4 ( 11... Bxe3 12. Qxe3 Bg4 { Fighting for the d4-square in this way is also possible. } ) 12. Bxd4 exd4 13. Nd5 Be6 14. Nxf6+ ( 14. Nf4 Bxc4 15. Qxc4 Nxe4 16. Ne6 b5 17. Qb3 { Black can simply capture the knight with an equal position. } ) 14... Qxf6 15. Bxe6 Qxe6 $11 ) ( 9. a3 Bd6 $5 { Starting with 9...0-0 is also possible. } 10. Rd1 ( 10. b4 O-O 11. Bb2 Qe7 12. Nbd2 e5 $11 { The light-squared bishop can be developed along the h3-c8 diagonal now. } ) 10... O-O ( 10... Qc7 { Stepping out of the pin is also a logical possibility. } ) 11. e4 ( 11. b4 e5 { We can see this typical pawn push once again. } ) ( 11. Bd3 Qc7 { It's good to remove the queen from the d-file to avoid any potential tactics. } ) 11... b5 12. e5 ( 12. Ba2 Qc7 $13 ) ( 12. Bd3 Qc7 $13 ) 12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 bxc4 14. Nxc4 Nd5 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 $11 ) 9... b5 $1 10. Bb3 ( 10. Bd3 Nb4 $1 11. Rd1 Qb6 12. Bg5 Bb7 $13 { Black will castle and exchange the bishop on d3 eventually. } ) ( 10. e5 bxc4 11. exf6 { Now 11...Qxf6 would run into 12.Qxc4 which attacks the minor pieces along the c-file, but Black has the following resource: } 11... Qd3 $1 12. fxg7 Rg8 13. Qxd3 cxd3 14. Be3 ( 14. Bh6 Nd4 15. Nbd2 Bb7 $13 ) 14... Bxe3 15. fxe3 Rxg7 16. Nc3 Bb7 17. Rad1 O-O-O $11 { Black has a strong pawn on d3 and pressure on the g2-pawn, so the endgame is balanced. } ) 10... Nd4 { Going for exchanges seems to be the easiest continuation. } ( 10... Qc7 $5 11. e5 Nd5 { Is another decent option for Black. } ) 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Be3 ( 12. Nc3 Qe5 $1 { A typical way to prevent e4-e5! } 13. Kh1 { Trying to dislodge the queen from the e5-square with f2-f4 is met by: } ( 13. Qf3 { Intending Bf4 next, but Black is fine after: } 13... Bb7 14. Bf4 Qh5 $11 ) ( 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Ng4 $1 { Provoking a queen exchange. } 15. Qg3 { 15.Qh3 can be met with 15...h5. } 15... Qxg3 16. hxg3 Ke7 $11 ) ( 13. g3 Bb7 14. Nxb5 ( 14. Bf4 $6 Qh5 $15 ) 14... Nxe4 15. Nc3 Ng5 { The queen on e5 is immune due to Nh3#. } 16. Ba4+ Ke7 17. Bxg5+ Qxg5 $11 ) 13... Bb7 14. f4 Qh5 { Exchanging the queens and reaching an endgame where Black is fine thanks to the active pieces. } ( 14... Qd4 $5 15. Nxb5 Qxe4 { Is another possibility for Black. } ) 15. Qxh5 Nxh5 16. f5 O-O 17. fxe6 fxe6 18. Bxe6+ Kh8 19. Bd2 Nf6 $11 { Black will regain the pawn eventually and will restore the material balance. } ) 12... Qe5 ( 12... Qxe4 $2 13. Nd2 Qf5 14. g4 $1 { Using the fact that the queen is overloaded and has to guard the bishop on c5. } 14... Qe5 15. Nf3 Qe4 16. Ng5 Qe5 17. Qf3 Bxe3 18. Qxa8 O-O 19. Nxf7 $18 ) 13. Bxc5 Qxc5 14. Nc3 O-O 15. Rac1 Bb7 { If Black manages to activate the rooks with Rfd8 and Rac8, Black will be completely fine, although White can try to pose Black some problems in the meantime. } 16. e5 ( 16. Nd5 Qd4 17. Ne7+ ( 17. Rfd1 Qxe4 18. Qxe4 Nxe4 19. Nb6 Rad8 20. Nd7 Rfe8 21. Rc7 Bd5 { This attempt from White was unsuccessful and now White is fighting for a draw. } 22. Bxd5 exd5 23. Kf1 { White had to take care of the back-rank issues. } 23... Nf6 $11 ) 17... Kh8 18. e5 Nd7 19. Rc7 Rab8 20. Re1 { 20.Rd1 is met by 20...Qxe5. } 20... Rfe8 21. Nd5 Red8 $11 ) 16... Nd7 17. Rfd1 ( 17. Nd5 Qd4 { Is similar. } ) 17... Nxe5 18. Nd5 ( 18. Na4 Qa7 19. Nc5 ( 19. Qxe5 bxa4 20. Bxa4 Rac8 $11 ) 19... Nc4 20. Nxb7 Qxb7 21. Bxc4 bxc4 22. Rxc4 Rac8 $11 ) 18... Nc4 19. Bxc4 exd5 20. Bxd5 Qb6 $11 ) ( 8. Nc3 { Transposes to 7.Nc3 a6 8. Qe2. } ) ( 8. a3 b5 9. Ba2 Bb7 10. Rd1 ( 10. Nc3 { Transposes to the upcoming lessons. } ) 10... Qb6 ( 10... Qc7 { Is also good enough. } ) 11. dxc5 ( 11. Nc3 Rd8 12. d5 exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Be7 15. e4 O-O 16. Be3 Qc7 { [%cal Gc5c4] } 17. Ng5 ( 17. Rac1 c4 { This is Black's idea. } ) 17... Nd4 18. Bxd4 cxd4 19. Bxb7 Qxb7 20. Nf3 Rfe8 $11 { [%cal Ge7f6] } ) 11... Bxc5 12. b4 Be7 { Black is fine in this type of position, and as an idea in general, when the b5-pawn is defended, a6-a5 can be considered later on. } 13. Bb2 O-O 14. Nbd2 a5 ( 14... Rfd8 $11 ) 15. bxa5 Qxa5 $11 ) 8... b5 9. dxc5 ( 9. d5 exd5 10. Bxd5 ( 10. e4 $6 { This is already too ambitious from White. } 10... d4 11. Bd5 Bb7 12. a4 Be7 $15 ) 10... Nxd5 11. e4 Qe7 $1 { An important move, forcing White to capture on d5 with the rook. } 12. Rxd5 Be6 ( 12... Bb7 { Is also good. } ) 13. Rd1 Qb7 14. Nc3 Be7 $11 { [%cal Ge8g8] Black has a pleasant position. } ) ( 9. Bd3 c4 10. Bc2 Nb4 $1 { It's important to eliminate White's light-squared bishop. } 11. e4 Bb7 12. Nc3 ( 12. d5 $6 Bc5 $1 13. dxe6 Qe7 $15 { 1/2 (38) Dzagnidze,N (2531) -Gaponenko,I (2347) Warsaw 2021 } ) 12... Nxc2 13. Qxc2 Qc7 ( 13... b4 { Is another option for Black. } ) 14. d5 Rd8 $13 { Black has the bishop pair and although the position is approximately equal, White is the one who should be more careful. } ) ( 9. Bb3 c4 { Transposes to 9.Bd3. } ) 9... Qc7 10. Bd3 ( 10. Bb3 { This is a bit passive for White. } 10... Bxc5 11. a4 b4 $13 { [%cal Gc8b7,Ge8g8] } ) 10... Bxc5 ( { Another possibility for Black is: } 10... Nb4 $5 11. a4 Nxd3 12. Qxd3 b4 { Although this is a more complicated continuation because Black is lagging behind with the development. } ) 11. a4 { The only way for White to fight for an advantage. } 11... bxa4 { 11...b4 would have been met by 12.Nbd2 with Nb3 to follow, when Black will start to face some unpleasant threats. } 12. Rxa4 ( 12. Nc3 Nb4 13. Nxa4 Be7 $11 ) 12... O-O $1 { It's important to sacrifice the pawn on a6 for quick development. } ( 12... Nb4 { This doesn't lead to equality because White has the following sequence: } 13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Bd2 a5 15. Na3 O-O 16. Bxd7 Nxd7 17. Nc4 $14 { [%csl Ra5][%cal Gd1a1] } ) 13. Bd2 { [%cal Gd1c1,Gd2c3] } ( 13. Bxa6 Qb6 14. Bb5 Rxa4 15. Bxa4 Ba6 16. Qd2 Nb4 17. Nc3 Be7 $44 { [%cal Gf8d8] The most direct move toward equality. } 18. Qd4 Bc5 $11 { White should go for the repetition since 19.Qh4 can be met with 19...Nd3. } ) ( 13. Rc4 Nb4 14. Nc3 ( 14. Bd2 Qb6 $11 ) 14... Nxd3 ( 14... Bd7 $5 { This is also good, intending Bb5 at some point. } ) 15. Rxd3 Qa7 16. Ne5 Bb7 { White must play energetically now. } 17. e4 { Trying to get the d3-rook to the kingside. } ( 17. Nd7 Nxd7 18. Rxd7 Bb6 { [%cal Gf8d8] } 19. Qh5 Bf3 $1 20. Rxa7 Bxh5 21. Rxa8 Rxa8 22. Rc6 Bd8 $11 ) 17... Rfd8 18. Rh3 ( 18. Bg5 Rxd3 19. Nxd3 ( 19. Bxf6 Rxc3 $1 { An important in-between move. } 20. Rxc3 { Transposes to 18.Rh3. } ) 19... Be7 20. e5 Nd5 21. Bxe7 Nxe7 22. Rc7 Nf5 $11 { Black will chase away the rook on c7 with Qb6 at some point, and then Black will be completely fine. } ) 18... Rd4 19. Bg5 Rxc4 20. Bxf6 Rxc3 $1 { This move is a must, otherwise, Black is getting checkmated. } 21. Rxc3 ( 21. bxc3 Qb6 $13 { [%cal Gb6b1] } ) 21... Bxf2+ 22. Kh1 ( 22. Qxf2 Qxf2+ 23. Kxf2 gxf6 24. Nd7 f5 $11 ) 22... Bxe4 { Everything is equal according to the engines, albeit the position remains sharp. } ( 22... Qd4 $5 { Is also possible. } ) 23. Qxe4 ( 23. Bxg7 Bd4 { A good inbetween move. } 24. Bf6 ( 24. Rc4 Kxg7 25. Qxe4 Bxb2 $11 { The dark-squared bishop is controlling the important a1-h8 diagonal, so Black is fine. } ) 24... Bxc3 25. Qxe4 Bxe5 26. Qxe5 Kf8 27. Qd6+ Ke8 28. Qc6+ { White has nothing better than making a draw. } 28... Kf8 29. Qd6+ $11 ) 23... gxf6 24. Nxf7 ( 24. Nc6 Qd7 25. Qg4+ Kh8 26. Qf3 Qd2 27. Qxf6+ Kg8 28. g3 Qe2 { The checkmate threat of Qf1 forces White to make a repetition. } 29. Qg5+ $11 ) 24... Rf8 $1 25. Nh6+ Kh8 26. Qxe6 Qd4 27. Qe2 ( 27. g3 Qe5 { The endgame is also equal. } ) 27... Qf4 $11 ) ( 13. Nc3 Nb4 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Bd7 16. Ra1 Bb5 17. Qe1 Rab8 $11 { Black's pieces are quite active, although the position remains approximately balanced. } ) 13... Be7 { Stepping away from the upcoming pin along the c-file. } 14. Rc1 $14 ( 14. Bc3 h6 $5 ( 14... Nd5 { This might be playable for Black, although the position can be slightly unpleasant. } 15. Be4 Rd8 16. Bxd5 Rxd5 17. Rxd5 exd5 $11 ) ( 14... a5 $5 { This is equal according to the engines but it leads to a complicated position. } 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Qc2 h6 17. Bb5 Bb7 18. Rc4 Rfc8 19. Rc1 Qd8 20. Bxc6 Bxc6 21. Rxc6 Rxc6 22. Qxc6 Bxb2 23. Rf1 a4 { [%csl Gb2][%cal Ga4a3] Black sacrificed a piece but the a-pawn is very quick and is supported by the rest of the army. } 24. Qc2 a3 25. Nbd2 Qb8 { [%cal Ga3a2] } 26. Nb3 ( 26. Rb1 Qb4 { [%cal Ga3a2] } ) 26... Qb7 27. Nfd2 Rc8 28. Qb1 Qd5 $44 { [%csl Ga3,Gb2] White's pieces are stuck while the a-pawn is very strong, so the position is balanced. } ) 15. Bxa6 ( 15. Rc4 Bb7 16. Ne5 Rfd8 $11 ) 15... Qb6 16. Bb5 Rxa4 17. Bxa4 Ba6 18. Qe1 Nd5 $11 { 1/2 (18) Kezin,R (2514) -Popov,I (2627) Sochi 2023 Black is down a pawn but intends to capture the bishop on c3 and have a strong bishop pair, while Rb8 is also a move to consider. Black doesn't have any problems in this position. } ) ( 14. Bxa6 Qb6 15. Bb5 Rxa4 16. Bxa4 Ba6 17. Qe1 Nb4 { Intending Nd3 next. } 18. Bxb4 Bxb4 19. Nc3 Rc8 $11 { By having the bishop pair and more active pieces, Black isn't in any danger. } ) 14... Qb6 15. e4 ( 15. Na3 { [%cal Ga3c4] } 15... Bd7 16. Nc4 Qb7 $11 { Nb4 can be considered next. } ) 15... Bb7 16. e5 Nd7 $1 { Keeping an eye on the e5-pawn and intending Nc5 next. } 17. Rg4 g6 18. Na3 { [%cal Ga3c4] } 18... Nb4 $1 19. Nc4 Qb5 $1 20. Bxb4 ( 20. Be4 Bxe4 21. Qxe4 Rfc8 $11 ) 20... Qxb4 21. h4 Nc5 22. h5 Nxd3 23. Qxd3 Rad8 24. Qe3 Bxf3 25. Qxf3 Qc5 $11 { Black has enough defensive resources in this position with Qd5 being one idea to try to exchange the queens, while the constant pressure on the e5-pawn is also unpleasant for White. } *

