1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 a6 { In the lesson we focus on rare 8th move options for White in the main line of 7.Nc3 a6. } 8. Re1 ( 8. Ne5 Nxe5 ( 8... Qc7 { Also possible,but a bit passive is } 9. Nxc6 Qxc6 { ˝-˝ (34) Aronian,L (2781) -Caruana,F (2820) Bucharest 2021 } ) 9. dxe5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Nd7 11. f4 b5 12. Be2 ( 12. Bd3 Bb7 { Black already has the easier game. } 13. Be4 $6 O-O-O 14. Bxb7+ Kxb7 15. Ne4 Be7 16. Bd2 Nb6 $15 { 1/2 (57) Medina,S (2137) -Haitshandiet,M San Antonio de Padua 2001 } ) 12... Bb7 13. a4 { With the knight on c3 and not on b1, this classical pawn break loses a tempo for White, but there is still no better choice. } 13... b4 14. Nb1 O-O-O 15. Nd2 Kc7 ( 15... Be7 16. Nc4 f6 $11 ) 16. b3 Nb6 $11 { With an equal position. } ) ( 8. Bd3 $5 { Maybe a bit more accurate move order than 8.Re1 } 8... cxd4 9. exd4 Be7 10. Bg5 ( { The other option are transposing to 8.Re1. } 10. a3 O-O ) ( 10. Re1 O-O 11. a3 ) 10... O-O 11. Rc1 $5 { An interesting independent continuation. One idea is tuck the bishop back on b1 with the rook already developed and build a battery. Another idea is to create some discovered attack possibilities against the c6-knight in the case Black's b-pawn leaves its defence. } ( 11. Re1 { Transposes to 8.Re1. } ) 11... h6 12. Bf4 ( 12. Bh4 Qb6 $5 ( { Typical is } 12... Nh5 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Ne5 Nf6 15. Ne4 Nfd5 16. Bb1 b6 17. Qd3 a5 { [%cal Gc8a6] } 18. Nc3 Nf5 19. Nc6 Nb4 $11 ) 13. Qd2 ( 13. Na4 Qa7 { The queen needs to kepp attacking the d4-pawn from afar. } 14. Ne5 Nxd4 15. Ng4 Nd5 $1 { White has a knight sacrifice that leads to bojective equality: } 16. Nxh6+ gxh6 17. Qg4+ ( 17. Bxe7 Nxe7 18. Qg4+ Kh8 19. Rc7 Nef5 20. Qf4 e5 $1 { Giving up a pawn to liberate the bishop. } 21. Qxe5+ Kg8 22. Rfc1 Ng7 $13 { White still has to porve his compensation. } ) 17... Bg5 $1 18. Bxg5 f5 { With a forced perpetual check: } 19. Qh5 hxg5 20. Qg6+ Kh8 21. Qh6+ $11 ) 13... Rd8 14. Rfd1 Bd7 15. d5 Nb4 $1 16. d6 { This is the resource White counts on. Otherwise his play doesn't make much sense. } 16... Qxd6 17. Bxf6 gxf6 { Forced in view of 17...Bxf6?? 18.Bh7+! But White doesn't gain more than a possiblity of forcing a draw soon as a result of spoiling the structure. } 18. Qe3 Kg7 19. Bb1 Qc5 20. Qf4 Be8 { It's hard to find something better for White than the following repetition: } 21. Qg3+ Kh8 22. Qh4 Kg7 $11 ) 12... b5 $5 ( 12... Bd6 13. Be5 Bxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. Re1 Nc5 16. Re3 Nb4 17. Bb1 Qxd1+ 18. Rxd1 $14 { 1-0 (64) Ding,L (2812) -Wei,Y (2737) China 2019 } ) 13. Qd2 { [%cal Gf4h6] Introducing the aggressive Bxh6 idea. } ( 13. Nxb5 { We are not afriad of this tactic as we get fantastic control over the central squares and the long diagonal in return for the pawn. Besides, a2 starts hanging and it's hard for White to even hold his material edge. } 13... axb5 14. Rxc6 Bb7 { [%cal Ga8a2] } 15. Rc7 Bd5 $13 ) ( 13. Ne4 Nxd4 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Be4 Ra7 $13 { Equal, but it should be quite pleasant playing a pawn up. } ) ( 13. Bb1 Bb7 14. Re1 Re8 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Rc8 $11 ) 13... Bb7 14. Bxh6 ( 14. Rfd1 Re8 $13 { [%cal Ge7f8] } ) 14... Nxd4 $1 15. Nxd4 ( 15. Bxg7 Nxf3+ 16. gxf3 Nh7 $1 { An extremely important resource. } 17. Bxh7+ Kxg7 18. Qxd8 Raxd8 19. Be4 Bc8 $44 { [%csl Gc8,Ge7] We retain the bishop pair easily get full compensation. } ) 15... gxh6 16. Rfd1 ( 16. Qxh6 { This leads to a perpetual: } 16... Qxd4 17. Qg5+ Kh8 18. Qh6+ $11 ) 16... Kg7 17. Qe3 ( 17. Bf5 { Both sides need to make a couple of only moves here: } 17... e5 $1 18. Qe3 exd4 19. Rxd4 Qe8 20. Ne2 $1 Rg8 $1 21. Rc7 Bf8 22. Rxb7 Qxe3 23. fxe3 Bc5 24. Rd3 Rge8 $11 { White cannot defend the e3-pawn. } ) 17... Qb8 $1 18. Nf5+ { A natural tactical exchange. } ( 18. Nce2 Bd6 19. g3 Rc8 $11 { The king is already quite safe. } ) 18... exf5 19. Qxe7 { Black consolidates with a few natural moves: } 19... Re8 20. Qc5 Ng4 21. Qd4+ ( 21. g3 Qe5 $11 ) 21... Kg8 22. g3 Qe5 23. Be2 Rad8 24. Qxe5 Nxe5 $11 { 1/2 (32) Budding,A (2241) -Szulc,S (2247) ICCF email 2023 } ) ( 8. Bb3 b5 9. d5 $5 ( 9. a4 $6 { Dubious. } 9... b4 10. Ne2 Na5 $1 11. Bc2 Bb7 $15 { The knight is passive on e2. } ) ( 9. dxc5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Bxc5 11. Bd2 Bb7 12. Rac1 Be7 13. Ne2 { Bringing the knight to d4 is the only challenging idea. } 13... O-O 14. Ned4 { 1-0 (54) Grischuk,A (2745) -So,W (2773) Chess.com INT 2022 } 14... Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Ne4 $1 { This tactical solution to Black's problems works well. } ( 15... Rfc8 16. f3 $14 { White will establish a pawn on e4, blocking Black's light-squared bishop in a typical fashion. Black needs to be careful not to run into a worse endgame like this. } ) 16. Rc7 ( 16. Nc6 { This is just completely equal. } 16... Bxc6 17. Rxc6 Nxd2 18. Rxd2 a5 $11 ) 16... Nxd2 17. Bxe6 $1 { The critical choice. } ( 17. Rxb7 Nxb3 18. Nxb3 Bf6 $11 ) ( 17. Rxe7 Nxb3 18. Rxb7 Nxd4 19. Rxd4 { The apparent activity of White's rooks can be easily neutralized: } 19... Rfd8 20. Ra7 Kf8 $11 ) ( 17. Nxe6 $6 Nxb3 18. Nxf8 Kxf8 19. Rxb7 Nc5 $15 { The minor pieces are a bit stronger here. } ) ( 17. Rxd2 Bb4 18. Rd1 Rab8 $11 ) 17... Bb4 $1 ( 17... fxe6 18. Rxe7 ) 18. Rxb7 ( 18. a3 Ba5 ) 18... fxe6 19. a3 Ba5 20. Nc6 ( 20. b4 Nc4 21. bxa5 Rf7 22. Rxf7 Kxf7 23. Nc6 Ke8 $11 ) 20... Rad8 21. Nxd8 Rxd8 { The endgame remains complex, but equal, e.g. } 22. Kh1 { Stepping out of ...Nf3+! } 22... Kf8 { Preparing ...Nc4. } 23. Ra7 Nc4 24. Rxd8+ Bxd8 25. Rxa6 Nxb2 26. Ra8 Ke7 27. Rb8 Nc4 28. Rxb5 Nxa3 { After the pawn liquidation on the queenside, a draw is likely. } 29. Rb4 e5 30. g3 Ke6 31. Kg2 Be7 $11 ) ( 9. Qe2 { Transpose to the next lessons. } ) 9... exd5 10. a4 ( 10. Nxd5 $6 c4 $15 ) ( 10. Bxd5 Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Qxd5 12. Nxd5 Bd6 $11 ) 10... Bb7 $14 { Returning the pawn in order to develop quickly. } ( { Also good but very sharp is } 10... Nb4 11. axb5 Be7 12. e4 c4 13. e5 Nd7 14. Bc2 Nc5 15. Nd4 O-O $13 ) 11. axb5 axb5 12. Rxa8 Bxa8 13. Nxb5 Be7 14. Bxd5 { This tactic wins White a pawn, but weakens his light squares and now Black gets the compensation. } 14... Nxd5 15. Qxd5 Qb8 ( 15... Qxd5 16. Nc7+ Kd7 17. Nxd5 Nb4 { Also looks drawish. } ) 16. Rd1 O-O 17. Qc4 ( 17. Nc3 Nd4 18. Qh5 g6 19. Qh3 Nb3 $13 ) 17... Na5 18. Qe2 Bc6 19. Nc3 Nb3 { The direct path. } ( 19... Re8 { Also looks good } ) 20. Qc2 Nxc1 21. Qxc1 Qa8 22. Ne1 Rb8 $44 { [%csl Gc6,Ge7][%cal Ge7f6] Black is practically out of danger. It is very hard for White to play for a win despite him being a pawn up. } ) 8... Be7 ( 8... b5 $5 { In this move order is interesting } 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. a4 b4 11. Ne4 Na5 ) 9. Bd3 ( 9. dxc5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Bxc5 { Transposes to the next lessons. } ) 9... cxd4 ( 9... O-O 10. dxc5 $1 Bxc5 ( 10... Nb4 $5 ) 11. a3 Bd6 12. Ne4 $14 { 1-0 (32) Oparin,G (2667) -Niemann,H (2708) Sharjah 2023 } ) 10. exd4 O-O 11. Ne5 $5 ( 11. Bg5 h6 ( { Another decent idea is } 11... b5 ) 12. Bf4 ( 12. Bh4 b5 13. a4 ( 13. a3 Ra7 $5 { [%cal Ga7d7] } 14. Rc1 Rd7 15. Bb1 Bb7 $13 ) 13... Bb7 $5 { The most convincing choice. We give up the pawn but get our pieces on excellent squares. } ( 13... b4 14. Ne4 Bb7 $11 ) 14. axb5 axb5 15. Rxa8 Qxa8 16. Bxb5 Rd8 $44 { The b2 and d4 pawns are long-term weaknesses. In addition Black can exert an annoying pressure with the queen and bishop battery. The compensation is fully sufficient. } ) ( 12. Be3 b5 13. Qd2 { [%cal Ge3h6] } 13... Re8 $13 { [%cal Gc8b7,Ge7f8] Preventing Bxh6! We plan to go ...Bb7, ...Bf8, ...Rc8 and then, once we've mobilized all the forces, ...b4 or ...Nb4. } ) 12... Bd6 ( 12... b5 $5 { This move leads to more risky lines, but objectively fully holds the position. } 13. Qd2 Re8 $1 { Preparing for Bxh6. } 14. d5 ( 14. Rad1 Bf8 15. Bb1 Bb7 16. a3 Rc8 $13 ) ( 14. Bxh6 $2 gxh6 15. Qxh6 Bf8 $19 ) 14... Nxd5 15. Nxd5 ( 15. Bxh6 Ndb4 $1 ) 15... exd5 ( 15... Qxd5 16. Qe3 f5 17. Rac1 Rd8 $13 ) 16. Bxh6 Be6 $1 17. Bxg7 ( 17. Bg5 Nd4 ) ( 17. Rac1 Bb4 18. Qf4 Bxe1 19. Rxc6 Rc8 20. Rxa6 gxh6 21. Qxh6 Qc7 22. Qh7+ Kf8 23. Qh8+ Ke7 24. Qh4+ Kf8 $11 ) 17... Kxg7 18. Qc3+ d4 19. Qxc6 Bd5 20. Qc1 Bxf3 21. gxf3 Qd6 $11 ) 13. Be5 b5 $1 14. Bxf6 ( 14. Qe2 Bb7 15. Rad1 Nb4 $1 { A pretty universal maneuver in the IQP positions. } 16. Bb1 Nbd5 17. Ne4 Nxe4 18. Qxe4 f5 19. Qe2 Re8 $11 { White has the e5-square control, but Black has the d5-outpost plus a strong bishop on the long diagonal. White doesn't have enough attacking chances to be better. } ) ( 14. a4 bxa4 ( 14... Bb7 $5 15. axb5 axb5 16. Rxa8 Bxa8 17. Bxb5 Ne7 $44 ) 15. Bxf6 ( 15. Rxa4 Nb4 16. Bb1 Bb7 $11 ) 15... Qxf6 16. Be4 Bd7 17. d5 exd5 18. Nxd5 Qd8 19. Rxa4 Re8 $11 ) 14... Qxf6 { The main idea for White is to break through with d5, but Black is fine in all versions of that. } 15. Be4 ( 15. d5 exd5 16. Nxd5 Qd8 17. Bb1 { [%cal Gd1d3] } 17... Nb4 18. Ne3 Be6 19. Nd4 Bc5 20. Nxe6 fxe6 $11 { Black's bishop is to strong for the second player to be worse because of the pawn structure. } ) ( 15. Bc2 { [%cal Gd1d3] } 15... Bb7 16. d5 ( 16. Ne4 Qe7 17. Qd3 g6 18. Qe3 Kg7 $11 ) 16... Nb4 17. Ne4 Qe7 18. dxe6 fxe6 { White's bishop is hanging after taking on d6. } 19. Bb3 Rad8 20. Nxd6 Bxf3 21. gxf3 Rxd6 22. Qxd6 { A necessary tactic. } 22... Qxd6 23. Rxe6 Qd3 24. Rd6+ Kh8 25. Rxd3 Nxd3 $11 ) 15... Bb7 16. d5 exd5 17. Nxd5 ( 17. Bxd5 Rad8 ( 17... Bb4 $5 ) 18. Ne4 { 1/2 (31) Gelfand,B (2675) -Dominguez Perez,L (2758) Chess.com INT 2021 } 18... Qe7 $11 ) 17... Qd8 { White is active, but doesn't have many threats. } ( 17... Qxb2 $2 18. Re2 Qa3 19. Re3 Qc5 20. Rc1 Qa7 21. Nf6+ $18 ) 18. Qd3 Re8 19. Rad1 Rb8 $11 { We should be able to exchange some pieces and neutralize White's activity soon. } ) ( 11. a3 b5 $1 12. Bc2 ( 12. Bb1 Bb7 13. Qd3 g6 $13 ) 12... Bb7 13. Qd3 g6 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Rad1 { A typical IQP setup. Black is fine based on ...b4 and ...Bf8 ideas. } 15... Rc8 ( 15... b4 $5 ) 16. Qe2 ( 16. Bb1 b4 ) 16... Bf8 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 $13 ) ( 11. Bf4 { The bishop doesn't belong here. } 11... b5 $13 { [%cal Gc8b7] } ) 11... Nxd4 { Accepting the pawn sacrifice. } ( 11... Bd7 $5 { According to engines it is also good. } 12. Re3 ( 12. Be3 Nb4 13. Bc4 Bc6 14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. d5 Na5 16. Be2 exd5 17. Bf3 Bb4 18. Bd4 Nc6 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 20. Nxd5 Qd6 $11 ) 12... g6 13. Rh3 Be8 14. Bh6 ( 14. Bf1 $5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Qxd1 16. Nxd1 Ng4 17. Rg3 h5 18. h3 Nxe5 19. Bh6 Bf6 20. Bxf8 Kxf8 $44 ) 14... Qxd4 15. Bxf8 Bxf8 16. Nxc6 Bxc6 17. Be2 { 1-0 (56) Matlakov,M (2670) -Wang,Y (2659) Qingdao 2023 } 17... e5 $1 { Keeping both bishops on the board, because there is ...e4 against Bf3 in most lines now: } 18. Bf3 Qxd1+ 19. Rxd1 e4 20. Be2 Re8 $44 { [%csl Gc6,Gf8][%cal Gf8c5] } ) 12. Bf4 ( 12. Bg5 Nc6 $13 ) 12... Nc6 $14 ( 12... Nf5 { 1/2 (39) Mamedyarov,S (2782) -Dominguez Perez,L (2758) Saint Louis 2021 } ) 13. Qf3 Bd7 14. Rad1 ( 14. Qh3 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 h6 16. Re3 { [%cal Ge3g3] } ( 16. Rad1 Qa5 ( 16... Bc6 $5 { It is a viable option to sacrifice the queen. } 17. Bh7+ Kxh7 18. Rxd8 Raxd8 $44 ) 17. g4 { [%cal Gg4g5] } 17... Ne8 $1 18. Bh7+ Kxh7 19. Qd3+ Kg8 20. Qxd7 Bh4 21. Qxb7 Nf6 $11 ) 16... Bc6 17. Rg3 ( { Similar is } 17. Rd1 Kh8 ) 17... Kh8 { White has a few attacking options, but all of them ultimately lead only to a draw. } 18. Rd1 ( 18. Rxg7 Kxg7 19. Qg3+ Kh8 20. Qh3 Kg7 $11 ) ( 18. Qh4 Bd6 19. Rxg7 Kxg7 20. Qg3+ Kh8 21. Qf4 Bxe5 22. Qxh6+ Kg8 23. Qg5+ $11 ) 18... Bd6 ( 18... Qa5 $5 ) 19. Rxg7 Kxg7 20. Qg4+ Kh8 21. Qf4 Bxe5 22. Qxh6+ Kg8 23. Qg5+ Kh8 $11 ) 14... Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Qb6 { Of course the position is dangerous with all of White's pieces directed against Black's king like this, but if he have this position prepared and now what to do, this dimishes the chances of things going wrong very significantly. } 16. Ne4 ( 16. Bd4 Qc7 17. Be5 $11 ( 17. Qh3 h6 ) ) ( 16. Bxf6 { This is just a bailout to an immediately equal position. } 16... Bxf6 17. Bxh7+ Kxh7 18. Rxd7 Qxb2 19. Ne4 b5 20. Nxf6+ Qxf6 21. Qxf6 gxf6 22. Rxe6 Rad8 $11 ) ( 16. Qh3 $5 h6 17. Re3 ( 17. g4 Ne8 $1 18. Bf4 Nf6 19. Bxh6 ( 19. Be5 Ne8 $11 ) 19... gxh6 20. g5 { Black has a good method of simplification against this attack: } 20... e5 $1 21. Qxh6 Qxf2+ $1 22. Kxf2 Ng4+ 23. Kf3 Nxh6 24. gxh6 Kh8 25. Rxe5 Bf6 26. Rh5 Rad8 $44 { Black is now a pawn down, but the bishop pair guarantees him equal chances. } ) 17... Rfd8 $1 18. Rg3 Kf8 $1 { The king escapes. } 19. Rxg7 { White continues attacking fiercely. } ( 19. Ne4 Qa5 20. Rxg7 Qxe5 21. Rg5 Qxg5 22. Nxg5 hxg5 23. Qh6+ Kg8 24. Qxg5+ Kf8 $11 ) 19... Kxg7 20. Ne4 Ba4 $1 { The only move! Some tempo play is required. } 21. b3 ( 21. Nxf6 Bxf6 22. Bxf6+ Kxf6 23. Qxh6+ Ke7 24. Qh4+ Kf8 $11 ) ( 21. Qh4 Bxd1 22. Nxf6 Rxd3 23. Nd5+ Kh7 24. Nf6+ Kg7 $11 ) 21... Rxd3 $1 22. Rxd3 ( 22. Qxd3 Rd8 23. Qf3 Rxd1+ 24. Qxd1 Qb4 25. Nxf6 Bxf6 26. Bxf6+ Kxf6 27. bxa4 $11 ) 22... Qb4 $1 23. Qe3 ( 23. Rg3+ Kf8 24. Qxh6+ Ke8 25. Nc3 Nd7 26. bxa4 Nxe5 27. Qh8+ Bf8 28. Qxe5 Rc8 $44 { The game can easily become dangerous for White as well. } ) 23... Bc6 24. Rd4 ( 24. Nxf6 { Just a way to force a draw. } 24... Bxf6 25. Rd4 Qe7 26. Rg4+ Kh7 27. Qd3+ Kh8 28. Qd2 Kh7 $11 ) 24... Rd8 $1 { Using the back rank weakness. } 25. Nxf6 Rxd4 26. Qg3+ ( 26. Nh5+ Kg6 $11 ) 26... Rg4 $1 27. Nxg4+ Kh7 { Finally we get a bit calmer, balanced position, where Black's bishop pair is offset by White's greater king shelter. A liquidation can easily occur, e.g. } 28. h3 ( 28. Qd3+ f5 ) 28... Qe4 29. Nxh6 ( 29. f3 Qg6 $11 ) 29... Qxg2+ 30. Qxg2 Bxg2 31. Nf5 ( 31. Nxf7 Bxh3 $11 ) 31... exf5 32. Kxg2 Kg6 33. Kf3 Kg5 $11 ) 16... Nd5 17. Bc2 ( 17. Nc3 Nf6 $11 ) ( 17. Qh5 h6 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qg4+ Kh8 20. Qh5 Kg7 $11 ) ( 17. Bc4 f6 18. Bd4 Qc6 19. Bb3 Kh8 20. Rc1 Qb5 21. Nc5 Bxc5 22. Rxc5 Qb4 23. Qd1 b6 24. Rc4 Qe7 $11 ) 17... Bc6 ( 17... Rad8 { Also good } ) 18. Qg4 ( 18. Qh5 f5 19. Ng5 Bxg5 20. Qxg5 Rf7 $11 { White has a definite compensation, but Black is fine. It is hard for either side to make progress } ) ( 18. Qg3 f6 $11 ) 18... g6 19. Qh3 { Stepping out of ...f5 apart from pressing on the h-file. } ( 19. Bb3 { This is a path to some tactical simplifications: } 19... f5 20. Qh3 fxe4 21. Qxe6+ Rf7 22. Rf1 Ba4 $1 23. Bxd5 Qxe6 24. Bxe6 Bxd1 25. Rxd1 Rd8 $11 ) 19... Rfd8 20. Rd3 { [%cal Gh3h7] } 20... h5 { Remember not to blunder the thematic Qxh7+! } 21. Rg3 Kf8 { The king is ready to escape all the way to the queenside if White allows it. Remember that all this time Black is playing a pawn up, which is the price White pays for his attacking possibilities. } 22. Rf3 Qa5 23. Nc3 { This is a way to finally initiate a direct tactical skirmish. White doesn't gain much from maneuvering anymore. } ( 23. Rf1 Ke8 $13 ) 23... Nxc3 24. Rxf7+ Kxf7 25. Bxg6+ Kf8 $1 { The only move. } 26. Qxh5 { Black is not getting mated, as a few tactical shots allow him to return some material end exchange the queens. } ( 26. Qxe6 Ne2+ $1 27. Kf1 Bxg2+ 28. Kxg2 Qd5+ 29. Qxd5 Rxd5 30. Rxe2 $11 { This is similar in character to our main line. } ) 26... Ne2+ 27. Kf1 Bxg2+ 28. Kxg2 Nf4+ 29. Bxf4 Qxh5 30. Bxh5 Rd4 31. Bh6+ Kg8 32. Rxe6 Rd6 $11 { Materially and positionally, the resulting endgame is quite balanced. } *

