1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 a6 8. a4 { One of the mainstream playable moves. } 8... Be7 { It's better to keep the tension in the centre rather than give White a realtively good IQP with 8...cxd4. } 9. Qe2 ( 9. dxc5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Bxc5 { The queen exchange with the pawns on a4 and a6 is not so great for White, as the b4-square ends up weakened. } 11. Bd2 ( 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 Be7 13. Be2 ( 13. Rac1 Na5 $1 14. Ne5 Rd8 15. Rxd8+ Bxd8 16. Rd1 Bc7 $11 ) 13... Rd8 ( 13... h6 { Also good } ) 14. Rxd8+ Bxd8 15. Rd1 ( 15. Nd2 Be7 16. Nc4 Bd7 17. Nb6 Rd8 $11 ) 15... Be7 16. Nb1 Nd5 17. Kf1 f6 18. Nd4 Bd7 $11 { 1/2 (20) Ozen,B (2294) -Swiatek,J (2101) FICGS email 2022 } ) 11... b6 ( 11... Ke7 $5 { An interesting novelty. Black keeps the king in the centre. } 12. a5 ( 12. Rac1 Rd8 ) ( 12. e4 Ng4 ) 12... Bb4 13. Na4 Bxd2 14. Nxd2 Rd8 15. Be2 Rb8 $11 ) 12. Bd3 ( 12. Rac1 Bb7 ) ( 12. Ng5 Bb7 13. Nce4 Be7 $11 ) 12... Bb7 13. Ne4 Be7 14. Bc3 O-O 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Be2 ( 17. Be4 f5 $11 ) 17... Rfd8 $11 { We are not afraid of this pawn structure. We put the king on e7n and the other rook on c8 with an extremely solid position. } ) ( 9. d5 { This break only leads to some liquidation, but cannot promise White any advantage or good winning chances. } 9... exd5 10. Nxd5 O-O ( 10... Na5 $5 ) 11. e4 Bg4 { Typical resource. The pin with ...Ne5 and ...Nd4 ideas suggests itself. } 12. h3 ( 12. Bf4 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Nd4 $11 ) 12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Ne5 14. Qe2 Nxc4 15. Qxc4 Nxd5 16. exd5 b5 $11 { The situation is drawish. } ) 9... O-O ( 9... cxd4 $5 { This is an idea of going for exchanges and forcing the way to a pretty dry equality. The main recommendation retain more winning chances. } 10. Rd1 e5 ( 10... O-O 11. exd4 { Big theory } ) 11. exd4 exd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qe5 Qd6 14. Qxd6 Bxd6 15. Rxd4 Bc5 16. Rd1 ( 16. Rf4 O-O 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Rb8 19. Rc4 Bd6 20. Bf4 Rd8 21. Rd1 b5 22. Bxd6 bxc4 23. Bxb8 Be6 $11 ) 16... Be6 17. Bxe6 fxe6 18. Bg5 Rc8 $11 ) 10. dxc5 ( 10. Rd1 Qc7 11. d5 ( 11. h3 Rd8 $11 ) ( 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. b3 b6 13. Bb2 Bb7 $11 ) 11... exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Rd8 { With a simple tactical idea of meeting Qc4 by ...Be6! } 14. Qc4 Be6 15. e4 Nb4 $11 ) 10... Qc7 $5 { A little bit more tricky than recapturing on c5. Black sometimes gets ...Ng4 ideas. } ( 10... Bxc5 11. e4 e5 { Also looks fine. } ) 11. b3 ( 11. e4 Ng4 $1 12. g3 ( 12. e5 Ngxe5 13. Bf4 Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 Qa5 15. Ne4 Bxc5 { White has compensation sufficient only for a draw. } 16. Nf6+ ( 16. Rad1 $6 Be7 $15 ) 16... gxf6 ( 16... Kh8 $5 ) 17. Bh6 Ne7 $1 18. Qxf6 Nf5 19. Qg5+ Kh8 20. Qf6+ $11 ) 12... Bxc5 13. Bf4 { We can block with the bishop or the pawn, having no problems in any case. } 13... e5 ( 13... Bd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Rfd1 Qc7 $11 ) 14. Nd5 Qd6 15. Bd2 Nf6 16. Be3 Bxe3 17. Qxe3 Bg4 $11 ) ( 11. Bd2 Bxc5 12. Rac1 b6 13. Bd3 Bb7 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Qe7 $11 { This is just a simple equality. } ) ( 11. Bd3 Bxc5 12. Bd2 Rd8 13. Rac1 Be7 14. Ne4 Qb6 $11 { Creating an annoyance in the b2 and b3 points. } ) 11... Na5 $5 ( 11... Bxc5 12. Bb2 { Playable, but minimally better for White according to the engines. } ) 12. Nd2 ( 12. e4 Nxc4 13. Qxc4 Qxc5 14. Qxc5 Bxc5 15. e5 Nd7 16. Ne4 b6 $11 ) ( 12. b4 Nxc4 13. Qxc4 b6 { White will not be able to hold his material very long. } 14. Ba3 ( 14. e4 bxc5 15. Bg5 Bb7 $11 ) 14... Bb7 $44 ) 12... Nxc4 13. Nxc4 ( 13. Qxc4 Qxc5 14. Ba3 Qxc4 15. Nxc4 Bxa3 16. Rxa3 Bd7 $11 { The endgame is close to a draw. } ) 13... Bxc5 { Black has the bishop pair. Whit gets a clear-cut a4-a5 and Na4-b6 idea, and a logical continuation includes Black trading his light-squared bishop for the knight appearing on a4 and a complete balance ensuing. } 14. a5 Bd7 15. Bb2 Rad8 16. Na4 ( 16. Rfc1 Be7 $11 ) 16... Bxa4 17. Rxa4 Nd5 $11 *[Event "?"]
