1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 a6 8. a3 { White doesn't stop ...b5, but makes a useful move in anticipation of it. } 8... b5 9. Ba2 ( 9. Bd3 Bb7 ( 9... cxd4 $5 10. exd4 Be7 ) 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. b4 Bd6 12. Ne4 { ˝-˝ (33) Jobava,B (2603) -Xiong,J (2709) lichess.org INT 2020 } ( 12. Bb2 { If White doesn't go for Ne4, Black can play the same idea with good results himself: } 12... Ne5 $1 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. f4 Bc7 15. a4 { White undermines the queenside pawn, but Black can simply give up a pawn and make use of the weakened kingside structure in White's camp. } 15... O-O 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rxa8 ( 17. Nxb5 Bb6 18. Qe2 Rxa1 19. Rxa1 Nd5 { White already needs to make a draw now: } 20. Bxh7+ Kxh7 21. Qh5+ Kg8 22. Bxg7 Bxe3+ 23. Kh1 Kxg7 24. Qg4+ $11 ) 17... Qxa8 18. Qe2 ( 18. Nxb5 Bb6 19. Qe2 Nd5 $11 ) 18... Bd6 { Now we can hit White's b-pawn. } 19. Nxb5 Bxb4 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Qg4+ Kh8 22. Qh4 f5 $11 { There's only a perpatual check available to White. } ) 12... Nxe4 ( 12... Be7 { Also fine } ) 13. Bxe4 f5 $1 14. Bxc6+ Bxc6 15. Bb2 O-O { Black equalizes easily. His bishop pair offsets White's dark-square control. There is a possiblity of an equal opposite-coloured bishops position arising. } 16. Be5 ( 16. Qd4 Qe7 17. Ne5 Bd5 $11 ) ( 16. Rc1 Bd5 $11 ) 16... Bxf3 ( 16... Be7 $11 ) 17. Qxd6 Bd5 18. Qxd8 Rfxd8 $11 { 1/2 (30) Bachmann,A (2648) -Ragger,M (2656) Linares 2017 } ) 9... Bb7 10. Qe2 ( 10. d5 { This push creates no problems for Black. } 10... exd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 Bd6 13. e4 ( 13. b4 O-O 14. Bb2 c4 15. e4 Qc7 $13 { Black can become better in the future thanks to the protected passed pawn. } ) 13... O-O $11 { 0-1 (42) Sargissian,G (2682) -Praggnanandhaa,R (2608) Krasnaya Polyana RUS 2021 } ) 10... Be7 ( { Other perfectly playable options are: } 10... Qc7 ) ( 10... cxd4 11. Rd1 b4 ) ( 10... Bd6 ) 11. Rd1 ( 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. b4 Bd6 13. Bb2 ( 13. Rd1 Qb8 ) 13... O-O 14. Nd2 { With the idea to bring a knight to e4. But Black euqalizes with simple moves: } 14... Ne5 { Stopping Ne4. } 15. f4 Ng6 16. Rad1 Qe7 17. Bb1 Bc7 18. Nce4 Nxe4 19. Nxe4 Bb6 $11 { Black is very solid and White's kingside structure is a bit overexposed as a result of f4. } ) 11... Qb8 $14 { A nice improvement } ( 11... Qc7 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. b4 Bd6 14. Bb2 Rd8 15. Rac1 Qb8 { Also fine, but a bit preferable for White. } ) 12. d5 { The most challenging option. } ( 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. b4 Bd6 { We are not losing time on ...Qc7 and ...Qb8 later like in the 11...Qc7 line. } 14. Bb2 O-O 15. Rac1 Ne5 $11 { Black is doing great. } ) ( 12. Bd2 O-O 13. Rac1 b4 $13 ) 12... exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 O-O 15. e4 h6 16. Be3 Qc7 { [%cal Ga8d8] The most natural move, intending to keep protecting the f7-pawn with the kingside rook and put the queenside rook on d8. } ( 16... Rd8 $5 { This way of playing in fact also turns out to be fine. } 17. Rac1 ( 17. Nh4 $5 Bxh4 18. Qh5 Ne5 19. Qxh4 Bxd5 20. exd5 c4 21. Bf4 g5 22. Qg3 Nf3+ 23. Qxf3 Qxf4 24. Qxf4 gxf4 $11 ) 17... c4 $11 ) 17. Rac1 ( 17. g3 Rad8 18. Bf4 Qc8 $13 ) 17... Na5 $1 { Black inititates the exchange of the annoying bishop on d5 and makes use of the b3-square available to the knight in some lines. } ( 17... c4 $6 18. b3 $1 Bxa3 19. Ra1 Be7 20. bxc4 $14 ) 18. b4 ( 18. Bxb7 Qxb7 19. Rd5 ( 19. Bxc5 $2 Nb3 $19 ) 19... Rad8 $11 ) ( 18. Bxc5 Bxc5 19. b4 Bxd5 20. Rxc5 Bc4 21. Qxc4 Nxc4 22. Rxc7 Rfc8 $11 { [%csl Ra3] We will easily regain the pawn. } ) 18... Bxd5 19. exd5 ( 19. Rxd5 Nb3 { An important resource. The knight can be supported by ...c4. } 20. Rcd1 ( 20. Rc3 $6 c4 21. Bxh6 Rfd8 $15 { Black doesn't have to accept the sacrifice. It is White who faces problems after the exchange of the rook on d5. } ) 20... Rfd8 $11 ) 19... Nc4 20. Rxc4 { An obvious exchange sacrifice. Otherwise Black has a perfect game. } 20... bxc4 21. Qxc4 Rac8 22. Rc1 { The prospect of bxc5 may look scary, but Black makes a straightforward draw by continously attacking the white pawns: } 22... Rfd8 23. bxc5 Qb7 24. Rd1 ( 24. c6 $2 Qb5 25. Qxb5 axb5 26. Bc5 Bf6 $19 { Here White loses the panws and the game. } ) 24... Qc7 25. Rc1 Qb7 $11 *

