1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 a6 8. Qe2 { One of the main moves, leading to some very sharp variations. } 8... b5 9. Bb3 ( 9. Bd3 cxd4 { It is a good concrete option to go for the IQP position here, exploiting the ...Nb4 tempo available. } ( { Also a decent option is } 9... Bb7 10. a4 b4 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Qb6 ) 10. exd4 Nb4 $1 ( 10... Be7 11. Bg5 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Rfd1 $44 { There is a dangerous compensation for White here. } ) 11. Be4 { The critical try. } ( 11. Ne5 { Giving up the bishop in this way cannot pose us problems. } 11... Nxd3 12. Qxd3 Bb7 13. Qg3 Nh5 14. Qh3 Nf6 $11 ) ( 11. Bb1 Be7 12. Rd1 Bb7 13. Ne5 O-O 14. Bg5 ( 14. a4 bxa4 15. Rxa4 Rc8 $13 ) 14... Nbd5 $13 { Black has achieved quite a lot by pushing the bishop back to b1 before the a1-rook had been developed. } ) 11... Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Nd5 13. Nxd5 ( 13. Re1 Bb7 14. Ne5 Bb4 15. Qg4 O-O 16. Bg5 { There are two options to counter White's attack. } ( 16. Bh6 Qf6 ) 16... h5 $5 { Leading to a forced draw in most lines. } ( 16... f5 { The simpler, less forcing choice. } 17. Qg3 Nf6 18. a3 Bd6 $11 ) 17. Qxh5 ( 17. Qg3 f6 18. Bh6 Qc7 $13 ) 17... f6 18. Ng6 ( 18. Qg4 fxg5 19. Qxe6+ Kh7 20. Qh3+ $11 ) 18... Bxc3 19. bxc3 fxg5 20. Qh8+ Kf7 21. Ne5+ Kf6 22. Qh7 ( 22. Ng4+ Kf7 23. Ne5+ $11 ) 22... Nf4 23. g3 ( 23. f3 Rc8 { [%cal Gc8c3] } ) 23... Qd5 24. f3 Rh8 25. Ng4+ Kf7 26. Nh6+ Kf6 $11 ) ( 13. Bg5 f6 { Not a big weakening, as the pawn takes away the e5-square. The king will be pretty safe on f7. } 14. Rfe1 Be7 15. Bd2 Kf7 16. Rac1 Ra7 $11 ) ( 13. Ne5 Bb7 14. Qf3 Qf6 15. Qh5 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Bd6 $13 ) 13... Qxd5 14. Qxd5 exd5 { Black's weak squares are compensated by his bishop pair. The endgame should be roughly equal. } 15. Bf4 Be7 16. Ne5 ( 16. Rfe1 Be6 17. Ne5 f6 18. Nc6 Kf7 19. Rac1 Rhc8 $11 ) 16... O-O ( 16... g5 $5 17. Bd2 f6 18. Nc6 Bd7 ) 17. Nc6 Bf6 18. Be5 Bh4 { Of course we don't want to exchange the bishop and end up with a bad vs. good minor piece position. } 19. g3 Bd8 20. Bd6 Re8 $11 ) 9... Bb7 10. d5 $5 { A combative pawn sacrifice that leads to sharp complications. } ( 10. dxc5 { A straightforward approach that is not so hard to counter. } 10... Bxc5 11. e4 Nd4 $1 { Important, as otherwise White is ready to push e4-e5 and Ne4. } 12. Nxd4 Bxd4 13. e5 ( 13. Rd1 Qb6 $13 ) 13... Nd5 14. Rd1 ( 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Rd1 Bxb3 16. axb3 Qb6 17. Qg4 ( 17. Bd2 O-O 18. Ba5 Qa7 $11 ) 17... Rd8 { A lot of exchanges inevitably lead to a position very close to a draw: } 18. Be3 Bxe3 19. Rxd8+ Kxd8 20. Qxg7 Bxf2+ 21. Kh1 Re8 { There are a few options, but neither of them really threatening for Black. } 22. Qxf7 ( 22. Rd1+ Kc8 23. Qxf7 Rd8 24. Rxd8+ Qxd8 25. Qxf2 Qd1+ 26. Qg1 Qxb3 $11 ) ( 22. Rc1 Bd4 23. Qf6+ Kd7 24. Qxf7+ Re7 25. Qf6 $11 ) 22... Qc5 23. Rd1+ Bd4 24. Qf4 Rf8 25. Qxd4+ Qxd4 26. Rxd4+ Ke7 27. Kg1 Rf5 28. Re4 a5 $11 { White is a pawn up but cannot make progress in this drawn endgame. } ) 14... Bxc3 15. bxc3 O-O 16. Rd3 ( 16. Qg4 Qc7 $13 ) ( 16. c4 Nc3 17. Qg4 h5 $1 { This intermediate move solves all problems. } 18. Qxh5 Nxd1 19. Bc2 g6 20. Bxg6 fxg6 21. Qxg6+ Kh8 22. Qh6+ $11 ) 16... Qh4 $1 { Preventing Qh5 and intending to meet 17.Rh3?! with 17...Nf4! } 17. Bxd5 ( 17. Rg3 { This gives us a chance to put the knight on f4: } 17... Nf4 18. Qe3 Ng6 19. Ba3 Rfd8 20. Bd6 Qf4 21. Qb6 Qe4 22. f3 Qc6 23. Qxc6 Bxc6 $11 ) 17... Bxd5 18. Rd4 Qe7 19. Rg4 ( 19. Qh5 f5 ) 19... Bc4 20. Qf3 f5 { A typical resource that nwutralizes the opponent's kingside pressure. } 21. exf6 Qxf6 22. Qg3 h5 $5 { Not necessary, but interesting. } 23. Rh4 ( 23. Rf4 Rfd8 $11 ) ( 23. Rg6 h4 24. Rxf6 hxg3 25. Rxf8+ Rxf8 26. hxg3 Rd8 $11 ) 23... Qf5 ( 23... Rac8 $5 24. Rxh5 Bd5 25. Bb2 b4 26. Rf1 bxc3 27. Ba1 Rf7 $11 { 1/2 (37) Maceda,C (2244) -Ligon,S (2298) FICGS email 2022 } ) 24. h3 e5 25. Bh6 Rf7 26. Re1 Re8 $11 ) ( 10. Rd1 Be7 $1 { Black does not need to worry about any attacks on the d-file. } 11. d5 ( 11. dxc5 Qc7 12. e4 ( 12. Bd2 O-O 13. Rac1 Ne5 $13 { [%cal Gb7g2] } ) 12... O-O { The simplest choice. } ( 12... Bxc5 { An alternative path with some complications. } 13. e5 ( 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 O-O 15. Rac1 Rad8 $11 ) 13... Ng4 14. Ne4 Ncxe5 15. Bf4 Bxe4 16. Nxe5 ( 16. Qxe4 $6 Qc6 $15 ) 16... Nxf2 17. Rf1 ( 17. Rd7 $6 Qb6 ) 17... Bd3 $1 18. Qf3 Be4 $11 ) 13. e5 ( 13. Be3 Rad8 { Sooner or later we will recapture the c5-pawn. } 14. h3 Na5 $11 ) 13... Nd7 14. Ne4 Nxc5 15. Nd6 Nb4 16. Bf4 Nxb3 17. axb3 Nd5 18. Bg3 Rad8 $11 { The position is dynamically equal. } ) ( 11. a4 $2 Na5 $1 12. Bc2 b4 13. dxc5 Qc7 14. Nb1 O-O $17 ) 11... exd5 12. Nxd5 ( 12. e4 d4 13. e5 O-O $1 { A thematic piece sacrifice that offers Black promising play. } 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Ne4 c4 16. Bc2 ( 16. Bxc4 $6 bxc4 17. Qxc4 { ˝-˝ (41) Bogdanovich,S (2564) -Xu,X (2549) Sanya 2017 } 17... Rc8 $15 ) 16... Be7 17. Be3 d3 18. Bxd3 cxd3 19. Rxd3 Qc7 20. Nc5 Rad8 $11 ) ( 12. Bxd5 Qc7 13. e4 Rd8 14. e5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Qc8 $13 ) 12... Nxd5 13. Bxd5 ( 13. e4 O-O 14. exd5 Na5 15. Bc2 Bf6 $13 ) 13... Qb6 { Black is ready to castle and ultimately exchange the d5-bishop, most probably by ...Nb4. White is unable to pose real problems in the meantime. } 14. e4 ( 14. Ng5 Bxg5 15. Qh5 O-O 16. Qxg5 h6 17. Qg3 Ne7 18. Bxb7 Qxb7 $11 ) ( 14. b3 O-O 15. Ba3 ( 15. Bb2 Nb4 $11 ) 15... Rad8 $11 ) ( 14. Bd2 O-O 15. Bc3 Rad8 $11 ) 14... O-O 15. Be3 ( 15. Bg5 h6 $11 ) 15... Nb4 16. Bxb7 Qxb7 $11 ) 10... exd5 ( 10... Nxd5 $6 11. Rd1 $36 { [%cal Ge3e4] } ) 11. e4 d4 12. e5 Ng4 $1 { Black is fine in this critical position, but it is better to remember some lines because of the forcing and high-risk nature of the position. } 13. Bg5 ( 13. Ng5 c4 14. Qxg4 h6 { Forcing a draw. } ( 14... cxb3 { This is a path to a very unclear position. } 15. Qh5 g6 16. Qf3 Qe7 $13 ) 15. Nxf7 Kxf7 16. Qf5+ Kg8 17. Qe6+ Kh7 18. Bc2+ d3 19. Qf5+ Kg8 $11 ) ( 13. h3 c4 $13 ) 13... Be7 { The simplest response. } ( 13... Qc8 $5 { Very sharp, also possible. Not recommended unless you have really studied, understood the position and remembered some lines. } 14. Nd5 ( 14. e6 $2 f6 $17 ) 14... c4 15. Bxc4 bxc4 16. Qxc4 h6 17. Bf4 Qd7 $1 18. Rfd1 ( 18. Nb6 Qf5 19. Nxa8 Qxf4 20. Rfe1 ( 20. Nc7+ $6 Kd8 21. Nxa6 Ngxe5 $15 ) 20... Bxa8 21. Qxa6 Na7 $3 22. Qxa7 ( 22. Qa4+ Bc6 ) 22... Bxf3 23. Qb8+ ( 23. g3 Qd2 ) 23... Ke7 24. Qd6+ Ke8 $11 ) ( 18. e6 fxe6 19. Nb6 Qf7 20. Nxa8 Bxa8 21. Qxa6 Bb7 22. Qb5 Qxf4 23. Rae1 ( 23. Qxb7 $6 Nce5 ) 23... Ba8 $1 24. Qa4 Bb7 $11 ) 18... g5 19. Bg3 ( 19. Nxd4 Rc8 20. e6 fxe6 21. Nc7+ Rxc7 22. Bxc7 Nxd4 23. Rxd4 Bd5 $13 ) ( 19. e6 fxe6 20. Nb6 Qf7 21. Re1 ( 21. Nxa8 gxf4 ) 21... gxf4 22. Rxe6+ Be7 23. Nxa8 Bxa8 24. Rxc6 Qxc4 25. Rxc4 Bxf3 26. gxf3 Ne5 27. Rc8+ Bd8 28. Re1 Kd7 29. Rxd8+ Rxd8 30. Rxe5 Kd6 31. Re4 Kd5 32. Kf1 Kc4 $11 ) 19... Bg7 20. Nxd4 ( 20. Nb6 $6 Qe6 21. Qxe6+ fxe6 22. Nxa8 Bxa8 23. Nxd4 Nxd4 24. Rxd4 Nxe5 25. Rd6 Ke7 26. Rxa6 Rc8 $15 ) 20... Ngxe5 21. Bxe5 ( 21. Qc5 Rc8 22. Nxc6 Rxc6 23. Qa7 Qc8 24. Nb6 Qc7 25. Nd5 Qc8 $11 ) 21... Bxe5 22. Nf3 ( 22. Nb6 Bxh2+ ) ( 22. Re1 Kf8 23. Nxc6 Qxc6 24. Qxc6 Bxh2+ 25. Kxh2 Bxc6 $11 ) 22... Kf8 23. Nb4 ( 23. Nb6 Qf5 24. Nd7+ Kg7 25. Ndxe5 Nxe5 26. Nxe5 Qxe5 27. Rd7 Qf6 28. Rxb7 Rac8 29. Qb3 Rhd8 $11 ) 23... Qe6 24. Qc5+ ( 24. Qxe6 fxe6 25. Nxc6 Bxb2 26. Rab1 Bxc6 27. Rxb2 Bxf3 28. gxf3 Ke7 $11 ) 24... Kg7 25. Nxc6 Bxh2+ 26. Kxh2 Qxc6 27. Qd4+ Qf6 $11 { Ѕ-Ѕ (31) Mikhailov,G (2329) -Mayorov,B ICCF email 2016. } ) 14. Ne4 d3 15. Qe1 d2 $1 { Trying to lure the bishop back to d2. } 16. Qe2 ( 16. Bxd2 O-O $13 ) 16... O-O 17. Nxc5 Bc8 $1 18. Qe4 { Other moves lead to a pretty simple equality for Black. } ( 18. h4 Bxg5 ( 18... Bf5 $5 19. Nb7 Qd7 20. Nd6 Be6 21. Rad1 ( 21. Qxd2 Ngxe5 ) 21... Bxb3 22. axb3 Ncxe5 23. Nxe5 Nxe5 24. Bxe7 Qxe7 25. Rxd2 Rfd8 $11 ) 19. hxg5 { 1-0 (36) Aditya,M (2485) -Ganguly,S (2589) chess24.com INT 2022 } 19... Bf5 20. Qxd2 ( 20. Rfd1 Qe7 ) 20... Ngxe5 $11 ) ( 18. Ne4 Ngxe5 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. Bxd2 Qd3 $11 ) ( 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. Qxd2 Ncxe5 20. Qd5 Nxf3+ 21. Qxf3 Qd6 22. g3 Ra7 23. Qc3 Rc7 24. Rac1 $11 ) 18... Bxg5 19. Qxc6 ( 19. e6 Qd6 $1 20. Qxg4 Bh6 21. exf7+ Kh8 $13 { It's dynamically balanced. Both sides have far-advanced pawns in the enemy's camp. } ) 19... Bf5 20. Nb7 Qe7 21. Nd6 Bg6 22. e6 ( 22. Nxf7 { I continued this line very far, because important material transformations continue to occur. This does not have to be all memorized, of course. It's a long line, but Black has quite simple moves, not so hard to find over the board. } 22... Bxf7 23. e6 Bg6 24. Nxg5 Rfc8 25. Qd5 Rd8 26. Qf3 Nf6 ( 26... Ne5 $5 27. Qf4 Nc4 ) 27. Qf4 a5 28. a3 a4 29. Ba2 Bc2 30. Rad1 Bxd1 31. Rxd1 Rac8 32. h3 Rc2 33. Nf7 Rxb2 34. Nxd8 Rxa2 35. Rxd2 Rxd2 36. Qxd2 Qxa3 37. Nc6 h6 38. e7 Qc5 39. Qd8+ Kh7 40. e8 Nxe8 41. Qxe8 Qc1+ 42. Kh2 Qc4 $11 { [%csl Ga4,Gb5] } ) 22... fxe6 23. Nxg5 { Black has two choices now. After both of them a period of complications eventually lead to a clarification and a pretty simple equal position at the end. } 23... Qxg5 ( 23... Ne5 $5 24. Nc8 Rfxc8 25. Qxe6+ Qxe6 26. Bxe6+ Kf8 27. Bxc8 Rxc8 28. f4 Nc4 29. Rfd1 Bc2 30. b3 Bxd1 31. Rxd1 h6 32. Nf3 Nd6 33. Nxd2 Rc2 34. a4 bxa4 35. bxa4 Nf5 $11 ) 24. Bxe6+ Kh8 25. Bxg4 Qxg4 26. Qd5 Qb4 27. Rad1 Qxb2 28. Rxd2 Qf6 $11 *

