1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 a6 8. dxc5 { One of the principled lines. White tries to transform his slight lead in development into an edge in the symmetrical endgame. } 8... Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bxc5 10. Bd2 { White intends to develop his play on the queenside with pieces and not pawns in this version of the endgame. } ( 10. Bd3 { [%cal Gc3e4] } 10... O-O 11. b3 ( 11. Ne4 Be7 12. Bd2 Rd8 13. Be1 Bd7 $11 ) 11... b5 ( 11... Bd7 12. Bb2 Rfd8 { Also fine } 13. Ne4 Be7 $11 ) 12. Bb2 ( 12. a4 b4 13. Ne4 Be7 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Rb1 Bb7 $11 ) 12... Bb7 13. Rac1 Be7 14. Ne4 Nb4 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bxf6 gxf6 $11 ) ( 10. b3 b5 11. Be2 Bb7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Rac1 Be7 $11 { [%cal Ga8c8,Gf8d8] } ) ( 10. a3 { This not so good with the knight on c3. The game becomes completely symmetrical: } 10... b5 11. Be2 Bb7 12. b4 Be7 13. Bb2 O-O $11 { [%cal Gf8d8] } ) ( 10. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2b3] } 10... O-O 11. Nb3 { One of the more interesting options for White. The knight maneuver introduces a certain imbalance in piece deployment. } ( 11. Nde4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Be7 13. b3 ( 13. Bd2 b5 14. Be2 Bb7 15. Bc3 ( 15. Rac1 Nd4 $1 ) 15... Rfd8 $11 ) 13... Rd8 14. Rxd8+ ( 14. Bb2 b5 ) 14... Nxd8 15. Bb2 b5 16. Bd3 Nc6 17. a4 Nb4 18. Be2 Bb7 $11 ) 11... Bb4 $5 { We intend to capture on c3 in some lines. ..e5, freeing the second bishop, is anothe rimportant idea. } ( 11... Be7 12. e4 ) ( 11... Ba7 { Also should be fine. } ) 12. Bd2 ( 12. Be2 e5 $14 { [%cal Gc8f5,Gc8e6] } ( 12... Bd7 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Rxd7 Rab8 15. a3 Bd6 16. Nd2 Nxd2 17. Bxd2 Be5 18. Rb1 Rfd8 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Be1 $14 { 1-0 (39) Mamedyarov,S (2741) -Praggnanandhaa,R (2678) chess24.com INT 2022 } ) 13. Bd2 ( 13. Na4 Bf5 14. Nb6 ( 14. Bd2 Bc2 $1 { After all the exchanges the position becomes absolutely equal. } 15. Bxb4 Bxd1 16. Bxf8 Bxe2 17. Bc5 Rd8 18. Nc3 Bc4 $11 ) 14... Rad8 15. Bd2 Bc2 16. Bxb4 Bxd1 17. Bxf8 Bxe2 18. Ba3 h5 $11 ) ( 13. Bf3 Be6 14. Bd2 Rfd8 $11 ) 13... Be6 14. Na4 Bxb3 15. axb3 Bxd2 16. Rxd2 Rfd8 17. Rxd8+ Rxd8 { [%cal Gd8d2] } 18. Nc5 Rd2 19. Kf1 Rxb2 20. Nxb7 Rxb3 21. Bxa6 $11 ) ( 12. a3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 e5 $1 14. a4 { [%cal Gc1a3] } 14... Bf5 15. Ba3 Rfd8 ( 15... Rfc8 16. Rdc1 ) 16. Nc5 ( 16. Rdc1 Ne4 17. f3 Nd2 18. Nxd2 Rxd2 19. e4 Be6 20. Bxe6 fxe6 $11 { We have a little bit compromised pawn structure, but White's bishop is quite passive. } ) 16... Na5 { Here we equalize by force. } 17. Ba2 Bc2 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Bb4 b6 20. Nxa6 Bxa4 $11 ) 12... Rd8 ( { Similar is } 12... Bd7 ) 13. Be2 ( 13. Rac1 Bd7 ) ( 13. a3 Be7 14. Rac1 Bd7 $11 ) 13... Bd7 ( 13... e5 14. Na4 Bxd2 15. Nxd2 Bf5 16. Nb6 Rab8 17. Rac1 Kf8 { Maybe also fine. } ) 14. Na4 ( 14. Rac1 Be8 $11 ) 14... Be8 { We exchange a lot of material and completely neutralize White's attempts: } 15. Bxb4 ( 15. Nb6 Rab8 ) 15... Rxd1+ 16. Rxd1 Nxb4 17. Nb6 Rb8 18. a3 Nbd5 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Rc1 Ba4 21. Nd2 ( 21. Nc5 Rc8 22. Bf3 b6 23. Bxd5 Rxc5 24. Rxc5 bxc5 $11 ) 21... Kf8 $11 { [%cal Gf8e7] } ) ( 10. Be2 O-O 11. Bd2 Bd7 12. Rac1 Rfd8 13. Na4 Ba7 { Transpose to 10.Nd2. } ) 10... O-O 11. Rac1 ( 11. Be1 b5 ( 11... Bd7 $6 12. Ne4 $1 ) ( 11... Be7 { Also possible } ) 12. Be2 ( 12. Bf1 Bb7 13. Rac1 Be7 14. a4 b4 15. Ne2 Rfc8 16. Ned4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 a5 18. Bb5 Bc5 19. Nb3 Bb6 $11 ) 12... Bb7 13. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2b3] } ( 13. Rac1 Be7 ) 13... Na5 $1 { We provoke a3-b4 to make any a4 undermining in the future ineffective because of the hanging pawn on b4. } 14. a3 ( 14. Rac1 Be7 ) 14... Be7 15. b4 Nc6 16. Nb3 Rac8 17. Rac1 Rfd8 18. Rxd8+ Nxd8 $11 ) ( 11. Be2 Bd7 12. Na4 ( 12. Be1 Rfd8 ) 12... Ba7 13. Rac1 Rfd8 { Transpose to 11.Rc1. } ) 11... Bd7 12. Na4 ( 12. Be1 Rfd8 13. Na4 Ba7 { Transposes to 12.Ba4. } ) ( 12. Be2 Rfd8 { Also will transpose } ) 12... Ba7 { White now retreats the bishop from c4 to put the knight on c5 (of course ...b5 is also a threat) . } 13. Be2 ( 13. Bb3 Rfc8 14. Be1 ( 14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 Ne4 $11 { [%cal Ge4d2] } ) 14... Be8 15. Nc5 Na5 $1 16. Bxa5 Rxc5 $11 ) ( 13. Bd3 { Black gets a tactical idea against the bishop on d3: } 13... Rfd8 14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 e5 $1 16. Bc2 ( 16. Bb1 e4 17. Nd4 ( 17. Ng5 Bg4 18. f3 exf3 19. gxf3 Bh5 $11 ) 17... Nxd4 18. exd4 Ba4 19. b3 Bc6 20. Bg5 Rd6 $11 { [%cal Ga8d8] } ) 16... Be6 ( 16... e4 $5 17. Ng5 b6 18. Rc3 Ne5 ) 17. a3 Nd7 18. Rc3 h6 19. Be1 Nb6 $11 { White has the bishop pair, but our pieces are much more active. } ) 13... Rfd8 14. Nc5 ( 14. Be1 Nd4 $1 { A simple completely euqalizing tactic. } ( 14... Be8 15. Nc5 Rxd1 16. Bxd1 Rb8 { Also should be ok. } ) 15. Nxd4 Bxa4 16. b3 Be8 17. Bf3 ( 17. Rc7 $6 Bxd4 ) 17... Bxd4 18. Rxd4 ( 18. exd4 Nd5 ) 18... Rxd4 19. exd4 Nd5 20. Bxd5 exd5 21. Rc7 Bc6 $11 { 1/2 (31) Panjwani,R (2469) -Pajeken,J (2420) Skanderborg 2023 } ) 14... Bxc5 15. Rxc5 Ne4 16. Rcc1 ( 16. Rc2 e5 $5 { [%cal Gd7e6] We don't have to exchange the knight for the bishop. We can play for more activity and more imbalance if we want to. } ( 16... Nxd2 17. Rcxd2 Be8 $11 ) 17. Be1 Be6 18. a3 ( 18. Ra1 f6 $11 ) 18... Bb3 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Rc1 f6 $11 ) 16... Nxd2 { Here trading is the most accurate choice. } ( 16... e5 17. Be1 Be6 18. a3 { A bit better version for White than 16.Rc2 } ) 17. Nxd2 ( 17. Rxd2 Be8 $11 ) 17... Ne7 { Trying to bring the bishop to a more active position. The game is very equal and drawish. } ( 17... Be8 { Also completely fine. } 18. a3 ( 18. Ne4 Kf8 19. Nd6 Ke7 20. Nxb7 Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 Rb8 22. Bxa6 Nb4 $11 ) 18... h6 19. Nb3 Kf8 20. Nc5 Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 Rb8 22. Nd7+ Bxd7 23. Rxd7 Ne5 24. Rc7 b5 25. b3 Rd8 26. Kf1 g5 $11 { 1/2 (27) Gutkind,K (2239) -Szulc,S (2101) ICCF email 2021 } ) 18. Nb3 ( 18. Nc4 Bb5 $11 ) 18... Ba4 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Nc5 Rc8 21. Kf1 b6 22. Nd3 Rxc1+ 23. Nxc1 a5 24. Nd3 Kf8 $11 { Ѕ-Ѕ (39) So,W (2771) -Dominguez Perez,L (2745) Saint Louis 2022. } *

