1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 a6 8. d5 $5 { One of the most dangerous and sharpest lines. } 8... Nxd5 $5 ( { The main line is } 8... Na5 9. b3 $1 b5 10. Bd3 b4 $1 ( 10... Be7 $6 11. e4 $16 ) 11. dxe6 $14 bxc3 12. exf7+ Kxf7 { With very big complications. } ) 9. Nxd5 b5 $1 ( { Another dangerous,but unclear line is } 9... Na5 10. e4 Nxc4 11. Bg5 $36 ) 10. Bb3 ( 10. e4 bxc4 11. Re1 f6 $1 ( 11... Bb7 $6 { This move does not equalize completely. } 12. Bf4 { 1/2 (27) Aditya,V (2409) -Vardan,N (2357) Budapest 2022 } 12... Bd6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Nf6+ Ke7 15. Nd5+ exd5 16. exd5+ Kf8 17. dxc6 Qxd1 18. Rexd1 Bxc6 19. Ne5 Bb5 20. a4 Be8 21. Nxc4 $14 ) 12. Qa4 Bd7 13. Qxc4 Na5 { This is a direct path. } ( 13... Bd6 $5 { Quite possible as well. } ) 14. Qd3 Bb5 15. Qe3 exd5 16. exd5+ Be7 { White needs to force a draw with a few accuarte moves now: } 17. Qe4 Kf8 18. Nh4 Bd6 19. Nf5 Nc4 20. Nxg7 Kxg7 21. Qg4+ Kf7 22. Qh5+ Kg8 23. Qg4+ $11 ) 10... c4 11. Bxc4 ( 11. a4 $5 Bb7 $1 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Bxa8 14. e4 cxb3 15. Qxb3 Bd6 $5 { The simplest path. We give up the b5-pawn. The bishop pair on the open board will ultimately guarantee us enough counterplay for a little material investment. } ( 15... exd5 16. exd5 ) 16. Qxb5 exd5 17. exd5 Qb8 18. Qa4 O-O 19. dxc6 Rc8 { [%cal Ga8c6] } 20. h3 Bxc6 21. Qg4 Qb7 22. Rd1 Bf8 $11 { White is not better, the bishop pair simply offsets the extra pawn. } ) ( 11. Nf4 { This is a completely harmless retreat. } 11... cxb3 12. Qxb3 Bb7 ( 12... Qc7 $5 13. Bd2 Bd6 14. Rac1 O-O ) 13. Rd1 Qf6 $1 14. e4 Ne5 15. Nh5 ( 15. a4 Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 Be7 $11 ) 15... Nxf3+ 16. gxf3 Qe5 17. Qd3 Bc6 $1 { The only move, but a fully satisfactory one. } 18. Bf4 Qxh5 19. Rac1 Be7 20. Rxc6 O-O $11 ) ( 11. e4 cxb3 12. Bg5 { We have two good options against this aggressive try. } ( 12. Bf4 Bd6 $13 ) 12... Ne7 ( 12... f6 $5 13. Bf4 exd5 14. exd5 Na5 15. Re1+ Kf7 16. d6 Bb7 17. axb3 Bxd6 $1 18. Bxd6 Re8 19. Ng5+ fxg5 20. Qh5+ Kg8 21. Bc7 Qd7 22. Bxa5 $11 ) 13. Re1 bxa2 14. Qd4 exd5 15. exd5 f6 16. d6 Kf7 $1 17. Ne5+ $1 { Keeping the initative going, but sacrificing another piece. } ( 17. Qd3 Be6 $13 ) 17... fxe5 18. Qxe5 Ra7 $1 { White is a lot of material down and he only has enogh momentum to guarantee a draw. } 19. Qf4+ ( 19. Rad1 a1 20. Rxa1 h6 21. Bxe7 Bxe7 22. Qd5+ Kg6 23. Qe4+ Bf5 24. dxe7 Bxe4 25. exd8 Rxd8 26. Rxe4 $11 ) 19... Ke8 20. Qe5 Kf7 $11 ) 11... bxc4 12. e4 ( 12. Nc3 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Be7 14. e4 Rb8 $11 { [%csl Rb2,Rc1][%cal Gb8b2] } ) 12... Bb7 ( 12... exd5 $2 13. exd5 Ne7 14. Re1 $16 ) 13. Re1 ( 13. Bf4 Rc8 14. Qe1 $5 ( 14. Rc1 f6 $1 { [%cal Ge8f7] } 15. Qe2 Kf7 16. Nc3 Nb4 { [%cal Gb4d3] } 17. Be3 Nd3 18. Rcd1 Bb4 $11 ) ( 14. Qe2 Bd6 $1 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Ne3 ( 16. Nb6 Nd4 $1 { This is why 14.Qe1 is a more cunning option. } 17. Nxd4 Qxb6 $11 ) 16... Nd4 17. Nxd4 Qxd4 18. f3 O-O 19. Rfd1 Qb6 20. Kh1 c3 $11 ) 14... Bc5 $1 ( 14... Be7 $5 15. Nxe7 Qxe7 16. Qc3 O-O 17. Qxc4 ( 17. Rfd1 Rfd8 ) 17... Ne5 18. Qe2 Nxf3+ 19. Qxf3 Rfd8 $44 { Black actually has sufficient compensation for the pawn in this opposite-coloured bishops position. } ) ( 14... Bd6 $2 { doesn't work now: } 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Nb6 $16 ) 15. Be3 ( 15. Bg5 f6 $13 ) ( 15. Rd1 { We can already take on d5 and castle soon, becoming fully safe. } 15... exd5 16. exd5+ Ne7 17. d6 O-O 18. dxe7 Qxe7 19. Qxe7 Bxe7 20. Rd7 Bxf3 21. Rxe7 Bd5 $11 ) 15... Bxe3 16. Nxe3 Qd3 { Now the c4 pawn gets traded for the e4-pawn quite inevitably. } 17. Rd1 Qxe4 18. Nd2 Qf4 19. Ndxc4 ( 19. Nd5 Qh4 $11 ) 19... O-O 20. Nd6 Rb8 21. Nxb7 Rxb7 $11 { A simple equality finally emerges from the complications. } ) ( 13. Ne3 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Nb4 15. Rd4 a5 { We give up the c4-pawn, but the bishop pair plus the knight on d3 will provide ample compensation. } 16. Rxc4 Nd3 17. b3 Be7 18. Bd2 O-O $44 { Black is not worse having such activity. } ) 13... Bb4 $1 { This may look counter-intuitive, but it is clearly the best choice. } ( 13... Rc8 14. Be3 $1 ( 14. Qa4 Bd6 $1 15. Bg5 Qa5 $1 16. Qxa5 Nxa5 17. Nb6 Rc6 18. Na4 c3 $1 19. Nxc3 Nc4 $44 20. b3 h6 $1 { [%csl Rg5] } ) 14... Nb4 $1 15. Nb6 Qxd1 16. Rexd1 Rc7 17. Nd2 c3 18. bxc3 Rxc3 19. Nbc4 Bc6 20. Ne5 $14 ) ( 13... Be7 $6 14. Nxe7 Qxd1 15. Rxd1 Kxe7 16. Bf4 Rhd8 17. Rdc1 $16 ) 14. Bg5 ( 14. Nxb4 { A soft choice. } 14... Qxd1 15. Rxd1 Nxb4 $11 ) ( 14. Bd2 Bxd2 15. Qxd2 O-O 16. Ne3 Ne5 $1 { The crucial move. } 17. Qxd8 Nxf3+ 18. gxf3 Raxd8 $1 { [%cal Gf7f5] } 19. Nxc4 ( 19. Rac1 f5 $1 ) 19... f5 $1 { Striking before White stabilizes with his pawn edge. } 20. Ne5 Rd4 $11 { Black has enough counterplay against e4. } ) 14... f6 15. Bd2 Bxd2 16. Qxd2 Rc8 $1 { A bit more accurate choice than 16...0-0 } ( 16... O-O 17. Ne3 Qd3 { Maybe also fine } 18. Qc3 $5 Qxc3 19. bxc3 Rfd8 20. Nxc4 a5 21. Rad1 Ba6 22. Nd6 Kf8 23. e5 Ke7 $44 { White keeps a small pressure, but it's very hard to transform this pawn advantage into a substantial edge. } ) 17. Ne3 ( 17. Rac1 O-O 18. Nf4 ( 18. Ne3 Qxd2 19. Nxd2 Rfd8 20. Ndxc4 Nb4 $11 { [%cal Gb4a2,Gb4d3] } ) 18... Qxd2 19. Nxd2 Nb4 $1 { Everything gradually comes off the board here. } 20. Nxe6 ( 20. a3 Rfd8 $1 21. Rxc4 ( 21. Nxc4 Na2 $1 ) 21... Nc2 22. Rxc8 Bxc8 23. Rd1 a5 { [%cal Gd8d1] } 24. Ne2 e5 $44 ) 20... Rfe8 21. Nf4 Nxa2 22. Rxc4 Rxc4 23. Nxc4 Rxe4 24. Rxe4 Bxe4 { This of course doesn't need to be further memorized, but I just continuead the line to show how the game may fizzle out after White tries to quickly bring his king to the centre. } 25. f3 Bc6 26. Kf2 Nc1 27. Ke3 g5 28. Nh5 ( 28. Kd2 gxf4 29. Kxc1 Kf7 30. Kd2 Ke6 $11 ) 28... Kf7 29. Nd6+ Ke6 30. Ne4 Bxe4 31. Kxe4 f5+ 32. Kd4 Nb3+ 33. Kc3 Na5 34. Kb4 Nc6+ 35. Kc5 Ne5 $11 ) ( 17. Rad1 O-O 18. Nc3 Qb6 $11 ) 17... Qxd2 18. Nxd2 Ne5 19. Rec1 { Not allowing the exchange of pawns with ...c3 is White's last possible attempt to keep pressing. } ( 19. f3 c3 20. bxc3 Rxc3 21. Rab1 Bc8 22. Rec1 Rxc1+ 23. Rxc1 Ke7 $11 ) 19... Ke7 20. f3 ( 20. Ndxc4 Nxc4 21. Nxc4 Bxe4 $11 ) 20... c3 $1 { The right way to give up the pawn that offers Black great activity and blockading chances in return. This was the plan all along. } 21. Rxc3 ( 21. bxc3 Rhd8 22. Nb3 Rd3 23. Nd1 g5 $44 { [%csl Rc3,Gd3,Ge5][%cal Gh7h5] } ) 21... Rxc3 22. bxc3 Rd8 ( 22... Bc6 $5 { An engine alternative that leads to a kind of positional draw, where White will not be able to improve despite his pawn advantage: } 23. Ndc4 Nxc4 24. Nxc4 Rc8 25. Nd2 e5 26. Rb1 Bb5 27. Rb3 Rd8 28. Rb2 Rc8 29. Rc2 Ba4 30. Rc1 Rb8 $11 ) 23. Nb3 ( 23. Ndc4 Nxc4 24. Nxc4 Rc8 25. Na5 Ba8 26. Rc1 f5 $1 27. exf5 exf5 28. Rc2 Bd5 29. Kf2 f4 30. Nb3 Bc4 $44 { Black has a total blockade, there's no way to make progress as White. } ) 23... Rd3 24. Nd1 Bc6 25. Kf1 g5 26. Rc1 ( 26. Ke1 g4 27. Nb2 Rd8 28. Kf2 gxf3 29. gxf3 f5 $11 ) 26... Bb5 ( 26... Ba4 27. Ke1 g4 $44 { was also fine, Black lost mainly because it was a blitz game. 1-0 (44) Nakamura,H (2768) -Dominguez Perez,L (2745) Chess.com INT 2022 } ) 27. Ke1 h5 28. Nd4 ( 28. Nc5 Rd8 $44 ) 28... g4 29. fxg4 hxg4 $44 { Black has a clear positional compensation for the pawn, occupying a number of excellent outposts. Despite being a pawn down, he should not fell any worse. } *

