1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 { There is a number of viable moves apart from 3...e5: 3...Nf6, 3...Nc6 and 3...b5. I recommend the absolute main line. } 3... e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Bxc4 Nc6 { In this lesson we focus on rare 6th moves for White. } 6. Qb3 ( 6. a3 Nf6 { White has lost a tempo on a3, so we play principled chess striking against the opponent's centre. } ( 6... Be6 { Also possible } ) 7. O-O ( 7. e5 Nd7 8. O-O Nb6 9. Bd3 Bg4 10. Re1 Be7 $13 { The game is still balanced, but White will already need to be accurate if he wants to keep full compensation. } ) 7... Be7 8. e5 Nd5 ( 8... Nd7 $5 { Also completely fine. } 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. e6+ Kg8 11. exd7 Qxd7 $13 ) 9. Nxd4 Nxe5 ( 9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Be6 11. Rd1 Nb6 12. Bxe6 Qxd4 13. Bxf7+ Kxf7 14. Rxd4 Rhd8 $11 { Here Black has obvious compensation for the pawn and he is the one playing for an advantage. } ) 10. Bxd5 Qxd5 11. Nc3 { White's activity is basically only sufficient to keep the equal chances whether Black moves the queen to d8 or d7. } 11... Qd7 ( 11... Qd8 12. Re1 Ng6 13. Bg5 O-O 14. Nc6 Qxd1 15. Nxe7+ Nxe7 16. Raxd1 Ng6 17. Nd5 c6 18. Ne7+ Nxe7 19. Rxe7 b6 $11 ) 12. Re1 Ng6 ( 12... f6 13. Bf4 O-O $11 ) 13. Bg5 O-O 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 15. Ndb5 Nf5 16. Qxd7 Bxd7 17. Nxc7 Rac8 18. N7d5 Rfd8 19. Rad1 ( 19. g4 Nh4 ) 19... Kf8 $11 ) ( 6. Nbd2 { An interesting choice. Surprsingly, there is only one clear way fro Black to be fine. } 6... Be7 $14 ( 6... Nf6 7. Qb3 ) 7. a3 ( 7. Qb3 $6 Nh6 $1 { One of the points of 6...Be7. } 8. O-O O-O $17 { [%cal Gc6a5] } ) ( 7. O-O Nf6 8. e5 ( 8. Re1 O-O 9. e5 Nd5 10. Nb3 Nb6 11. Bf1 Bg4 12. Nbxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Qxd4 ( 13... Bxf3 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. gxf3 Bb4 16. Re4 Bd2 $11 ) 14. Nxd4 Rad8 $11 ) 8... Nd7 $1 9. e6 ( 9. Re1 Nb6 10. Bd3 Bg4 $13 ) ( 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. e6+ Kg8 11. exd7 Qxd7 12. Nb3 ( 12. Qb3+ Qe6 ) 12... Bf6 $13 ) 9... fxe6 10. Bxe6 Nc5 11. Bc4 Be6 12. Bxe6 Nxe6 { White can only fight to regain the pawn here, not to gain an edge: } 13. Qb3 Nc5 14. Qc4 Qd6 15. b4 Nd7 16. b5 Nce5 17. Qxd4 Nxf3+ { What follows is not the only possibility. } ( 17... O-O $11 ) 18. Nxf3 Qxd4 19. Nxd4 O-O-O { White is in more danger because of his loose pawns and plays to keep equality. } 20. Ne6 ( 20. Bf4 Nc5 $15 ) 20... Bf6 21. Nxd8 Bxa1 22. Bf4 Rxd8 23. Rxa1 Nc5 $11 ) 7... Nf6 ( 7... a5 { This is perfectly playable, but continuing development with 7...Nf6 is simpler. } 8. O-O Nf6 9. e5 Nd7 10. e6 fxe6 11. Bxe6 Nde5 ( 11... Nc5 12. Bc4 Be6 13. Bxe6 Nxe6 14. Qb3 Nc5 15. Qc4 Qd6 16. Re1 Rf8 $1 17. Rb1 a4 18. b4 axb3 19. Nxb3 O-O-O 20. Bg5 Rxf3 $1 21. Bxe7 Nxe7 22. gxf3 Nxb3 23. Qxb3 b6 $44 ) 12. Ba2 Bg4 13. h3 Bh5 14. Re1 Nd3 15. Re6 Nc5 $11 ) 8. b4 O-O 9. O-O Bg4 10. Qc2 d3 $5 { The way to equalize by force. } ( 10... Nd7 11. b5 Nce5 12. Nxd4 Nb6 13. Bb2 Bf6 $11 { This is also even. } ) 11. Bxd3 ( 11. Qxd3 Qxd3 12. Bxd3 Rfd8 $15 ) 11... Bxb4 { The point of ...d3. } 12. e5 Bxd2 13. Bxd2 Bxf3 14. exf6 Qxf6 { Black gets pretty self-explantory compensation for the piece: } 15. gxf3 Nd4 16. Qd1 Nxf3+ 17. Kg2 ( 17. Kh1 $2 Rad8 $19 ) 17... Nh4+ 18. Kh1 Rad8 19. Be4 Qd4 ( 19... Rfe8 { This is a way to finish the game with a perpetual check. } 20. f3 Rxe4 21. fxe4 Qg6 22. Qe2 Rxd2 23. Qxd2 Qxe4+ 24. Kg1 Qg4+ 25. Kf2 Qf3+ $11 ) 20. Qg4 Rfe8 21. f3 Nxf3 22. Bxf3 Qxg4 23. Bxg4 Rxd2 24. Rfd1 Rxd1+ 25. Rxd1 Kf8 26. Bf3 c6 $11 { Equal, but easier for Black who has as many as four pawns for the piece. } ) 6... Bb4+ $1 { Throwing in this check is very important. } 7. Nbd2 ( 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8. Nbxd2 Qf6 9. O-O Nge7 { This of course works because we have gotten the bishop out of the way with ...Bb4+. } 10. e5 ( { Similar is } 10. Rfe1 O-O ) 10... Qg6 11. Rfe1 ( 11. Bd3 Qh5 ) 11... O-O 12. Bd3 Qh5 13. Be4 ( 13. Nf1 Bg4 14. Be4 ( 14. Ng3 Qh6 ) 14... Rab8 15. Ng3 Qh6 $13 ) ( 13. Re4 Bf5 14. Rh4 Qg6 15. Bxf5 Nxf5 16. Rf4 { 0-1 (44) Bagrationi,A (2500) -Donchenko,A (2618) Chess.com INT 2019 } 16... Nd8 $1 { Bringing the knight to the superb e6-square. Black starts playing for an edge. } 17. h3 h5 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 19. Rxd4 Ne6 20. Rc4 Rad8 $15 ) 13... a6 { [%cal Gc8e6] } ( 13... Rb8 14. Rad1 Rd8 $11 ) 14. Rad1 Be6 15. Qc2 ( 15. Qxb7 $2 Ra7 $17 { [%csl Rb7] } ) 15... Rad8 $11 ) 7... Qf6 { Preparing a harmonious setup with ...Nge7 and ...0-0 next. } ( { Another possible continuation is } 7... Nh6 8. Bd5 ( 8. Bb5 a5 ) ( 8. O-O O-O ) 8... a5 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc4 $13 ) 8. O-O ( 8. Bb5 Bxd2+ ( { Black can also inlcude first } 8... a5 ) 9. Bxd2 Ne7 10. Bg5 Qg6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rfe1 ( 12. Rac1 Be6 13. Qa3 f6 14. Bd2 Rfd8 $11 ) 12... Bg4 13. Bxe7 Bxf3 ( 13... Nxe7 14. Nxd4 Rfd8 $11 ) 14. Qxf3 Nxe7 15. e5 Qe6 $11 ) ( 8. a3 Bd6 $1 9. O-O Nge7 10. e5 Bxe5 { There follows a very forcing line that ends in a draw: } ( 10... Nxe5 $2 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Nf3 Bf4 13. Bxf4 Qxf4 14. Rfe1 Qf6 15. Qb4 $16 { [%csl Re8][%cal Ge1e8] } ) 11. Ne4 Qg6 12. Neg5 O-O 13. Nxf7 Rxf7 14. Ng5 Nd8 15. Qb5 Nec6 16. Re1 Kf8 17. Nxf7 Nxf7 18. Bxf7 Kxf7 19. Rxe5 Nxe5 20. Qxe5 Qd6 $11 ) ( 8. e5 Qg6 9. O-O Nge7 { Transpose to 8.0-0. } ) 8... Nge7 9. e5 ( 9. a3 Bd6 { Transpose to 8.a3. } ) 9... Qg6 10. Nh4 ( 10. Bd3 Qe6 11. Nc4 ( 11. Bc4 Qg6 $11 ) 11... h6 12. Nxd4 ( 12. a3 { If White doesn't recapture the pawn, he should be careful in the resulting game, as it's not clear how to proceed. } 12... Bc5 13. Bf4 a5 14. Rac1 O-O 15. Rfe1 a4 16. Qd1 b6 17. Bg3 Ba6 $13 ) 12... Nxd4 13. Qxb4 O-O 14. Be3 Rd8 $11 { With an easy game. } ) ( 10. a3 Bxd2 11. Bxd2 O-O $13 ) 10... Qh5 11. Ndf3 { A bit strange piece placement with a cunning idea. } 11... a5 $1 { The natural 11...0-0?! can be met by 12.h3!, all of a sudden threatening g4. } 12. a3 a4 13. Qc2 Ba5 14. h3 ( 14. Qxa4 h6 { [%cal Gg7g5] Black has the g-pawn push idea of his own! } 15. b4 g5 16. bxa5 gxh4 17. Nxd4 Rg8 $13 { The attack gives Black plenty of counterplay. 1/2 (37) Krzyzanowski,W (2457) -Schuster,P (2454) ICCF email 2016 } ) 14... Nxe5 ( 14... Ng6 15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. Ng5 O-O $13 ) 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. Qxa4+ c6 17. Nf3 { Finally we are close to reaching a fairly simple, equal position without danger. } 17... Qf5 ( { Othe roptions are: } 17... Qh5 ) ( 17... Qd6 ) 18. Nxd4 Qf6 19. Be3 O-O $11 *

