1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Bxc4 Nc6 6. O-O Be6 { In this lesson we cover rare 7th moves, which are not so threatening, and a major option of 7.Nbd2. } 7. Nbd2 $5 ( 7. Qb3 $6 { This just loses time. } 7... Bxc4 8. Qxc4 Qd7 9. Rd1 Qe6 $15 { White struggles to show compensation or recapture the pawn. } ) ( 7. Bg5 Qd7 8. Bxe6 fxe6 9. Qb3 Nf6 $13 { The game is balanced, but it is rather White who should be careful. } ) ( 7. Bb3 $6 { Another passive move. } 7... Nf6 ( 7... Qd6 8. Bxe6 Qxe6 ( 8... fxe6 9. Na3 Nf6 10. Nb5 Qd7 11. Nbxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Qxd4 13. Nxd4 e5 14. Ne6 Kf7 15. Nxf8 Rhxf8 16. f3 $11 ) 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Ne7 11. Bf4 Nc6 12. Qe3 O-O-O 13. Nc3 Bb4 14. Nd5 Bd6 $11 ) 8. Ba4 ( 8. e5 Ne4 ) 8... Bc5 9. e5 ( 9. Qc2 Bb6 ) 9... Ng8 $5 10. Nbd2 Bb6 11. Nb3 d3 $13 ) 7... Qf6 $1 { This is supposed to be the best move. } ( 7... Bxc4 $6 8. Nxc4 Bc5 ( 8... Nf6 $6 9. Qb3 b6 10. Nce5 $16 { 1-0 (39) Miton,K (2619) -Nisipeanu,L (2659) Mulhouse 2011 } ) ( 8... Bd6 9. Qb3 Nge7 10. Qxb7 O-O 11. Rd1 $14 ) 9. Qb3 Bb6 10. Rd1 $36 ) ( 7... Bc5 $6 8. Bxe6 fxe6 9. Qb3 Qd7 10. Qxb7 Rb8 11. Qa6 Nf6 12. b3 O-O 13. Bb2 $16 ) ( 7... Qd6 8. Qb3 b6 ( 8... O-O-O $6 9. Ng5 $16 ) 9. Rd1 $36 ) ( 7... Nf6 8. Qb3 Qd7 ( 8... Qc8 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Ng5 Nd8 11. Qg3 $36 ) 9. Qxb7 Rb8 10. Qa6 Rb6 11. Qa4 Rb4 12. Bxe6 Rxa4 13. Bxd7+ Kxd7 14. a3 $14 { [%csl Ra4] } ) ( 7... Bd6 8. Bxe6 fxe6 9. Nc4 $1 Qd7 ( 9... Nge7 $6 10. Ng5 Qd7 11. Qh5+ Ng6 12. f4 O-O-O 13. Nxd6+ cxd6 14. Bd2 Kb8 15. b4 $16 ) 10. Nxd6+ ( 10. b4 $5 a6 11. Bb2 ) 10... Qxd6 ( 10... cxd6 11. Nxd4 $14 ) 11. Ng5 Nf6 12. f4 Qd7 13. e5 Nd5 14. Qg4 O-O 15. Qh3 g6 16. Bd2 $5 ( 16. Nxe6 Rf7 ) 16... Rf5 17. Rac1 Raf8 18. Ne4 $14 b6 19. a3 a5 20. Qd3 ) ( 7... Qd7 $6 8. Bb5 $1 Nge7 ( 8... Bd6 9. Nb3 ) 9. Nb3 a6 10. Nc5 Qd6 11. Nxe6 fxe6 ( 11... axb5 12. Nexd4 ) 12. Bc4 $16 ) 8. a3 { [%cal Gb2b4] } ( 8. Bb5 Ne7 9. Qa4 ( 9. Nb3 Bg4 $1 { A simple path available once the d2-knight stops defending f3. } 10. Qxd4 ( 10. e5 $6 Qg6 ) 10... Bxf3 ( 10... a6 11. Qxf6 gxf6 12. Be2 Rg8 13. Rd1 Ne5 $11 ) 11. Qxf6 gxf6 12. gxf3 O-O-O 13. Kh1 a6 14. Be2 Ng6 15. Be3 Bd6 $11 { The kingside and centre dark-squares are a good offset for the bishop pair. } ) ( 9. Nc4 h6 $1 ( 9... O-O-O 10. Bg5 Qg6 11. Rc1 $36 ) 10. Na5 O-O-O 11. Nxc6 Nxc6 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Qa4 Kb7 ( 13... c5 14. Qxa7 Bg4 $11 ) 14. Bd2 c5 $11 ) 9... O-O-O ( 9... a6 $14 { In this move order this is also an option. } 10. Nxd4 Rc8 11. Bxc6+ Nxc6 12. Nxc6 Bd7 13. Qd4 Qxc6 14. Nb3 Qg6 15. Bf4 c5 16. Qd5 Qf6 17. Be5 Qe7 $11 { [%cal Gd7e6] } ) 10. Nb3 Bg4 { Again this is a major idea once the knight leaves d2. } 11. Bg5 Qg6 12. Nbd2 f6 13. Bf4 ( 13. Bh4 Bxf3 14. Nxf3 Qxe4 15. Rac1 ( 15. Bg3 { Transposes to 13.Nf4. } ) 15... a6 16. Bc4 ( 16. Bxa6 bxa6 17. Qxa6+ Kd7 18. Bg3 Qd5 19. b4 Nxb4 20. Qa4+ Nec6 21. Nxd4 Bc5 22. Nb3 Bd6 23. Rfd1 Ra8 24. Rxd5 Rxa4 25. Nc5+ Ke7 26. Rxd6 cxd6 27. Nxa4 Ra8 $11 ) 16... Kb8 17. Bg3 { Transposes to 13.Nf4. } ( 17. Rfe1 $6 Qf5 18. Bg3 Qa5 19. Qxa5 Nxa5 20. Bxa6 Nec6 21. Bf1 Bd6 22. Rb1 b6 $15 ) ) 13... Bxf3 14. Nxf3 Qxe4 15. Bg3 a6 16. Bc4 { Looks like a tricky position. Black is fine of course. } ( 16. Bxa6 bxa6 17. Qxa6+ Kd7 18. Rac1 Qd5 { Transposes to 13.Nh4. } ) 16... Kb8 $14 ( 16... Ne5 { This is objectively fine, but involves some counter-intuitive play. } 17. Bxe5 fxe5 18. Rac1 Nd5 ( 18... Kb8 $5 19. Ng5 Qc6 20. Qxc6 Nxc6 21. Nf7 Bd6 22. Nxh8 Rxh8 23. Bxa6 e4 24. Bc4 Bb4 25. Bd5 e3 $11 ) 19. Rfe1 ( 19. Bxa6 Nb6 20. Qb5 Kb8 21. Rfe1 bxa6 22. Qxb6+ cxb6 23. Rxe4 Bd6 24. Nxe5 Bxe5 25. Rxe5 Rhe8 $11 ) ( 19. Qa5 Kb8 20. Rfe1 Bb4 21. Qxc7+ Nxc7 22. Rxe4 Bd6 $11 ) 19... Nb6 20. Qb3 ( 20. Qa5 Qg6 21. Nxe5 Qf6 22. Bb3 d3 23. Rcd1 Bd6 24. Rxd3 ( 24. Nxd3 Rhe8 $11 ) 24... Bxe5 25. Rxd8+ { ˝-˝ (25) Kovalenko,I-Straka,Z (2577) ICCF email 2016 } 25... Kxd8 $1 ( 25... Rxd8 26. Qxe5 Qxe5 27. Rxe5 $14 ) 26. Qxe5 ( 26. Rxe5 Nd7 27. Re1 Re8 28. Rxe8+ Kxe8 29. Qxc7 Qxb2 $11 ) 26... Qxe5 27. Rxe5 Nd7 $11 ) ( 20. Be6+ Kb8 ) 20... Qf4 2