1. Be4 Qh5 12. Nf1 Bd5 { Exchanging the strong bishop on e4. } 13. Ng3 Qg4 14. b4 $1 { A try for a queenside initiative at the cost of a pawn. } 14... Nxb4 15. Ba3 Nbc6 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 17. Rb1 Bxe4 18. Rxe4 ( 18. Nxe4 Nc6 19. Qb3 b6 20. Neg5 ( 20. Qxf7 Qd7 21. Qc4 Qd5 $15 ) 20... Qd7 { [%cal Gc6a5] } 21. a3 { A very difficult move required from White. } ( 21. Nxf7 $6 Na5 ) 21... Na5 22. Qxf7 Bxa3 23. Qa2 Be7 24. Nf7 Rhf8 25. Nxd8 Rxd8 $44 { The position is very double-edged, but Black has four connected passed apwns after all! } ) 18... Qg6 { There is a plenty of options, but White ultimately doesn't break through decisively with the attack and the whole position is sound for Black. } 19. e6 ( 19. Qa4 Nc6 20. Qb5 Bb4 21. Rxb4 Nxb4 22. Qxb4 d3 $13 ) ( 19. Qb3 Qb6 20. Qd3 Qa6 $11 ) 19... Nc6 20. Qb3 b6 21. Qb5 ( 21. Qa4 Rd6 ) 21... Rd6 22. Rc1 ( 22. Nh4 Qf6 23. Nhf5 Rxe6 24. Nh5 Qd8 25. Rxe6 fxe6 26. Qxc6 exf5 27. Qa8+ Kd7 28. Qd5+ Kc8 $11 ) 22... Kb7 23. exf7 Rf6 ( 23... a6 $5 24. Qc4 d3 ) 24. Nxd4 Nxd4 25. Rxd4 Rxf7 { Finally White has to settle for a perpetual. } 26. Qd5+ Kb8 27. Qd8+ Kb7 28. Qd5+ $11 ) ( 8. e5 Qg6 ( 8... Nxe5 $2 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 Qf6 11. Ne4 $18 ) 9. Bxe6 Qxe6 10. Ng5 Qd5 11. e6 fxe6 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 { Black can simply accept the coming exchanges. } 13. Re1 Ne5 14. Qh5+ g6 15. Rxe5 gxh5 16. Rxe6+ Kf7 17. Re5 Re8 18. Rxe8 Kxe8 { White needs to play a few good moves to even keep equality. } 19. Ne4 Bg7 20. Bf4 Nf6 21. Nxf6+ Bxf6 22. Bxc7 Kf7 $11 ) ( 8. Qa4 $5 { One of the very serious options. } 8... O-O-O 9. Rd1 $14 { A very critical novelty. } ( 9. Bb5 Nge7 { Transposes to 8.Nb5. } ) ( 9. b4 $5 Bxb4 ( 9... Kb8 $2 10. b5 Ne5 11. Nxe5 Qxe5 12. Nf3 $16 { 1-0 (36) Salem,A (2633) -Christiansen,J (2501) Almaty 2022 } ) 10. Rb1 Bxd2 11. Ba6 $1 ( 11. Bxd2 $6 Bxc4 12. Qxc4 Nge7 $15 ) 11... bxa6 12. Bxd2 ( 12. Qxc6 Bd5 $1 { Black holds his own by returning some material. } 13. Qc2 Bxc1 14. Rfxc1 Bc6 $1 15. Qxc6 Qxc6 16. Rxc6 Nf6 17. Rxa6 Nxe4 18. Rxa7 Rhe8 19. Rbb7 Re7 20. Rb4 Rd5 21. Nxd4 Nd6 $11 ) 12... Bg4 $1 { An importantresource. Black creates counterplay by threatening to wreak White's kingside. } 13. Bg5 ( 13. Rfc1 $6 Nge7 14. Bg5 Qd6 { White needs to attack with energy for several next moves: } 15. e5 Qg6 16. e6 Qxe6 17. Qxa6+ Kd7 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 19. Rxc7+ Kxc7 20. Qxa7+ Kd6 21. Qxd4+ Qd5 22. Qxg4 { White is a whole rook down, but keeps some threats. Neverthless, Black has a strong disruptive move and ultimately obtains slightly better chances: } 22... h5 $1 23. Bf4+ ( 23. Qb4+ Ke6 24. Qxe7+ Kf5 $15 ) 23... Kc6 24. Qe2 Qd3 $1 25. Rc1+ Kb5 26. Qxe7 Qd1+ 27. Qe1 Qxe1+ 28. Rxe1 h4 $15 ) 13... Qd6 14. e5 Qd5 15. Rfc1 Nge7 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 17. Qxa6+ Kd7 18. Rxc7+ Ke8 { The king has escaped the danger zone. White needs to find a drawing trick: } 19. Rb5 Qe6 20. Rbb7 Qxa6 21. Rxe7+ Kf8 22. Rxf7+ $11 ) ( 9. Re1 $14 Nge7 { One of the good moves. There are others moves as well. } 10. b4 Ng6 11. Bxe6+ ( 11. b5 Bxc4 12. bxc6 Ba6 13. cxb7+ Bxb7 $13 ) ( 11. Rb1 Kb8 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Nb3 Nge5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Na5 Ka8 16. Qb5 Rb8 17. f4 Ng6 18. Nc6 bxc6 19. Qxc6+ Rb7 20. Qe8+ $11 ) 11... Qxe6 12. b5 ( 12. Rb1 Bd6 13. b5 ( 13. Rb3 Kb8 14. Bb2 d3 15. b5 Nce5 16. Nd4 Qc8 17. Nc6+ Nxc6 18. bxc6 b6 $13 ) 13... Nce5 { Both sides will attempt to break thorugh on opposite flanks: } 14. Qxa7 Nd3 15. Rf1 Ngf4 16. Qa8+ Kd7 17. Qxb7 Qg4 18. g3 Qh3 19. Nh4 Ne2+ 20. Kh1 Bxg3 21. Qc6+ Kc8 22. Qa8+ $11 ) 12... Nb4 13. Qxa7 ( 13. Nb3 Qb6 $1 14. Rd1 Nc2 15. Rb1 d3 $13 ) 13... Nc2 14. Bb2 Nxe1 15. Rxe1 Qb6 16. Qa8+ Kd7 17. Qa4 Bc5 { White has full compensation for the exchange, but Black is not worse. } 18. Nc4 ( 18. Nb3 d3 19. Nxc5+ Qxc5 20. Rc1 Qb6 21. Bxg7 Rhe8 $13 ) 18... Qa7 19. Nce5+ Nxe5 20. Nxe5+ Ke8 21. Qc4 Rf8 22. Nd3 Be7 23. Qxc7 g5 $13 ) 9... Bg4 $1 { The only good move according to computer analysis. } 10. h3 h5 { Classical resource, somewhat reminiscent of the Exchange Ruy Lopez. } 11. e5 { Throwing in this move allows White to accept the piece sacrifice on g4. } ( 11. Bb5 Nge7 12. b4 d3 13. Rb1 Qg6 14. Kh1 Kb8 15. Bb2 f5 { Very sharp and forcing, putting pressure on White. } 16. Bxc6 Nxc6 17. b5 Nb4 18. a3 Nc2 19. Ne5 Qe6 $13 20. f3 { White had to do something against ...fxe4, This offers Black a draw by a simple perpetual check, but in other lines White can only be worse. } 20... Bxh3 21. gxh3 fxe4 22. Nxe4 Qxh3+ 23. Kg1 Bc5+ 24. Nxc5 Qg3+ $11 ) ( 11. Re1 g5 $1 { A very similar line in terms of this idea occurs in the Exchange Ruy Lopez. Black wants to take on f3 and play ...g4. } 12. b4 ( 12. e5 Qg7 ) 12... Bxf3 13. Nxf3 g4 14. e5 Qg7 15. Ng5 Bxb4 16. Rb1 $1 { White should not be afraid to give up a rook to get his own attack going. } 16... Bxe1 17. Rxb7 Bxf2+ $1 { Giving up part of the material to lure White's king forward. } 18. Kxf2 Qxe5 19. Rb5 $1 g3+ 20. Kf3 ( 20. Kf1 $6 Qf6+ 21. Nf3 Rd6 $17 ) 20... Qf6+ 21. Kxg3 Nge7 { After these wild complications, White is the one having to be a bit more careful, e.g. } 22. Nxf7 Rdf8 23. Bg5 Rhg8 24. Kh2 Rxg5 25. Nxg5 Qf4+ 26. Kh1 Qc1+ $11 ) 11... Nxe5 $5 ( 11... Qg6 { Also good } ) 12. hxg4 ( 12. Qxa7 Nxc4 13. hxg4 hxg4 14. Qa8+ Kd7 15. Qa4+ $11 { This should simply end in a rpetition. } ) 12... hxg4 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Nf1 Bc5 15. b4 Qh5 16. Ng3 Qh2+ 17. Kf1 Bb6 18. Bxf7 ( 18. Bf4 $2 Nf6 19. Rac1 Kb8 $19 { [%csl Rf1][%cal Gd8e8,Gh2h1] } ) 18... Kb8 19. Qb3 Nh6 20. Bxh6 Qxh6 21. Qd3 { All of this has been absolutely forced and now we have more of a choice. } 21... Rdf8 ( 21... c6 $44 { With some ideas invloving ...Bc7 } ) 22. Bg6 Rf6 23. Be4 ( 23. Bf5 Rhf8 24. Kg1 ( 24. a4 { This leads to a picturesque drawing idea: } 24... c6 25. b5 g6 26. a5 Bc5 27. Bxg4 Rxf2+ 28. Kg1 Bd6 29. Qxd4 Bxg3 30. Qd8+ Rxd8 31. Rxd8+ Kc7 32. Rd7+ $11 ) 24... Rxf5 { Black wins two minor pieces for the rook. } 25. Nxf5 Qf4 26. Re1 a6 27. g3 Qxf5 28. Qxf5 Rxf5 29. Re4 a5 30. bxa5 Rxa5 31. Rxg4 c5 { [%csl Gc5,Gd4] Even in the endgame, the situation does not lose it's sharpness. Objectively it's dynamically balanced, e.g. } 32. Rb1 Ka7 33. Rg6 Ra6 34. Kf1 c4 $44 ) 23... Rhf8 { The game is very complex, but Black is the side with the more sheltered king, which should make him quite comfortable in practical play. } 24. Rd2 c6 25. Rb1 Qh2 26. Ke1 Bc7 27. Kd1 Rxf2 28. Rxf2 Rxf2 29. Ne2 a6 30. Kc2 Qd6 $44 ) 8... Bd6 { [%cal Gg8e7] } ( 8... Nge7 $5 { Another decent option } 9. b4 Ng6 10. Bb5 Be7 { ˝-˝ (40) Grischuk,A (2771) -Radjabov,T (2756) Shamkir 2019 } 11. Re1 $13 ) 9. b4 ( 9. Qb3 $6 { This is dubious. } 9... O-O-O { 1-0 (42) Bluebaum,M (2642) -Christiansen,J (2582) Warsaw 2021 } 10. Re1 Nge7 $15 { This is a worse version of the 8.Qa4 lines for White. } ) ( 9. Bxe6 Qxe6 ( 9... fxe6 $6 10. Nc4 ) 10. b4 ( 10. e5 Be7 11. Nb3 O-O-O 12. Nbxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qd7 14. Be3 Bc5 15. Qe2 Bxd4 16. Rfd1 Qe6 17. Bxd4 a6 $11 { The knight will join the game shortly. } ) 10... a6 { Stopping b5. } 11. Re1 ( 11. Bb2 Nge7 ) 11... Nh6 $1 { Black equalizes easily like this, bot falling into 11...Nge7? 12.e5! } 12. Nb3 O-O-O 13. Bb2 d3 14. Nbd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 f6 16. Qxd3 Ng4 17. Rad1 Ne5 $11 ) ( 9. e5 Nxe5 10. Bxe6 ( 10. Re1 O-O-O ) 10... fxe6 { Black needs to recapture with the pawn not to run into an e-file x-ray. } 11. Re1 ( 11. Qa4+ Nc6 $11 ) ( 11. Nxd4 O-O-O $11 ) 11... O-O-O 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Nf3 ( 13. Qa4 Kb8 ) 13... Bf4 14. Qb3 Rd6 15. Bxf4 Qxf4 16. Rxe6 Nh6 $11 { Black is already developed and still a pawn up. White can keep the balance, but he is not able to achieve more than that. } ) 9... a6 { Simply preventing b4-b5. } ( 9... Nge7 10. Bxe6 Qxe6 11. b5 Ne5 12. Nxd4 Qd7 13. f4 Rd8 14. N2b3 c5 $13 ) 10. Re1 ( 10. Bxe6 fxe6 $5 ( 10... Qxe6 { Transpose } ) 11. Nc4 e5 12. Qb3 Nge7 $13 ) ( 10. e5 $5 Nxe5 11. Re1 { This leads to very sharp consequences, but Black is doing ok. } ( 11. Nxe5 Qxe5 12. Nf3 Qh5 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Qxd4 Ne7 15. Bf4 Bxf4 16. Qxf4 Nd5 17. Qe4 O-O-O 18. Qxe6+ Kb8 $11 { 1/2 (21) Schleef,H-Wittal,W freechess.de 2021 } ) 11... O-O-O 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. b5 axb5 14. Bxe6+ fxe6 15. Nf3 Bf4 16. a4 b4 17. a5 Rd6 18. Qb3 Ne7 19. a6 bxa6 { Black has so many pawns, but White creates threats and tactics. These factors balance each other out. } 20. Bxf4 Qxf4 21. Rxe6 Nd5 22. g3 Qf8 23. Rxa6 ( 23. Nxd4 Rxe6 24. Nxe6 Qd6 25. Qc4 Qxe6 26. Rxa6 Qe1+ 27. Kg2 Qd2 28. Ra8+ Kd7 29. Qb5+ c6 30. Qb7+ Nc7 31. Rxh8 Qd5+ $11 ) 23... Rxa6 24. Rxa6 Nb6 25. Qe6+ Kb7 26. Rxb6+ cxb6 27. Qd7+ $11 ) ( 10. Qa4 Ne7 11. Bxe6 ( 11. b5 O-O 12. Bxe6 axb5 $1 ) 11... Qxe6 12. b5 Na7 ( 12... Ne5 $5 ) 13. bxa6+ ( 13. b6+ Nac6 14. Nxd4 Qg6 15. Nc4 cxb6 16. Nxc6 Nxc6 17. Rb1 O-O 18. Nxd6 Qxd6 19. Rxb6 Qe7 20. Be3 Rfd8 21. Rfb1 Rd7 $11 { ˝-˝ (30) Sasikiran,K (2548) -Vinchev,S (2481) GER email 2018 } ) 13... Nac6 14. Nxd4 Rxa6 15. Nxe6 Rxa4 16. Nxg7+ Kd7 17. Nh5 Kc8 $44 { Black has a good compensation thanks to the weakness on a3 and the active rook. ˝-˝ (30) Zeihen,P (2285) -Polyakov,E (2182) ICCF email 2017 } ) 10... Nge7 11. e5 Nxe5 ( 11... Bxe5 $6 { Do not capture like this. } 12. Ne4 Qg6 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Bxe6 fxe6 ( 14... Qxe6 15. Ng3 $16 ) 15. Nc5 $36 ) 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Bd3 ( 13. Ne4 Qg6 14. Bxe6 Qxe6 15. Nc5 Qd5 { An interesting improvement. } ( 15... Qf5 $5 16. f4 ( 16. g4 Qf6 ) 16... Bd6 17. Nxb7 Qd5 18. Nxd6+ Qxd6 19. Qe2 Rd8 20. Qe4 Rd7 21. Qa8+ Rd8 $11 { 1/2 (22) Yurov,A (2475) -Botev,K (2463) ICCF email 2020 } ) 16. Qh5 Ng6 17. f4 d3 18. Bb2 ( 18. fxe5 b6 $1 19. Ne4 Qd4+ 20. Kf1 Qxa1 21. Nf6+ Kf8 22. Qf3 Rd8 23. Nd7+ Kg8 24. Nf6+ Kf8 $11 ) 18... d2 19. Rxe5+ Nxe5 20. Qxe5+ Qxe5 21. fxe5 O-O-O { This is an attractive line, because Black can be absolutely sure to be at least fine with his play here. } 22. Rd1 b6 23. Ne4 Rd3 24. Kf2 Rhd8 25. Bc3 f6 26. exf6 gxf6 $13 { White is not able to just capture the d2-pawn without giving something up. For the engine it's equal, but it could become a bit tricky for White over the board. } ) ( 13. Qh5 Ng6 14. Ne4 Qh4 15. Qxh4 Nxh4 16. Bd3 Bf6 ( 16... Ng6 { Also fine } ) 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Re4 Ng6 19. Rxd4 Ke7 $11 { [%cal Gh8d8] White has the compensation with the pair of bishops, but Black is solid. } ) 13... Bd6 $14 { Strange, but fine. } ( 13... Bf4 14. Ne4 Qh6 15. g3 $5 ( 15. Bxf4 Qxf4 16. g3 Qg4 17. Qa4+ Bd7 18. Qc2 O-O 19. Nc5 Ng6 20. Be2 Qh3 21. Bf1 Qg4 $11 { 1/2 (30) Tauscher,K (2348) -Brorens,D (2316) ICCF email 2019 } ) 15... Bxc1 16. Rxc1 O-O 17. h4 $44 ) 14. Ne4 Qe5 15. f4 ( 15. g3 { [%cal Gc1f4] } 15... Qd5 16. Bd2 O-O 17. Rc1 Ng6 18. Ng5 Rfe8 19. Be4 Qa2 { White is almost forced to settle for a draw: } 20. Bb1 ( 20. Bxb7 Bd5 $1 21. Bxa8 Rxa8 $44 { [%csl Gd5] The weakness of the long diagonal poses an obvious danger to White. } ) ( 20. Ra1 Qc4 $11 ) 20... Qb3 21. Bc2 Qd5 22. Be4 Qa2 $11 ) 15... Qd5 16. Nxd6+ Qxd6 17. f5 Bd5 18. Qe2 ( 18. Qg4 h5 $1 19. Qxd4 O-O-O 20. Bf4 Nc6 21. Qf2 Qf6 $13 ) 18... f6 $1 { White is two pawns down for now, but he has an unpleasant e-file pin. } 19. Bb2 ( 19. a4 { [%cal Gc1a3] } 19... Kf7 20. Qh5+ g6 21. Qg4 Rag8 22. Bf4 Qd8 23. fxg6+ hxg6 24. Bg3 Nf5 25. Bxf5 gxf5 26. Qxf5 Rg5 27. Qd3 Bc6 $13 ) 19... Bb3 $1 { Protecting the d4-pawn and keeping the rook from d1. Black is ready for ...Kf7 next. } 20. Rac1 ( 20. a4 Kf7 21. Qh5+ g6 22. Qh4 ( 22. Qh6 Rae8 ) 22... gxf5 $1 23. Qh5+ ( 23. Bxf5 Nxf5 24. Qh5+ Kg7 25. Qg4+ $11 ) 23... Kg7 24. Bc1 Rhe8 25. Bh6+ Kh8 26. Bxf5 Qd5 $1 27. Bg7+ ( 27. g4 Ng6 $1 28. Bxg6 hxg6 29. Qh4 Qf7 30. Be3+ Kg8 31. Bxd4 g5 $11 ) 27... Kxg7 28. Qxh7+ Kf8 29. Qh6+ ( 29. Be6 Qxe6 30. Rxe6 Bxe6 31. Qh6+ Kf7 $11 ) 29... Kf7 30. Qh7+ $11 ) 20... Kf7 ( 20... h5 $5 ) 21. Qh5+ ( 21. Bc4+ Bxc4 22. Qxc4+ Nd5 23. Re6 Qd7 24. Bxd4 Rhe8 25. Rce1 c6 $11 { The knight is very solid on d5. White has compensation, but nothing more. } ) ( 21. Qf3 Rhe8 ( 21... Rhb8 $5 22. Be4 ( 22. Re6 Qd7 ) 22... d3 23. Bxd3 Kg8 24. Bxa6 Bd5 25. Bc4 c6 $11 ) 22. Qxb7 Kf8 { We return some material, but fully consolidate our position. } 23. Re2 ( 23. Qf3 Rad8 $13 ) 23... Rad8 24. Qxa6 ( 24. Rce1 Bf7 25. Qxa6 Qxa6 26. Bxa6 d3 27. Rd2 Rd6 28. Bxd3 Bc4 29. Re3 Red8 30. Rxe7 Kxe7 31. Re2+ Re6 32. fxe6 ( 32. Bxc4 $2 Rxe2 33. Bxe2 Rd2 $19 ) 32... Bxd3 33. Re3 Bb5 $11 ) 24... Qxa6 25. Bxa6 d3 26. Rd2 Bc2 27. Bxd3 Bxd3 28. Rcd1 Nxf5 29. Rxd3 Re1+ 30. Rxe1 Rxd3 31. Rc1 Rb3 $11 ) 21... Kf8 ( 21... g6 $6 22. Qh4 $40 ) 22. a4 ( 22. Bc4 Bxc4 23. Rxc4 Nc6 24. Re6 Qd7 25. a4 d3 { White's rooks have left the first rank. The d-pawn push suddenly forces White to seek a forced draw. } ( 25... Re8 $5 { Also equalizes. } 26. Rxe8+ Qxe8 27. Qxe8+ Kxe8 28. b5 axb5 29. axb5 Ne7 30. Rxc7 d3 31. Kf2 Kd8 32. Rxb7 Re8 33. Rb8+ ( 33. b6 Nc6 ) 33... Nc8 34. Bc1 Kd7 35. b6 ( 35. Rb7+ Kd8 ) 35... Nd6 36. Rxe8 Nxe8 $11 { [%cal Gd7c6] } ) 26. Bxf6 ( 26. b5 d2 27. Qd1 axb5 28. axb5 Qd3 29. bxc6 Qxc4 30. Qxd2 bxc6 31. Qe3 Qb4 32. Ba3 Qxa3 33. Re8+ Rxe8 34. Qxa3+ $11 ) 26... d2 $1 27. Bxg7+ Qxg7 28. f6 { White has to force a repetition whether we put the queen on g6 or d7. } 28... Qg6 ( 28... Qd7 29. Qh6+ Kf7 30. Qh5+ Kxe6 31. Qh3+ Kd6 32. Qd3+ Ke6 $11 ) 29. Qc5+ Kg8 30. Qd5 Kf8 $11 ) 22... Bf7 23. Qf3 Qxb4 $5 { We have as many as three pawns now. White keeps playing for the initative. } ( 23... c6 $13 ) 24. Re2 Nd5 25. Bc4 ( 25. Rc4 Qd6 26. Rxd4 ( 26. Bxd4 Kg8 ) 26... c6 27. Bc4 Kg8 28. Ba3 Qc7 29. Rde4 Rd8 30. Bxd5 ( 30. Re7 Nxe7 31. Bxf7+ Kxf7 32. Rxe7+ Qxe7 33. Qb3+ Rd5 34. Bxe7 Kxe7 35. Qxb7+ Rd7 $11 ) 30... Rxd5 31. Re7 Qd8 32. h3 h5 33. Rxb7 Rd7 $11 ) 25... Nc3 $1 26. Bxc3 dxc3 27. Bxf7 Qd4+ 28. Re3 Kxf7 { Finally we get a major piece ending that is fast approaching a clearer type of equality. } 29. Rd1 Qxa4 30. Qd5+ Kf8 31. Rxc3 ( 31. Qc5+ $11 { White can just draw like this. } ) 31... Qb5 $1 32. Qxb5 ( 32. Qa2 Re8 $11 ) 32... axb5 33. Rxc7 h5 34. Rdd7 Rh7 35. h4 b6 36. Kf2 Re8 37. Rb7 Kg8 38. Rxb6 g6 $11 { Finally the game completely liquidates to a drawn rook rook endgame. } *

