1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Bxc4 Nc6 6. O-O Be6 7. Bb5 { In this lesson we move to one of the main options. It is not so popular over the board on the high-level anymore. The line is regarded to be theoretically completely fine for Black, and the main tests of it are played out in correspondence games. } 7... Bc5 { There are a lot of choices, but other than 8.b4 and 8.Nbd2 they don't make much sense. } 8. b4 { The main challenge. } ( 8. Qc2 Bb6 9. Bxc6+ ( 9. a4 a5 ) 9... bxc6 10. Qxc6+ Bd7 11. Qc4 Be6 $11 { White has prematurely released the tension by taking on c6 and now has nothing better than a draw. } ) ( 8. Nbd2 Ne7 9. Ng5 ( 9. Nb3 Qd6 ( 9... Bb6 $5 10. Nbxd4 ( 10. Nfxd4 Bd7 ) 10... Bd7 ) 10. Nxc5 ( 10. Bf4 Qxf4 11. Nxc5 Bg4 12. Qxd4 ( 12. Nxb7 O-O $13 ) 12... Bxf3 13. gxf3 O-O 14. Qe3 Qh4 $11 ) 10... Qxc5 11. Nxd4 O-O-O { The long castling leads to a forced equality, where Black repeatedly exploits the central squares with the rooks to his benefit. } 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Qa4 Rd4 $1 ( 13... Nd4 14. Bc4 { is not as accurate. } ) 14. Be3 Rxa4 15. Bxc5 Rxe4 16. Rfe1 Rxe1+ 17. Rxe1 Rd8 18. Rxe6 Rd5 19. b4 b6 20. Bxe7 Rxb5 21. Rxc6 Re5 $11 ) 9... Qd7 $1 { Transpose to 8.Bbd2. } ( 9... Qd6 $6 10. Qh5 g6 11. Qh4 $36 { The queen on d6 will come under attack with Nc4. } ) 10. Nxe6 ( 10. Ndf3 f6 11. Nxe6 ( { Similar is } 11. b4 Bb6 ) 11... Qxe6 12. b4 ( 12. Nxd4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 a6 14. Qc4 Qd6 15. Bxc6+ Nxc6 16. Be3 O-O-O $11 { Black has clearly equalized. He can use the central files with ...Rhe8 and ...Qd3. } ) 12... Bb6 ( 12... Bxb4 13. Nxd4 Qxe4 { A bit risky } ) 13. Nxd4 Qe5 14. Bxc6+ bxc6 15. Nb3 Qxe4 16. Re1 Qf5 17. Be3 ( 17. Qe2 O-O ) 17... Kf7 $11 { White has some compensation, but Black's rooks are already coming into the game and there won't be clear targets in his camp. } ) ( 10. Qh5 g6 11. Qf3 O-O-O $15 ) ( 10. Nb3 Bb6 ) 10... Qxe6 11. Nb3 Bb6 ( { Another decent option is } 11... Qd6 12. Bf4 Qxf4 13. Nxc5 a6 ) 12. Nxd4 Qg6 13. Nxc6 ( 13. Nf5 O-O $11 ) ( 13. Nf3 Rd8 14. Qc2 O-O 15. Bd2 Qh5 $11 ) 13... Nxc6 14. Bf4 O-O { This is pretty much a draw. } 15. Bxc6 Qxc6 16. Rc1 Qxe4 17. Bxc7 Bxc7 18. Rxc7 Rac8 $11 ) ( 8. Ng5 Qd7 ( 8... Qe7 $5 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Qc2 Rb8 $1 ( 10... Bd7 11. Nf3 Bb6 12. a4 a5 13. Nbd2 Nf6 14. b3 O-O 15. Ba3 c5 16. Rac1 $14 ) 11. Nxe6 ( 11. Nf3 Nf6 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Nbd2 Bb6 15. Qxc6+ Kf8 $13 { [%cal Gh8g8] } ) 11... fxe6 12. Nd2 Nf6 13. e5 ( 13. Nf3 e5 ) ( 13. Nb3 Nd7 ) 13... Nd5 14. Ne4 Bb6 15. Qxc6+ Qd7 16. Qxd7+ Kxd7 $11 ) 9. Nd2 ( 9. Nxe6 $6 Qxe6 $15 ) 9... Nge7 { Transposes to 8.Bbd2. } ( 9... Bg4 $5 10. f3 ( 10. Qc2 $6 Bb6 $15 ) ( 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. f3 d3+ 12. Kh1 Bh5 13. Nh3 f6 14. Nb3 Bb6 $13 ) 10... Bh5 11. Nh3 f6 12. Nf4 Bf7 13. Nd3 Bd6 14. Re1 ( 14. f4 a6 15. Ba4 Nh6 $13 ) 14... O-O-O 15. Qa4 a6 16. Bxc6 Qxc6 17. Qxc6 bxc6 18. Nb3 Ne7 $11 ) ) ( 8. Ne5 Ne7 9. Bg5 f6 ( 9... Qd6 10. Bf4 Qd8 $11 ) 10. Bxc6+ ( 10. Bxf6 { Another move order with additional possibilities. } 10... gxf6 11. Bxc6+ ( 11. Qh5+ $6 Kf8 12. Qh6+ Kg8 13. Qxf6 Nxe5 14. Qxe6+ Nf7 15. Bc4 Qe8 16. f4 Ng6 $15 { The attack is not enough for equality. } ) 11... Nxc6 ( 11... bxc6 12. Qh5+ Kf8 13. Qh6+ Kg8 14. Qxf6 Qd6 15. Qg5+ Kf8 16. Qf6+ $11 ) 12. Qh5+ Kf8 13. Nxc6 Qd6 14. Na5 Bb6 $13 { It's doubled edged, but White has to watch out for this bishop pair. } ) 10... Nxc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bxf6 { This is just a simplifying tactical operation that leads to easy equality. } 12... Qxf6 13. Qh5+ Qg6 14. Qxc5 Qxe4 15. Nd2 Qd5 $11 ) 8... Bb6 ( 8... Bxb4 $2 9. Qa4 a5 10. a3 Be7 11. Nxd4 $16 ) 9. a4 ( 9. Bb2 Ne7 10. Bxc6+ Nxc6 11. b5 Na5 12. Bxd4 O-O 13. Nc3 Re8 $13 ) ( 9. Nbd2 Ne7 ( { Maybe possible is } 9... a6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 ) 10. Ng5 O-O { There are no games here, but there are some interesting, double-edged lines and it's useful to know them. } 11. Qh5 h6 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Bc4 d3 $1 { A very energetic move. Black attempts to take over the initiative and not just defend. } ( 13... Qd6 $6 14. Nf3 ) 14. Nf3 ( 14. Bxe6+ Kh8 15. Nf3 Qd6 16. Bg4 Nd4 17. Ne5 Kg8 18. Nd7 Rfd8 19. e5 Qd5 $13 ) 14... Qe8 $1 15. Qh3 ( 15. Bxe6+ Kh8 16. Qh3 Qg6 $13 ) ( 15. Qg4 Ng6 16. Bxe6+ Kh8 17. Bf5 Nge5 $13 ) 15... Nd4 16. Bd2 ( 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. Rb1 ( 17. Bxe6+ Kh7 ) 17... Rd8 18. Bxe6+ Kh7 19. Bg5 Rd6 $13 { It's very complex, but Black shouldn't be worse. } ) 16... Nxf3+ 17. gxf3 Kh7 18. Bxe6 Nc6 { White can try to create an attack on the g-file, but Black still has enough counterplay of his own. } 19. Bf5+ ( 19. Kh1 Nd4 ) 19... Kg8 20. Kh1 Nd4 21. Bxh6 Nxf5 22. exf5 Rf7 23. Rg1 Bxf2 24. f6 ( 24. Bxg7 Rxg7 25. Rxg7+ Kxg7 26. Qg2+ Kf7 27. Qxf2 Rd8 $11 { [%csl Gd3] } ) 24... Bxg1 25. Rxg1 Rxf6 26. Rxg7+ Kh8 27. Rg4 Rg6 28. Bf4+ Kg8 29. Be5 Rxg4 30. Qxg4+ ( 30. Qh8+ Kf7 31. Qf6+ $11 ) 30... Kf7 31. Qf5+ Ke7 32. Bf4 Qd7 $11 ) 9... a6 ( 9... a5 $2 { This is just bad. } 10. bxa5 Rxa5 11. Nbd2 $16 ) 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Nbd2 { Less common, but perhaps a bit more challening than 11.Bb2 } ( 11. a5 Ba7 12. Bb2 Nf6 { Transpose to 11.Nb2. Transposes to 11.Nb2. } ) ( 11. Bb2 Nf6 12. a5 Ba7 13. Bxd4 ( 13. Nxd4 Qd6 $5 { Just to keep the tension. } ( 13... Bxd4 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. Bxd4 Nxe4 16. Bxg7 Rg8 17. Be5 O-O-O $11 ) 14. Nxe6 Qxe6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Nd2 O-O 17. Rc1 Qd6 $11 { [%csl Rb4] } ) ( 13. Nbd2 O-O 14. Qc2 ( 14. Rc1 Re8 15. Ne5 ( 15. Rxc6 Qe7 $13 { [%csl Rb4] } ) 15... Bd5 $1 16. Nxc6 Bxc6 17. Rxc6 Qe7 $11 ) 14... Re8 ( 14... Nh5 15. g3 Qd6 $13 ) 15. Qxc6 Bd7 16. Qxa6 Qb8 17. Qd3 Bb5 18. Nc4 Qb7 $11 { 1/2 (23) Gerhards,G (2323) -Steiger,W (2299) ICCF email 2009 } ( 18... Rxe4 19. Nxd4 Qd8 $11 ) ) ( 13. Qd3 O-O ( 13... Nh5 14. g3 ) 14. Rc1 ( 14. Nbd2 c5 15. bxc5 Bxc5 16. Rfc1 ( 16. Bxd4 Bb4 ) 16... Bb4 17. Ba3 ( 17. Qxd4 c5 18. Qe3 Bxa5 19. Bxf6 Bxd2 20. Nxd2 Qxf6 $11 { Kenneskog,T (2285) -Ventura Bolet,M (2089) /Barcelona ESP 2014 Kenneskog,T (2285) -Ventura Bolet,M (2089) /Barcelona ESP 2014 } ) 17... c5 18. Bxb4 cxb4 19. Nxd4 ( 19. Rc6 Rb8 ) 19... Re8 $11 ) ( 14. Bxd4 Rb8 $11 { [%csl Rb4] } ) 14... Nh5 { The most direct choice. } ( { Also possible are } 14... Qe7 ) ( 14... Qb8 ) 15. g3 f5 $1 16. exf5 Rxf5 ( 16... Bxf5 $6 17. Qc4+ ) 17. Nbd2 Qd5 18. Re1 c5 19. bxc5 Bxc5 20. Rac1 Bb4 $5 { Black equalizes completely by force. } 21. Nxd4 Raf8 22. Rxe6 Rxf2 23. Qe4 Qxe4 24. Nxe4 Rxb2 25. Rxa6 ( 25. Nc6 Bd6 ) 25... Ra2 $11 ) ( 13. Re1 O-O ( { Other goood options are: Other good options are: } 13... Qe7 ) ( 13... d3 ) 14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Nxd4 ( 15. Qxd4 Qxd4 16. Nxd4 Rfd8 17. Nxc6 Rd6 18. Rc1 ( 18. Ne7+ Kf8 19. e5 Rd4 20. exf6 gxf6 { [%csl Re7] } 21. f4 ( 21. Nc6 Rc4 ) 21... Rxf4 22. Nc3 Rd4 $11 { [%csl Re7] } ) 18... Nxe4 19. f3 Nf6 20. Na3 Kf8 21. b5 Bd7 22. Ne5 axb5 23. Nxd7+ Rxd7 24. Nxb5 c6 $1 { An important resource. } 25. Rxc6 Rd5 26. Rb6 Nd7 27. Rb7 Nc5 $11 ) 15... Ng4 $1 { A sudden turn to the kingside that works well once the knight has left f3. } 16. Nf3 { Forced if White wants to cover all the kingside squares. } ( 16. h3 Qf6 17. hxg4 Rfd8 18. e5 Qf4 $11 ) 16... Qxd1 17. Rxd1 Rfb8 18. Rd4 c5 19. bxc5 Rb5 20. c6 Rc5 $11 ) 13... Bxd4 $1 ( { The main line is } 13... Nxe4 14. Bxa7 Qxd1 15. Rxd1 Rxa7 ) 14. Nxd4 ( 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. Nxd4 c5 16. bxc5 Nxe4 $11 ) 14... Qd6 $1 { getting the queen to an excellent square and holding the whole position together. } 15. Nxe6 ( 15. Nc3 O-O 16. e5 { This just leads to many exchanges and a likely draw in the endgame. } 16... Qxe5 17. Re1 Qd6 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Qxd6 cxd6 20. Rxe6 Rad8 21. Rd1 Rfe8 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Kf1 d5 24. Na4 Nd7 25. Rc1 Re6 $11 { 1/2 (46) Hunger,H (2303) -Piaggesi,F (2211) ICCF email 2021 } ( 25... Rb8 ) ) ( 15. Na3 O-O-O $5 { A good choice if Black wants to play for a win. } ( 15... O-O { Also good } ) 16. Nac2 ( 16. Nxe6 Qxe6 17. Qe2 Kb7 18. f3 Nd5 19. Qd2 Ne7 $11 ) 16... Nxe4 17. Qd3 c5 18. bxc5 Nxc5 19. Qc3 Rhe8 $11 ) 15... Qxe6 16. f3 ( 16. Nc3 O-O 17. Qe2 Rfd8 $11 ) 16... O-O 17. Na3 c5 $5 { Black gets rid of the weakness by sacrificng it. Now the white pawns become vulnerable. } ( 17... Rab8 18. Rb1 ) 18. bxc5 { Black has various ways to achieve compensation. } 18... Rfd8 ( 18... Rab8 $5 19. Qc2 h6 20. Rfc1 ( 20. Qc4 Qe5 ) ( 20. Nc4 Rb5 ) 20... Nh5 $44 ) 19. Qc2 h5 20. Qc3 { 1/2 (20) Ozen,B (2263) -Szulc,S (2218) LSS email 2023 } 20... Rab8 $44 { Black has active pieces and some kingside prospects. It's hard for White to do anything substantial with the pawn edge. } ) 11... Nf6 ( 11... Ne7 12. Nb3 $14 ) 12. Ne5 { Hitting c6 and preparing to put the knight on the classical blockading d3-square. } ( 12. Qc2 O-O $11 ) ( 12. a5 Ba7 { Will transpose later. } ) 12... Qd6 13. Nd3 ( 13. Ndc4 { A viable pawn sacrifice, but it doesn't give White more than equality. } 13... Bxc4 14. Nxc4 Qxb4 15. Nxb6 Qxb6 16. Ba3 { The point of White's idea. Black can still attempt to castle by playing ...c5. Forcing play ensues. } 16... c5 17. Rb1 Qa5 18. Rc1 Nd7 19. Qg4 { White has to try a quick attack and not let Black castle. } 19... g6 20. e5 Qb6 { Black holds well and White has nothing better than a simplifying operation. } 21. e6 fxe6 22. Bxc5 Nxc5 23. Qxd4 O-O 24. Qxc5 Qxc5 25. Rxc5 $11 { Finally the tactics have only provided White an equal rook endgame. } ) 13... Nd7 14. Nf3 ( 14. f4 f6 $1 { f4-f5 is a threat, so this is a must. } 15. Ba3 O-O 16. Qc2 f5 17. e5 Qd5 18. Rfc1 { White will be able to grab the c6-pawn, but this is only regaining the pawn after all. Black should calmly prepare for it. } ( 18. Rac1 Rfc8 $11 ) ( 18. a5 Ba7 19. Rac1 Rfc8 $13 ) 18... Rfc8 19. Qxc6 Qxc6 20. Rxc6 Bd5 21. Rac1 { If the c6-rook retreats passively, ...Be4! can give Black an initative. } 21... Bxc6 22. Rxc6 a5 23. b5 { 1/2 (23) King,A (2200) -Preussner,M (2269) ICCF email 2023 The correspondence game was drawn based on the following logical positional repetition: } 23... Nb8 24. Rc1 Nd7 $11 { White wants to cement the rook on c6, and Black to chase it away. Neither side can make visible progress. } ) ( 14. Qc2 a5 $13 { If White is too reluctant with a4-a5, Black can use the ...a5 move to his advantage. } ) ( 14. a5 Ba7 15. Qc2 O-O $11 ) 14... O-O 15. a5 ( 15. Bf4 Qe7 16. Rc1 ( 16. a5 Ba7 { Transposes to 15.a5. } ) 16... a5 $11 { This move always appears at some point if White doesn't play a4-a5. } ) 15... Ba7 16. Bf4 Qe7 { Black is ready for the liberating ...c5 break with a likely mass liquidation. } 17. Rc1 ( 17. Qc2 c5 $11 ) 17... c5 18. bxc5 Nxc5 19. Nxc5 { The last challenging try. } ( 19. Nxd4 { This is immediately completely equal: } 19... Nxd3 20. Qxd3 Qd7 21. Be5 ( 21. Rfd1 Rfd8 ) 21... c5 22. Qg3 f6 23. Nxe6 Qxe6 24. Bd6 Rfe8 25. Bxc5 Bxc5 26. Rxc5 Qxe4 $11 { 1/2 (28) Pappier,C (2501) -Poess,F (2485) ICCF email 2022 } ) 19... Bxc5 20. Nxd4 Bd7 $1 { The last truly accurate move Black needs to make. The cooperative 20...Bxd4 would still give White some pressure. } 21. Nf5 ( 21. Bxc7 Rac8 $11 { [%cal Ge7e4] } ) 21... Bxf5 22. exf5 { The game is very likely to further simplify, the bishop and a couple of pawns can get exchanged as the following lines illustrate. } 22... Rad8 ( 22... Rfe8 $5 23. h3 Rad8 24. Qc2 Bd6 $11 { 1/2 (27) De Oliveira,J (2575) -Moll,R (2604) GER email 2016 } ) 23. Qf3 Bd6 24. Rfe1 Qf6 25. Bxd6 Qxd6 26. Rc6 ( 26. Qe3 h6 $11 { 1/2 (31) Krutous,A (2340) -Rosenhoefer,T (2312) ICCF email 2022 } ) 26... Qb4 27. Qc3 Qxc3 28. Rxc3 Rd5 $11 *[Event "?"]

