1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Bxc4 Nc6 6. O-O Be6 7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. Qb3 Qd7 9. Qxb7 (9. Ng5 {A minor option that gives us an easy game.} O-O-O $1 10. Nxe6 Re8 11. Nxf8 Rxf8 12. f3 Nf6 13. Bd2 (13. Nd2 g5 $1) 13... Rhg8 {[%cal Gg7g5] Black gets a nice kingside initiative.} 14. Na3 g5 15. Rac1 g4 $13) 9... Rb8 10. Qa6 Nf6 (10... Nge7 $5 {[%cal Ge7g6] Lately became popular, but I still prefer the main move.}) 11. Nbd2 (11. b3 $146 Nxe4 {We can gladly accept the pawn sacrifice.} 12. Re1 Nf6 13. Qc4 (13. Ba3 Bd6 14. Qc4 e5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. f4 Ng4 17. fxe5 Ngxe5 18. Qc5 Kd8 $1 {[%cal Gh8e8]} 19. Rxe5 Nxe5 20. Qxe5 Re8 21. Qg3 Rb6 22. Nd2 d3 $13) 13... Nd5 {Blocking Rxe6+, of course.} 14. Bb2 (14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Bb4 16. Bd2 O-O $11 {Our slight structural weakness is compensated by the higher activity of the pieces.}) (14. Ba3 Bb4 15. Rc1 Rb6 16. Bxb4 Ndxb4 17. Nbd2 O-O 18. a3 Nd5 $11) 14... Bb4 (14... Rb4 $6 15. Qf1) 15. Rc1 Rb6 16. Bxd4 (16. Nxd4 Ne5 17. Qe2 Ng6 $13) 16... Nxd4 17. Qxd4 O-O (17... Rd6 $11) 18. Nbd2 (18. Nc3 Qf7 $11) 18... Bxd2 {We don't allow the Nc4 tempo.} 19. Nxd2 (19. Qxd2 Rd6) 19... Rd6 {Our pieces are centralized and ready to pose some threats.} 20. Ne4 Nf4 21. Qe3 Rd3 22. Qe1 Qf7 23. Qf1 Qg6 24. f3 Rd4 $11 {Again, Black has enough activity in return for the weakened structure.}) (11. e5 Ng4 {We can just focus on attacking the e5-pawn.} 12. Re1 Qd5 13. h3 {1-0 (29) Praveen Kumar,C (2255) -Hossain,E (2522) New Delhi 2008} Ngxe5 {There is no reason not to take.} 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Bf4 Nc6 16. Nd2 Bb4 17. Bxc7 Bxd2 18. Bxb8 O-O 19. Bc7 Bxe1 20. Rxe1 e5 21. Rc1 Rf6 22. Qc8+ Kf7 23. Qb7 Kg6 $11 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gg6]}) (11. Rd1 Nxe4 (11... Bd6 {Also fine}) 12. Qe2 Nc5 13. Be3 d3 14. Qd2 Na4 {Not the only way to play, but the most precise. It also challenges White to play accurately.} 15. b3 Bb4 16. Qc1 O-O 17. bxa4 ({Similar is} 17. a3 Ba5) 17... Rxf3 $1 {The point.} 18. a3 {A pretty tough only move to make. The game should end in a draw.} Ba5 19. gxf3 Ne5 20. Kh1 (20. Qc5 Nxf3+ 21. Kh1 Qxa4 22. Nd2 Nxd2 23. Rxd2 Bxd2 24. Bxd2 Qe4+ 25. Kg1 Qg4+ $11) 20... Qd5 21. Rg1 Nxf3 22. Rg3 Nh4+ 23. Kg1 Nf3+ $11) 11... Bd6 12. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]} (12. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]} O-O 13. Ba3 (13. Bb2 e5 $1 {[%csl Rb2,Gd4,Ge5] The central pawns create a barrier against the white bishop.} 14. Rfc1 (14. Rac1 Nb4 $1 15. Qc4+ Qf7 $13 {[%csl Ra2] a2 is hanging. That's why it's better to put the other rook on c1.}) 14... Rb6 (14... Ne7 $6 {This move misses a tactic.} 15. Bxd4 exd4 16. e5 $16) 15. Qe2 (15. Qa4 $6 Nb4 $1) (15. Qc4+ Kh8) 15... Na5 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gd2c4] Not allowing Nc4 so easily.} 16. Ne1 (16. Rc2 Qe6 17. Rac1 Nd7 {We play this move in order to advance the c-pawn to c5.} 18. Ne1 h6 19. Nd3 c5 $11 {This is a positional draw where neither side can improve. But if White proceeds with Nc4, he can become worse:} 20. Nc4 $2 Nxc4 21. Rxc4 Ra6 $1 22. Ra1 Rb8 $15 {With queenside pressure for Black.}) 16... c5 17. Nd3 Qb5 18. Rc2 Nd7 19. Rac1 Qa6 20. Qf1 h6 $11 {A positional equality has been established. Neither side has a clear plan of how to improve.}) 13... Nh5 $1 {It's important to create immediate threats on the kingside as a means of counterplay.} (13... Rb6 14. Qa4 e5 15. Rac1 $14) 14. g3 (14. Bxd6 cxd6 15. Rfc1 Rb6 $13) 14... Nf6 {This not just a retreat, as we are threatening ...Nxe4.} 15. Kg2 (15. Rae1 Rb6 16. Qa4 e5 17. Bc5 (17. Nc4 Rbb8 $11) 17... Bxc5 18. Qc4+ Qf7 $5 {A direct approach. Black creates a lot of activity.} (18... Kh8 19. Qxc5 Qe8 $13 {1-0 (38) Ralls,R (2097) -Manarin,F (1943) ICCF email 2023}) 19. Qxc5 Nd7 20. Qc2 Nb4 21. Qxc7 Rc6 22. Qa5 Nd3 23. Rd1 Rc2 {Black is very active in return for one pawn and is not afraid to sacrifice another one.} 24. Ng5 (24. Qxa7 h6 25. Qb7 Kh7 {[%csl Gc2,Gd3] Black is two pawns down, but the advanced pieces on c2 and d3 are a constant nuisance for White.} 26. Qd5 Qe7 $44) 24... Qe7 25. f4 {This is a method of creating his own play for White. The extreme complications should end in a draw:} (25. Qd5+ Kh8 26. f4 h6 27. Qe6 Qxe6 28. Nxe6 Re8 $13) 25... N7c5 26. Ndf3 (26. b4 exf4) 26... exf4 27. b4 fxg3 28. hxg3 Qd7 {Sending the queen to the kingside. It's clear that White won't escape without allowing at least a perpetual check.} 29. bxc5 Qg4 30. Rd2 Qxg3+ 31. Kh1 Nf2+ 32. Rdxf2 (32. Rfxf2 $2 Rc1+) 32... Rxf2 33. Rxf2 Qxf2 34. c6 Rxf3 35. Qd5+ Kh8 36. Nxf3 Qxf3+ $11) (15. Ne1 Rb6 16. Qa4 Nb8 (16... Ne5 $11 {Also fine}) 17. Qxd7 Nbxd7 18. Bxd6 cxd6 $11) (15. Rac1 Rb6 16. Qa4 Bxa3 17. Qxa3 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Rxf3 $13) (15. Bb2 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Rxf3 17. Rac1 Rb6 18. Qc4 Ne5 19. Qe2 Be7 20. Rfd1 Rb4 $13) 15... e5 16. Rac1 (16. Bc5 Rbe8 17. Rac1 (17. Qb5 Nd8 18. Qxd7 Nxd7 19. Bxd6 cxd6 {It may look like White is more active, but remember that the protected passed pawn on d4 is a long-term asset for Black, especially in the endgame.} 20. Rac1 a5 21. Rc7 (21. Nc4 Nb7) 21... Nc5 $11) 17... Nd8 $1 18. Qxa7 Qg4 {Black turn with his pieces to the kingside, where he should achieve sufficient compensation for the lost pawn.} 19. h3 Qg6 20. Nh4 Qh5 21. Bxd6 cxd6 22. Nf5 Nf7 $13 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gh5e2] Black has enough kingside counterplay. It is pretty unpleasant in a practical game to be attacked in this way as White.}) (16. Rfc1 Ne7 17. Qc4+ Kh8 18. Bxd6 cxd6 19. Qc7 Rfc8 20. Qxd7 Nxd7 21. Nc4 Rc6 $11) 16... Ne7 {The knight will contribute to Black's kingside tactical chances from g6. In all lines Black gradually generates kingside pressure, often giving up a7. Black benefits in the long-term from the whole ...Nh5-g3-Nf6 idea, because he has a clear-cut path to attack the weakened kingside.} 17. Ne1 (17. Bxd6 cxd6 18. Qc4+ Kh8 19. Qc7 Rfc8 20. Qxd7 Nxd7 21. Nc4 Rc6 $11) (17. Rc2 Ng6 18. Ng1 (18. Ne1 h5 19. Bc1 h4 20. f3 Rf7 21. Qxa7 Qb5 $44 {1/2 (28) Hoeven,D (2649) -Kribben,M (2665) ICCF email 2017}) 18... Qe7 ({Another option is} 18... Rb6 19. Qxa7 Qb5) 19. Bc5 (19. Rxc7 Qxc7 20. Bxd6 Rb6 21. Qc4+ Qxc4 22. Nxc4 Ra8 $1 23. Nxb6 axb6 24. a4 Nxe4 (24... Rc8 25. Re1 Rc2 26. Bb4 h5 $11 {1/2 (27) Kogelov,G (2256) -Gavrijski,D (2209) ICCF email 2022}) 25. Bb4 Nc5 $11) (19. Bxd6 cxd6 20. Rfc1 Rb6 $11) 19... Kh8 $1 (19... Bxc5 $2 20. Qc4+) 20. Rfc1 (20. Bxa7 Ra8) (20. Qxa7 Qe6 $44) 20... Nd7 21. Bxd6 cxd6 22. Qxa7 Qe6 23. Qa6 Nc5 24. Rxc5 Ra8 25. Qb6 Rab8 26. Qa6 Ra8 $11 {˝-˝ (30) Jendrian,M (2477) -Malashenkov,A (2453) ICCF email 2017}) 17... h5 $1 ({Also good is} 17... Ng6 18. f3 h5) 18. h4 (18. Nd3 h4 19. f3 Ng6 20. Rf2 Kh7 $11 {˝-˝ (32) Stalmach,K (2567) -Telepnev,I (2500) ICCF email 2014}) 18... Ng6 19. f3 Ng4 $5 (19... Rb6 20. Qxa7 Ng4 $13 {Also interesting}) 20. fxg4 Nxh4+ $1 21. gxh4 Qxg4+ 22. Kh1 Qxh4+ 23. Kg1 Qg4+ 24. Ng2 (24. Kh1 Qh3+ $11) 24... h4 25. Kh1 Qh3+ 26. Kg1 Qg4 $11) (12. Qe2 {Probably more dangerous for White than for Black.} d3 {A nice way to immediately pose White practical problems with a pawn on the 3rd rank. Black was the one with the initiative in the following game:} 13. Qd1 O-O 14. b3 Nb4 15. Bb2 Bf4 16. Rc1 Nc2 17. g3 Bh6 18. Ne5 Qb5 19. Nec4 {1/2 (19) Jorgensen,B (2339) -Ilyin,P (2404) ICCF email 2018} Qc5 20. Ne5 Qb5 $11) (12. Qd3 O-O 13. h3 (13. Nc4 Ng4 {This time this move becomes serious once the white knight has lost connection and ...Rxf3 ideas appear.} 14. h3 Rxf3 $5 (14... Nge5 {The more simple-minded option is also good.} 15. Ncxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. f4 Bd6 18. Qxd4 Rb4 19. Qxa7 Qb5 $44 {With plenty of compensation for the material.}) 15. Qxf3 Nh2 16. Qd3 Nb4 {Dislodging the queen before recapturing the exchange.} 17. Qb3 Nc6 18. Qd1 Nxf1 19. Qxf1 Ne5 $11)) (12. Re1 Ng4 $1 {A logical choice once White's rook has left the f-file and his kingside is a bit more vulnerable.} 13. h3 Nge5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. f4 Ng6 (15... Qc6 16. Qxc6+ Nxc6 $11) 16. g3 O-O 17. Nf3 e5 18. f5 Qb5 19. Qxb5 Rxb5 20. b3 Ne7 $13 {With a double-edged endgame, probably a bit more promising for Black.}) 12... O-O 13. b4 (13. Qd3 Ng4 $1 {White is a bit slow with his play, so this pawn sacrifice for activity in response is very effective.} 14. h3 Nge5 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Qxd4 Qb5 $1 17. a4 (17. Qc3 Rb6 $13) 17... Qe2 18. Qe3 Qxe3 {˝-˝ (18) Gagunashvili,M (2582) -Doric,D (2464) Rijeka 2010} 19. fxe3 Rfd8 $11) 13... h6 $5 {Very rare move.} (13... e5 14. Ne1 $1 Rb6 15. Qe2 $14) (13... Ng4 $5 {The main move} 14. h3 Nge5 15. Ne1 g5 {Is also very interesting.}) 14. Bb2 (14. Ra2 {[%cal Ga2c2]} e5 15. Ne1 (15. Rc2 Nd8 16. Ne1 Qb5 $1 {We get the ...a5 break in the endgame because of a3-b4.} 17. Qxb5 Rxb5 18. Nd3 a5 19. f3 axb4 20. axb4 Ne6 21. Nc4 Nd7 22. Bd2 Ra8 $11) 15... Rb6 16. Qe2 a5 17. Nc4 Rbb8 18. bxa5 (18. b5 Rxb5 {The whole idea is absed on the fact that we can actually take here.} 19. Nxd6 Rc5 $1 20. Nc4 (20. Nd3 cxd6 21. Nxc5 dxc5 22. Qb5 Rc8 $13 {With a big compensation provided by the two connected passed pawns.}) 20... d3 21. Qxd3 Qxd3 22. Nxd3 Rxc4 23. f3 Rd8 $11) 18... Rb3 $1 19. Rc2 (19. Nd2 Rc3) 19... d3 20. Nxd3 Nd4 21. Qd1 Qa4 $1 (21... Nxc2 $6 22. Qxc2 $14 {[%csl Ga5,Gc4]}) 22. Nxd6 cxd6 23. Rb2 Rxa3 24. Qxa4 Rxa4 25. f3 Rxa5 $11) (14. Qc4 Ng4 $1 15. h3 (15. Bb2 a5) 15... Nge5 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Qxd4 Nd3 $44 18. Qc4 c5 $1) (14. Ne1 Ng4 15. g3 Qe8 $13 {[%cal Ge8h5]}) 14... e5 15. Qc4+ (15. Ne1 Nh5 $1 16. Qa4 (16. Nd3 Nf4 17. Nxf4 Rxf4 $11) (16. g3 Nd8 $1 17. Qe2 Nf6 18. Nd3 a5 {This is the difference between b3 and a3-b4 lines. Here the ...a5 resource can give Black sudden counterplay on the queenside.} 19. bxa5 (19. f4 Nf7 20. Nc4 Rfe8 $11) (19. Nc4 axb4 20. Ncxe5 Bxe5 21. Nxe5 Qb5 22. Qxb5 Rxb5 23. Bxd4 Nxe4 24. axb4 Rxb4 $11) 19... Re8 20. Rfc1 Qa4 21. Nc4 Nc6 22. Qc2 Qb5 23. Rab1 Qa6 24. f4 Nd7 $13 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] It's a very complex position, but Black is well prepared for mass exhchanges in the centre. The bishop on b2 is a bad, blocked piece until White gets rid of the e5-d4 construction.}) 16... Nf4 17. g3 Ne2+ {We can invade into White's camp with this annoying knight, because we will always have ...Nc3 as a bailout.} 18. Kg2 a5 {This connects well with ...Ne2.} 19. Qc2 (19. b5 Qe6 20. Nd3 Na7 $13) 19... Kh8 20. Ndf3 (20. Nc4 Nc3) 20... Nc3 {Everything comes together: After capturing on c3, White loses b4.} 21. Bxc3 dxc3 22. Qxc3 axb4 23. axb4 Bxb4 (23... Rxb4 $11) 24. Qc4 Bxe1 25. Raxe1 Rf6 $11) (15. Rac1 Nd8 $1 {The retreat works, because in the Bxd4 line we will get the ...Bxb4! move after e4-e5.} 16. Bxd4 (16. Nc4 Rb5 $1 17. Qxa7 Ne6 18. Nxd6 Qxd6 19. Qa4 Rfb8 20. Rfe1 c5 $13) (16. Qc4+ Ne6 17. Bxd4 exd4 18. e5 Bxb4 19. axb4 Nd5 20. Nxd4 Rxb4 21. Nxe6 Qxe6 $11) 16... exd4 17. e5 Bxb4 $1 18. axb4 (18. exf6 Bxd2 $11) 18... Nd5 19. Nxd4 Rxb4 20. e6 (20. Rc4 c5 $11) 20... Qe8 21. N2f3 Ra4 22. Qd3 Nxe6 {A couple of Black's pieces look shaky, but Black can hold everything together by tactics.} 23. Rce1 Nef4 24. Qb3 Qg6 25. g3 Rb4 26. Qa2 Nh3+ 27. Kh1 (27. Kg2 Qf7 $11) 27... Qf7 28. Re5 c5 $11 29. Nf5 Nf6) (15. Rfc1 Nd8 {Similar to 15.Rac1.}) 15... Kh8 16. Rac1 Rb6 17. Qc2 (17. Qe2 Rfb8 $5 {Black wants the rook to be protected on b5 after Nc4. ...a5 is the obvious idea hanging in the air now.} 18. Nc4 Rb5 19. Qc2 (19. Nh4 Kh7) 19... Bf8 20. Ncd2 (20. Rfe1 Qe8 $13) (20. Ne1 a5 $1) 20... R5b6 $11) (17. Nh4 {This move initiates a forced sequence.} Qg4 $1 18. g3 Nxe4 19. Nxe4 Qxe4 20. f4 (20. Rce1 Qg4) 20... exf4 21. Rce1 Qh7 22. Qe6 Rf6 {A lot of material comes off the board as a result of these complications:} 23. Qc8+ Rf8 24. Re8 Rb8 25. Rxf8+ Bxf8 26. Qxc7 Qe4 27. Qxf4 (27. Rxf4 Qe1+ $11) 27... Qxf4 28. Rxf4 Kh7 29. Nf3 a5 $11 {And the game reaches a pretty clear draw.}) (17. Ne1 $2 a5 $17) 17... Ne7 $14 {A very attractive possibility.} (17... Rc8 {A viable alternative played in a correspondence game.} 18. Qd3 (18. Nc4 Rb5 19. Qd3 {Transposes}) 18... Rcb8 19. Nc4 Rb5 20. Nh4 a5 21. Nxd6 Qxd6 22. f4 axb4 23. a4 Ra5 24. Qc4 Rb6 25. Nf5 Qd7 26. fxe5 Rxe5 $1 27. Nxh6 Re6 28. Nf5 Rxe4 29. Rcd1 Rb8 $11 {1/2 (33) Czudek,B (2033) -Swiatek,J (2099) FICGS email 2022}) 18. Bxd4 {This is pretty much a bailout for White. The natural 18.Nc4 can end up very tough for him.} (18. Nc4 Ng6 $1 {The big point of 17...Ne7. Black already gets a great and dangerous compensation for the exchange.} 19. Nxb6 axb6 20. Rcd1 (20. Ne1 Nf4 $13 {Based on the fact that g3 is not possible:} 21. g3 $2 Nh3+ 22. Kg2 Ng5 23. f3 Qh3+ 24. Kg1 Ng4 $19) 20... Nf4 $44 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5]}) (18. Ne1 Ng6 19. Nc4 Rc6 $11 {[%cal Gg6f4]}) 18... exd4 19. e5 d3 $1 {The way to make it all work.} 20. Qxd3 (20. Qc4 Nfd5 21. exd6 Rxd6 22. Kh1 Qf5 {White keeps only a slight pressure and Black should be able to neutralize it fully during the course of the next several moves:} 23. Qe4 (23. Rfe1 Ng6 $11) 23... Ra6 $1 24. Qxf5 Rxf5 25. Nc4 Ng6 26. Rcd1 Rf4 27. Ne3 Nxe3 28. fxe3 Rc4 29. Rxd3 c5 30. bxc5 Rxc5 31. Kg1 Ne5 32. Nxe5 Rxe5 $11 {A quite automatic draw despite a pawn advantage for White.}) 20... Bxe5 21. Nxe5 Qxd3 22. Nxd3 Rd8 {White cannot preserve his material edge now and has to go for a material imbalance.} 23. Nc4 Rxd3 24. Nxb6 cxb6 25. Rc7 Ned5 (25... Nf5 26. Rxa7 Nd4 $11 {Also fine}) 26. Rxa7 Kh7 {[%csl Gd5,Gf6]} 27. h3 h5 28. Rb1 Rd4 $11 {The game remain in a state of dynamic balance.} *

